Right?

02:11:20.400 --> 02:11:21.440
“No, they do.”

02:11:21.440 --> 02:11:22.560
That’s wrong.

02:11:22.560 --> 02:11:23.920
It’s a negative.

02:11:23.920 --> 02:11:27.200
We have to say, “No, they don’t.”

02:11:27.200 --> 02:11:29.040
“No, they do not.”

02:11:30.480 --> 02:11:33.440
Okay, and again, we have ‘have’ over here.

02:11:34.560 --> 02:11:34.800
“It…”

02:11:36.640 --> 02:11:38.320
Which one, ‘do’ or ‘does’?

02:11:39.440 --> 02:11:40.960
The answer is ‘does’.

02:11:41.760 --> 02:11:43.520
“Does it have a ball?”

02:11:44.800 --> 02:11:47.520
Again, the answer is negative.

02:11:47.520 --> 02:11:50.240
“No, it…does not.”

02:11:51.040 --> 02:11:54.960
or the contraction, “No, it doesn’t.”

02:11:56.080 --> 02:11:56.880
Okay.

02:11:56.880 --> 02:12:00.640
So that was our practice for asking questions
with ‘have’.

