02:17:40.160 --> 02:17:41.840
Let's get started.

02:17:44.640 --> 02:17:48.000
Let's start with the first usage for the present
simple tense.

02:17:48.640 --> 02:17:50.960
The first usage is pretty easy.

02:17:50.960 --> 02:17:55.600
We use it to talk about facts, truths, and
generalizations.

02:17:55.600 --> 02:17:56.880
Let's look at some examples.

02:17:57.760 --> 02:18:00.000
‘The Sun is bright.’

02:18:00.000 --> 02:18:01.439
Now that's a fact.

02:18:01.439 --> 02:18:02.879
It doesn't change.

02:18:02.880 --> 02:18:05.280
Everybody knows that the Sun is bright.

02:18:05.280 --> 02:18:06.719
It was bright yesterday.

02:18:06.720 --> 02:18:07.600
It's bright today.

02:18:07.600 --> 02:18:09.281
And it will be bright tomorrow.

02:18:09.280 --> 02:18:10.559
That makes it a fact.

02:18:11.680 --> 02:18:12.960
‘Pigs don't fly.’

02:18:13.520 --> 02:18:14.960
That's also a fact.

02:18:14.960 --> 02:18:17.840
Everybody knows that pigs don't fly.

02:18:19.439 --> 02:18:21.679
‘Cats are better than dogs.’

02:18:21.680 --> 02:18:23.600
Now this you may not agree with.

02:18:23.600 --> 02:18:25.360
This is my truth.

02:18:25.359 --> 02:18:29.599
I'm making a generalization about cats and
dogs in this example.

02:18:30.240 --> 02:18:32.800
And finally, ‘It's cold in winter.’

02:18:33.439 --> 02:18:38.319
This really depends on where you live,
but for a lot of people, or let's say for

02:18:38.319 --> 02:18:40.479
most people,
it is cold in the winter,

02:18:41.040 --> 02:18:43.280
so that's the truth for some people.

02:18:44.399 --> 02:18:49.359
Now let's look back and see what verb I used
in the present simple tense.

02:18:50.240 --> 02:18:52.479
For the first sentence, we have ‘is’.

02:18:53.040 --> 02:18:56.720
I use the ‘be’ verb ‘is’ to talk about
the Sun.

02:18:58.000 --> 02:19:03.680
In the next sentence,
I use the negative of do - ‘do not’

02:19:03.680 --> 02:19:09.600
And you'll notice I use the contraction and
put these two words together to make it ‘don't’.

02:19:10.880 --> 02:19:13.440
‘Cats are better than dogs.’

02:19:13.439 --> 02:19:18.719
I use the ‘be’ verb "are" to talk about
cats because ‘cats’ is plural.

02:19:19.359 --> 02:19:22.080
And finally, it's cold and winter.

02:19:22.640 --> 02:19:25.920
Here I use the ‘be’ verb "is" again,

02:19:25.920 --> 02:19:29.680
but I use the contraction to combine ‘it’
and ‘is’

02:19:30.319 --> 02:19:31.280
and made ‘it’s’.

02:19:32.240 --> 02:19:33.840
Let's move on to the next usage.

02:19:35.680 --> 02:19:40.400
We also use the present simple tense to talk
about habits and routines.

02:19:40.399 --> 02:19:43.519
So things and actions that happen regularly.

02:19:43.520 --> 02:19:44.800
Let’s look at the examples.

02:19:45.520 --> 02:19:48.241
‘I always eat lunch at noon.’

02:19:48.240 --> 02:19:53.359
You'll notice I use the adverb ‘always’
because I'm talking about something that I

02:19:53.359 --> 02:19:54.719
do regularly.

02:19:54.720 --> 02:19:55.360
What is that?

02:19:55.920 --> 02:19:57.440
‘Eat lunch at noon.’

02:19:58.000 --> 02:20:00.240
So I use the present simple tense.

02:20:00.240 --> 02:20:02.080
And here I use the verb ‘eat’.

02:20:02.640 --> 02:20:03.680
‘I eat…’

02:20:04.720 --> 02:20:07.920
The second example says you play games every
day.

02:20:08.720 --> 02:20:12.800
Do you see the clue that helps you know that
this is something that happens regularly?

02:20:13.520 --> 02:20:14.960
It's ‘every day’.

02:20:14.960 --> 02:20:18.640
So it's something that happens as a routine
or a habit,

02:20:18.640 --> 02:20:20.640
so you play games.

02:20:20.640 --> 02:20:22.161
The verb here is ‘play’.

02:20:22.800 --> 02:20:23.920
‘You play…’

02:20:25.359 --> 02:20:30.240
The next example says ‘Seth starts work
at 9:00 a.m. daily.’

02:20:30.240 --> 02:20:33.599
Again this is something that happens regularly.

02:20:33.600 --> 02:20:36.480
‘Seth goes to work at 9:00 a.m.’ every
day.

02:20:37.200 --> 02:20:41.439
Now you'll notice I put a blue line under
the ‘s’ in ‘starts’.

02:20:42.160 --> 02:20:44.319
Can you figure out why?

02:20:44.319 --> 02:20:49.840
Well remember that when the subject of a sentence
is ‘he’, ‘she’, or ‘it’,

02:20:49.840 --> 02:20:55.600
we need to add an ‘s’ or ‘es’ to the
end of the verb in the present simple tense.

02:20:56.240 --> 02:20:59.519
Seth is a ‘he’, so we need to add an ‘s’.

02:21:00.160 --> 02:21:03.840
‘Seth starts work at 9:00 a.m. daily.’

02:21:04.560 --> 02:21:09.040
And the last example:
‘They study English every Monday.’

02:21:09.040 --> 02:21:13.200
Again, ‘every Monday’ means that they
do it regularly,

02:21:13.200 --> 02:21:16.160
and that's why we use the present simple tense.

02:21:16.160 --> 02:21:17.280
‘They study…’.

02:21:18.160 --> 02:21:21.920
So as a review,
remember we use the present simple tense

02:21:21.920 --> 02:21:26.319
to talk about habits and routines that happen
regularly.

02:21:26.319 --> 02:21:27.120
Let's move on.

02:21:27.680 --> 02:21:32.320
We also use the present simple tense with
non-continuous verbs.

02:21:32.319 --> 02:21:35.200
These are verbs that we&nbsp;
don't use in the continuous&nbsp;

02:21:35.200 --> 02:21:35.920
form,

02:21:35.920 --> 02:21:37.520
even if they're happening right now.

02:21:38.080 --> 02:21:40.080
They're also called stative verbs.

02:21:40.960 --> 02:21:46.480
These are connected with thoughts, opinions,
feelings, emotions, and our five senses.

02:21:47.040 --> 02:21:48.240
Let's look at these examples.

02:21:48.960 --> 02:21:50.240
‘I love my mom.’

02:21:50.880 --> 02:21:52.800
The verb here is ‘love’.

02:21:52.800 --> 02:21:56.400
That's an emotion, so I use the present simple
tense.

02:21:57.200 --> 02:21:58.639
‘It smells good.’

02:21:59.200 --> 02:22:03.920
‘Smell’ is one of the five senses, so
I use the present simple tense.

02:22:03.920 --> 02:22:09.120
You'll notice I underlined the ‘s’ because
remember the subject is ‘it’.

02:22:10.319 --> 02:22:12.000
‘Kelly feels happy.’

02:22:13.200 --> 02:22:14.880
This is talking about a feeling.

02:22:15.680 --> 02:22:19.600
Again the subject here is ‘Kelly’ which
is a ‘she’,

02:22:19.600 --> 02:22:21.840
so I added an ‘s’ to the verb.

02:22:22.960 --> 02:22:25.520
And finally, ‘They need help.’

02:22:26.240 --> 02:22:30.719
We don't say, ‘they are needing help’
even though it's happening right now.

02:22:30.720 --> 02:22:34.400
‘Need’ is non-continuous, so we say,
‘they need help’,

02:22:34.960 --> 02:22:40.399
so remember you also use the present simple
tense with non-continuous verbs,

02:22:40.399 --> 02:22:45.759
connected with thoughts, opinions, feelings,
emotions, and our five senses.

02:22:45.760 --> 02:22:46.800
Let's move on.

02:22:46.800 --> 02:22:51.920
Speakers occasionally use the present simple
tense to talk about something that will happen

02:22:51.920 --> 02:22:53.120
in the near future.

02:22:53.680 --> 02:22:58.400
Now this can be a little confusing, but we're
not using the future tense,

02:22:58.399 --> 02:23:00.719
we're using the present simple tense.

02:23:00.720 --> 02:23:04.960
It's possible to do that and it's actually
common for people to do that.

02:23:04.960 --> 02:23:08.720
Again, for something that will happen in the
near future.

02:23:08.720 --> 02:23:09.920
Let's look at the examples.

02:23:10.720 --> 02:23:12.880
‘I have class at 6 p.m.’

02:23:13.760 --> 02:23:17.040
‘6 p.m.’ that's pretty soon, so I can
say,

02:23:17.040 --> 02:23:18.319
'I have class.'

02:23:18.319 --> 02:23:20.240
- the present simple tense.

02:23:21.280 --> 02:23:23.920
‘Lisa arrives on Sunday.’

02:23:23.920 --> 02:23:26.960
Again the near future, ‘Sunday’.

02:23:26.960 --> 02:23:29.120
So I use the present simple tense.

02:23:29.920 --> 02:23:36.000
I added an ‘s’ at the end of arrive, because
Lisa, the subject, is a ‘she’.

02:23:37.280 --> 02:23:38.960
‘We start work soon.’

02:23:39.520 --> 02:23:42.480
Again, the near future, ‘soon’,

02:23:42.479 --> 02:23:45.839
so I use the present simple verb ‘start’.

02:23:46.399 --> 02:23:49.439
And finally, ‘My students come tomorrow.’

02:23:50.000 --> 02:23:53.120
This is something that will happen in the
near future,

02:23:53.120 --> 02:23:55.120
so I use the verb ‘come’.

02:23:56.160 --> 02:24:02.000
So remember it is possible, and it is common
to use the present simple tense

02:24:02.000 --> 02:24:05.040
to talk about something that will happen in
the near future.

02:24:05.920 --> 02:24:07.680
Let's go to the next usage.

02:24:07.680 --> 02:24:12.241
Let's talk about a possible negative usage
for the present simple tense,

02:24:12.240 --> 02:24:14.800
and that is ‘do not’ and ‘does not’.

02:24:15.520 --> 02:24:18.560
The first example says,
‘Mike eats bread.’

02:24:19.359 --> 02:24:24.880
I put an ‘s’ at the end of ‘eat’ because
the subject is Mike which is a ‘he’.

02:24:25.920 --> 02:24:28.080
Now that's not a negative statement.

02:24:28.080 --> 02:24:31.519
What happens when I want to turn it into a
negative statement?

02:24:31.520 --> 02:24:35.440
Well I change it like this -
‘Mike doesn't eat bread.’

02:24:36.000 --> 02:24:39.920
So you'll notice that I didn't move the ‘s’
here, okay.

02:24:39.920 --> 02:24:42.000
Instead I added ‘doesn't’.

02:24:43.120 --> 02:24:48.880
I took ‘does’ and ‘not’ and I turned
it into a contraction by combining the two

02:24:48.880 --> 02:24:50.720
and making it ‘doesn't’.

02:24:50.720 --> 02:24:54.320
So if the subject is ‘he’, ‘she’,
or ‘it’,

02:24:54.319 --> 02:24:57.840
we use ‘does not’ or ‘doesn't’ to
make it negative.

02:24:58.960 --> 02:25:00.240
‘You swim well.’

02:25:00.960 --> 02:25:05.520
In this case, I don't need to put an ‘s’
at the end of ‘swim’ because the subject

02:25:05.520 --> 02:25:06.000
is ‘you’.

02:25:06.800 --> 02:25:11.120
If I want to make this sentence negative,
I use ‘don't’.

02:25:11.680 --> 02:25:13.600
‘You don't swim well.’

02:25:14.240 --> 02:25:17.679
I use the contraction for ‘do’ and ‘not’.

02:25:17.680 --> 02:25:20.000
I combine them to make ‘don't’,

02:25:20.640 --> 02:25:24.640
so if the subject is ‘I’, ‘you’, ‘we’,
or ‘they’,

02:25:24.640 --> 02:25:27.360
we use ‘do not’ or ‘don't’.

02:25:28.160 --> 02:25:33.920
So to review ‘do not’ and ‘does not’
or ‘don't’ and ‘doesn't’

02:25:33.920 --> 02:25:37.600
is a possible usage for the negative for present
simple

02:25:37.600 --> 02:25:37.840
tense.

02:25:38.399 --> 02:25:39.359
Let's continue on.

02:25:40.080 --> 02:25:45.120
Now I'll talk about one possible question
form for the present simple tense

02:25:45.120 --> 02:25:48.399
and that is by using ‘do’ or ‘does’.

02:25:48.399 --> 02:25:51.920
So let's look at the example,
‘They live here.’

02:25:51.920 --> 02:25:53.520
That's not a question, right?

02:25:54.160 --> 02:25:55.040
'They live here’

02:25:55.600 --> 02:25:59.281
In order to turn it into a question, it's
really simple.

02:25:59.280 --> 02:26:04.479
All I have to do is add ‘do’ to the beginning
and add a question mark at the end.

02:26:05.120 --> 02:26:06.479
‘Do they live here?’

02:26:07.200 --> 02:26:11.040
So if the subject is ‘I’, ‘you’, ‘we’,
or ‘they’,

02:26:11.680 --> 02:26:14.880
simply add ‘do’ to the beginning of the
question.

02:26:15.840 --> 02:26:18.960
How about this one,
‘He plays soccer.’

02:26:18.960 --> 02:26:24.560
In this statement, the subject is ‘he’
and that's why you should know by now,

02:26:24.560 --> 02:26:27.040
I have an ‘s’ at the end of ‘play’.

02:26:27.840 --> 02:26:32.640
However, to turn this into a question, I add
‘does’ at the beginning.

02:26:33.280 --> 02:26:35.519
‘Does he play soccer?’

02:26:36.080 --> 02:26:41.840
What you'll notice here is that I no longer
have the ‘s’ at the end of play.

02:26:41.840 --> 02:26:45.040
Instead I just used ‘does’ at the beginning,

02:26:45.040 --> 02:26:49.760
so for ‘he’, ‘she’, or ‘it’, put
‘does’ at the beginning,

02:26:49.760 --> 02:26:54.320
and don't worry about putting an ‘s’ or
‘es’ at the end of the verb.

02:26:54.960 --> 02:27:01.120
So to review, one possible way of forming
a question for the present simple tense is

02:27:01.120 --> 02:27:03.599
using ‘do’ or ‘does’ at the beginning.

