The subject of this sentence is ‘his father’.

02:28:35.280 --> 02:28:38.479
What subject pronoun do we use for ‘his
father’?

02:28:39.280 --> 02:28:40.800
The correct answer is ‘he’.

02:28:41.680 --> 02:28:46.960
Remember for ‘he’, ‘she’, ‘it’,
the ‘be’ verb is ‘is’.

02:28:48.960 --> 02:28:52.720
For the negative, we can say ‘isn't’ or
‘is not’.

02:28:53.439 --> 02:28:59.120
And for a contraction, for ‘father’ and
‘is’, we can say, ‘His father's busy.’

02:29:00.640 --> 02:29:07.840
Now I want you to try to find the mistakes
in this sentence.

02:29:08.399 --> 02:29:10.399
‘We isn't good friends.’

02:29:11.120 --> 02:29:12.399
Did you find the mistake?

02:29:15.600 --> 02:29:17.440
This is the mistake.

02:29:17.439 --> 02:29:22.160
The subject is ‘we’ and the ‘be’ verb
is ‘are’.

02:29:22.160 --> 02:29:25.760
Therefore, the correct answer is ‘we are
not’,

02:29:25.760 --> 02:29:29.200
or the contraction, ‘we aren't good friends.’

02:29:33.680 --> 02:29:35.120
The next sentence.

02:29:35.120 --> 02:29:36.399
Can you find the mistake?

02:29:37.439 --> 02:29:39.040
‘Are John a teacher?’

02:29:40.080 --> 02:29:42.559
Think about the subject of this sentence.

02:29:44.160 --> 02:29:45.599
The subject is ‘John’.

02:29:46.960 --> 02:29:49.840
And ‘John’, the subject pronoun is ‘he’.

02:29:50.960 --> 02:29:54.480
Therefore, we don't use ‘are’, we use
‘is’.

02:29:56.640 --> 02:30:00.480
‘Is John a teacher?’

02:30:00.479 --> 02:30:01.599
‘Is John a teacher?’

02:30:01.600 --> 02:30:04.640
And finally, ‘It am a puppy.’

02:30:05.240 --> 02:30:07.840
hmm
This one is a big mistake.

02:30:08.479 --> 02:30:10.160
The subject here is ‘it’.

02:30:10.960 --> 02:30:13.120
What ‘be’ verb do we use for ‘it’?

02:30:13.840 --> 02:30:15.840
The correct answer is ‘is’.

02:30:16.640 --> 02:30:21.760
So we don't say, ‘It am a puppy,’ we say,
‘It is a puppy.’

02:30:22.720 --> 02:30:23.760
Great job guys.

02:30:23.760 --> 02:30:25.840
Let's move on to the next checkup.

02:30:25.840 --> 02:30:30.640
For the next checkup, I want you to think
of some other verbs in the present simple

02:30:30.640 --> 02:30:30.960
tense.

02:30:31.600 --> 02:30:33.760
Take a look at the first sentence.

02:30:33.760 --> 02:30:38.240
‘He __ blank __ …’, I want you to think
of the verb, ‘like his dinner’.

02:30:39.040 --> 02:30:43.439
What do we do to the verb when the subject
is ‘he’, ‘she’, or ‘it’?

02:30:44.160 --> 02:30:45.840
Remember we add an ‘s’.

02:30:46.720 --> 02:30:50.241
‘He likes his dinner.’

02:30:50.960 --> 02:30:55.120
For the negative, you can also say, ‘He
doesn't like his dinner.’

02:30:56.240 --> 02:31:01.120
The next sentence says, ‘My students __
blank __…’, I want you to think of ‘need’,

02:31:01.760 --> 02:31:02.160
‘…books’.

02:31:03.760 --> 02:31:06.880
What is the subject pronoun for ‘my students’?

02:31:07.600 --> 02:31:09.281
The correct answer is ‘they’.

02:31:10.319 --> 02:31:15.840
If the subject is ‘I’, ‘you’, ‘we’,
or ‘they’, in the present simple tense,

02:31:15.840 --> 02:31:19.120
we don't change the verb,
we keep it as is.

02:31:19.760 --> 02:31:24.640
So the correct answer is,
‘My students need books.’

02:31:25.359 --> 02:31:30.160
Now for the negative, you can say,
‘My students don't need books.’

02:31:31.600 --> 02:31:35.600
The next sentence says,
‘I __ blank __…’, think of the verb,

02:31:35.600 --> 02:31:37.440
‘…live in London.’

02:31:38.800 --> 02:31:39.920
What do we do here?

02:31:40.880 --> 02:31:46.080
Again the subject is ‘I’, therefore we
don't change the verb.

02:31:46.080 --> 02:31:49.840
The correct answer is,
‘I live in London.’

02:31:50.640 --> 02:31:51.600
What's the negative?

02:31:52.240 --> 02:31:54.319
‘I don't live in London.’

02:31:55.520 --> 02:32:00.480
For the next part, I would like for you to
try to find the mistake in the sentence.

02:32:01.120 --> 02:32:03.200
‘He doesn't likes math.’

02:32:04.080 --> 02:32:05.359
What's the error here?

02:32:06.319 --> 02:32:07.920
Well this is a negative.

02:32:08.640 --> 02:32:11.201
‘He doesn't…’, that's correct.

02:32:11.200 --> 02:32:17.439
However, we do not add an ‘s’ when we
have ‘doesn't’ in front of ‘it’.

02:32:18.800 --> 02:32:20.800
‘Do he eat candy?’

02:32:21.680 --> 02:32:24.080
Here we have a question.

02:32:24.080 --> 02:32:26.800
The subject of the sentence is ‘he’.

02:32:27.680 --> 02:32:33.281
For ‘he’, ‘she’, ‘it’, when we're
making a sentence in the present simple tense,

02:32:33.280 --> 02:32:36.800
we use ‘does’ not ‘do’.

02:32:37.520 --> 02:32:40.640
So the correct answer is,
‘Does he eat candy?’

02:32:41.920 --> 02:32:45.840
And finally, ‘Sam is play computer games.’

02:32:46.560 --> 02:32:50.960
There are two present simple verbs here and
we can't have that,

02:32:50.960 --> 02:32:56.880
so the correct way to fix this sentence is
to get rid of the ‘is’.

02:32:56.880 --> 02:33:04.319
So take that out and say,
‘Sam plays computer games.’

02:33:04.319 --> 02:33:08.639
Add an ‘s’ because the subject is ‘Sam’
which is a ‘he’.

02:33:09.600 --> 02:33:10.480
Great job!

02:33:10.479 --> 02:33:12.639
Let's move on to the next practice.

02:33:12.640 --> 02:33:16.241
For this next practice, we're taking a look
at routines.

02:33:16.240 --> 02:33:22.160
Remember the present simple tense can be used
to describe events that happen regularly.

02:33:22.160 --> 02:33:24.240
Let's take a look at the first sentence,

02:33:24.960 --> 02:33:28.080
‘We _ blank _ the bus every day.’

02:33:28.080 --> 02:33:30.240
And I want you to use the verb ‘take’.

02:33:31.120 --> 02:33:35.840
Here we see the clue word ‘every day’
which shows that this is a routine.

02:33:36.800 --> 02:33:39.120
The subject of the sentence is ‘we’.

02:33:40.080 --> 02:33:41.920
In the present simple tense,

02:33:41.920 --> 02:33:47.040
remember if the subject is ‘I’, ‘you’,
‘we’, or ‘they’,

02:33:47.040 --> 02:33:48.880
we do not change the verb.

02:33:49.439 --> 02:33:55.439
Therefore the correct answer is,
‘We take the bus every day.’

02:33:56.640 --> 02:34:02.241
In the second sentence it says,
‘He _ blank _ to school every morning.’

02:34:02.240 --> 02:34:03.760
Again a routine.

02:34:05.200 --> 02:34:06.639
The subject here is ‘he’.

02:34:07.520 --> 02:34:11.041
What do we do if the subject is ‘he’,
‘she’, or ‘it’?

02:34:11.680 --> 02:34:14.720
We add ‘s’ or ‘es’ to the verb.

02:34:15.439 --> 02:34:20.639
In this example, the verb is ‘go’, so
we have to add ‘es’.

02:34:21.200 --> 02:34:25.120
‘He goes to school every morning.’

02:34:26.319 --> 02:34:31.920
In the next sentence, it says,
‘Lizzy not play (in parenthesis) tennis.’

02:34:32.560 --> 02:34:35.440
Here I want you to think about the negative
form.

02:34:36.560 --> 02:34:38.400
Lizzy is a ‘she’.

02:34:38.399 --> 02:34:43.040
The subject pronoun is ‘she’ so what do
we do for the negative?

02:34:43.680 --> 02:34:51.920
We say ‘does not’ or the contraction ‘doesn't
play tennis’.

02:34:51.920 --> 02:34:56.080
We do not add an ‘s’ or ‘es’ to the
end of the verb.

02:34:56.640 --> 02:34:59.840
Instead we say ‘doesn't’ or ‘does not’.

02:35:00.880 --> 02:35:04.560
Now I want you to find a mistake in the next
sentence.

02:35:05.200 --> 02:35:08.000
‘They watches TV at night.’

02:35:08.800 --> 02:35:11.840
Can you figure out what's wrong with the sentence?

02:35:12.640 --> 02:35:14.161
The subject is ‘they’.

02:35:15.359 --> 02:35:19.280
Therefore, remember, we do not change the
verb.

02:35:20.560 --> 02:35:22.161
We say ‘watch’.

02:35:22.720 --> 02:35:25.840
‘They watch TV at night’.

02:35:26.800 --> 02:35:32.400
In the next sentence, or question, it says,
‘Does he plays soccer every week?’

02:35:33.520 --> 02:35:35.600
The subject of the sentence is ‘he’.

02:35:36.399 --> 02:35:40.559
To make a sentence, putting ‘does’ at
the beginning is okay,

02:35:41.600 --> 02:35:45.840
However, we don't put an ‘s’ at the end
of ‘play’.

02:35:46.720 --> 02:35:49.680
Therefore, the correct answer is to simply
say,

02:35:50.240 --> 02:35:53.840
‘Does he play soccer every week?’

02:35:54.560 --> 02:35:58.800
And finally, ‘He always forget his book.’

02:35:59.920 --> 02:36:02.319
In this case, the subject is ‘he’.

02:36:03.280 --> 02:36:10.559
Remember, again, for he/she/it we add 's'
or 'es' to the end of the verb.

02:36:10.560 --> 02:36:12.400
What's the verb in the sentence?

02:36:13.040 --> 02:36:14.000
It's ‘forget’.

02:36:14.960 --> 02:36:21.840
Therefore we have to say,
‘He always forgets his book.’

02:36:22.399 --> 02:36:23.280
Great job.

02:36:23.280 --> 02:36:25.599
Let's move on to the next practice.

02:36:25.600 --> 02:36:31.281
In this checkup, we'll take a look at how
the present simple tense can be used to describe

02:36:31.280 --> 02:36:32.240
future events.

02:36:33.280 --> 02:36:35.599
Take a look at the first sentence.

02:36:35.600 --> 02:36:38.720
It says, ‘The airplane _ blank _ tonight.’

02:36:39.439 --> 02:36:41.599
And we're looking at the verb ‘leave’.

02:36:42.560 --> 02:36:44.960
What is the subject of the sentence?

02:36:45.600 --> 02:36:47.840
The correct answer is ‘airplane’.

02:36:48.720 --> 02:36:51.680
What subject pronoun do we use for ‘airplane’?

02:36:52.479 --> 02:36:53.120
It's ‘it’.

02:36:54.080 --> 02:36:59.840
Remember in the present simple tense, for
‘he’, ‘she’, ‘it’, we add an ‘s’

02:36:59.840 --> 02:37:01.600
or ‘es’ to the verb.

02:37:02.319 --> 02:37:06.000
The verb here is ‘leave’ so we simply
add an ‘s’.

02:37:06.720 --> 02:37:11.360
The correct answer is,
‘The airplane leaves tonight.’

02:37:12.640 --> 02:37:18.161
In the second sentence, it says,
‘Does the movie _blank_ soon?’

02:37:18.160 --> 02:37:20.240
And we're using the verb ‘start’.

02:37:21.359 --> 02:37:23.679
What is the subject of this sentence?

02:37:24.399 --> 02:37:25.519
It’s ‘movie’.

02:37:26.319 --> 02:37:29.359
And what subject pronoun do we use for movie?

02:37:29.920 --> 02:37:30.640
It’s ‘it’.

02:37:31.359 --> 02:37:35.200
So it's like saying, ‘Does it _ blank _
soon?’

02:37:35.760 --> 02:37:42.240
Well this is a question, so we already have
the correct word in the front - ‘does’.

02:37:42.880 --> 02:37:47.760
For he/she/it, when we're asking a question,
we use ‘does’.

02:37:48.720 --> 02:37:54.241
Now all we have to do is use the same verb
in its base form,

02:37:54.800 --> 02:37:57.760
so ‘Does the movie start soon?’

02:37:57.760 --> 02:38:01.281
We do not add an ‘s’ or ‘es’ here.

02:38:02.399 --> 02:38:06.000
Finally, it says,
‘Viki _ blank _ tomorrow.’

02:38:06.800 --> 02:38:09.520
The subject of the sentence is ‘Vicki’.

02:38:10.399 --> 02:38:14.160
‘Vicki’ is a girl so the subject pronoun
is ‘she’.

02:38:15.120 --> 02:38:19.439
You'll remember now that for… in this case,
we put ‘works’.

02:38:20.080 --> 02:38:23.200
w-o-r-k-s ‘works’.

02:38:23.920 --> 02:38:25.680
‘Vicki works tomorrow.’

02:38:26.640 --> 02:38:29.760
Now let's find the mistakes in the sentence
below.

02:38:30.560 --> 02:38:33.600
‘He do leave at 3:30 p.m.’

02:38:34.319 --> 02:38:36.160
Actually there's only one mistake.

02:38:36.720 --> 02:38:37.520
Can you find it?

02:38:38.800 --> 02:38:42.000
‘He do leave at 3:30 p.m.’

02:38:43.359 --> 02:38:46.639
We do not need the ‘do’ here.

02:38:46.640 --> 02:38:50.880
We only use ‘do’ in a question or in the
negative form.

02:38:51.520 --> 02:38:55.041
But also the subject is ‘he’, so we would
use ‘does’.

02:38:55.840 --> 02:38:58.000
Either way we don't need this here.

02:38:58.720 --> 02:39:02.640
Well now we have the verb ‘leave’ with
the subject ‘he’.

02:39:03.600 --> 02:39:04.560
Do you know what to do?

02:39:05.600 --> 02:39:10.080
We simply change this to ‘leaves’.

02:39:10.080 --> 02:39:12.319
Just like we did in the first sentence.

02:39:12.880 --> 02:39:15.680
‘He leaves at 3:30 p.m.’

02:39:16.880 --> 02:39:21.040
In the next sentence,
‘They don't start school today.’

02:39:21.840 --> 02:39:24.080
We have a negative sentence.

02:39:24.080 --> 02:39:26.640
‘They don't…’, that's correct.

02:39:27.359 --> 02:39:29.200
‘…do not’ is correct.

02:39:29.200 --> 02:39:30.639
For subject pronoun ‘they’.

02:39:31.439 --> 02:39:36.559
However, in the negative form, we don't have
to change the main verb at all.

02:39:37.680 --> 02:39:43.520
Therefore, all we will do is say,
‘They don't start school today.’

02:39:43.520 --> 02:39:44.320
No ‘s’.

02:39:45.760 --> 02:39:48.800
Finally, ‘Does we eat at noon?’

02:39:49.760 --> 02:39:50.480
Take a look.

02:39:50.479 --> 02:39:54.639
What is the subject or subject pronoun in
the sentence?

02:39:55.359 --> 02:39:56.960
The correct answer is ‘we’.

02:39:58.560 --> 02:40:00.480
Think about the question form.

02:40:01.120 --> 02:40:06.319
Do we say ‘do’ or ‘does’ in the question
form for the subject pronoun ‘we’?

02:40:07.439 --> 02:40:09.839
The correct answer is ‘do’.

02:40:09.840 --> 02:40:11.120
We say ‘do’.

02:40:12.240 --> 02:40:16.160
So the correct way to say this sentence or
question is,

02:40:16.160 --> 02:40:18.000
‘Do we eat at noon?’

