02:40:49.680 --> 02:40:51.520
Hi, everybody.
I'm Esther.

02:40:51.520 --> 02:40:56.480
I'm so excited to be teaching you the&nbsp;
present continuous tense in this video.

02:40:57.120 --> 02:41:01.040
This tense is used to describe:
an action that's happening right now,

02:41:01.680 --> 02:41:06.320
a longer action in progress ,
and something happening in the near future.

02:41:06.880 --> 02:41:10.240
There's a lot to learn, but don't worry I'll
guide you through it.

02:41:10.240 --> 02:41:11.200
Let's get started.

02:41:14.640 --> 02:41:20.400
The present continuous tense is used to talk&nbsp;
about actions that are happening right now.

02:41:20.399 --> 02:41:21.279
For example,

02:41:21.279 --> 02:41:25.279
‘I'm teaching English’ and
‘You are studying English.’

02:41:25.920 --> 02:41:28.000
Let's take a look at some more examples.

02:41:28.640 --> 02:41:32.400
The first sentence says, ‘He is watching a movie’.

02:41:33.040 --> 02:41:36.240
We start with the subject and a ‘be’ verb.

02:41:36.800 --> 02:41:38.960
In this case, the subject is ‘he’.

02:41:39.840 --> 02:41:43.840
For ‘he’ / ‘she’ and ‘it’,&nbsp;
we use the ‘be’ verb ‘is’.

02:41:44.800 --> 02:41:49.520
Then you'll notice I added an ‘-ing’&nbsp;
to the end of the verb ‘watch’.

02:41:50.319 --> 02:41:52.240
‘He is watching a movie.’

02:41:53.279 --> 02:41:57.359
The next sentence says,
‘Tim is playing a computer game.’

02:41:57.359 --> 02:41:59.040
He's doing that right now.

02:42:00.160 --> 02:42:05.680
Tim is a ‘he’, therefore, again&nbsp;
we use the ‘be’ verb ‘is’.

02:42:06.319 --> 02:42:12.319
And again you'll notice I added&nbsp;
‘-ing’ to the end of the verb.

02:42:12.319 --> 02:42:13.840
The next sentence says,

02:42:13.840 --> 02:42:16.319
‘The machine is making a noise.’

02:42:17.200 --> 02:42:20.240
Now pay attention to the subject, ‘the machine’.

02:42:21.120 --> 02:42:22.880
What is the proper pronoun?

02:42:23.520 --> 02:42:28.241
The answer is ‘it’, therefore&nbsp;
we use the ‘be’ verb ‘is’.

02:42:28.880 --> 02:42:31.359
‘The machine is making a noise.’

02:42:32.240 --> 02:42:38.559
We can also say, ‘It is making a noise’.
Or the contraction, ‘It's making a noise’.

02:42:39.359 --> 02:42:43.040
And finally, ‘Tom and Ben are speaking English’.

02:42:43.600 --> 02:42:47.040
In this case, you'll notice&nbsp;
that we use the ‘be’ verb ‘are’.

02:42:47.840 --> 02:42:49.120
Can you figure out why?

02:42:50.240 --> 02:42:55.599
That's because Tom and Ben -
the subject pronoun for these two is ‘they’.

02:42:56.479 --> 02:42:58.319
‘They are speaking English.’

02:42:59.439 --> 02:43:01.439
Let's move on to the next usage.

02:43:02.800 --> 02:43:08.480
The present continuous tense is also used
to describe a longer action in progress.

02:43:09.040 --> 02:43:12.399
Even though you might not be&nbsp;
doing the action right now.

02:43:12.960 --> 02:43:14.880
Let's take a look at some examples.

02:43:15.600 --> 02:43:16.960
The first sentence says,

02:43:16.960 --> 02:43:19.760
‘I'm reading an interesting book these days.’

02:43:20.560 --> 02:43:24.880
In this case, the subject is&nbsp;
‘I’, so the ‘be’ verb is ‘am’.

02:43:25.840 --> 02:43:31.120
In this example, we use the contraction&nbsp;
‘I'm’ by putting ‘I’ and ‘am’ together.

02:43:31.760 --> 02:43:36.320
Again, you'll notice there's&nbsp;
an ‘-ing’ after the verb.

02:43:36.319 --> 02:43:38.000
The next sentence says,

02:43:38.000 --> 02:43:40.960
‘You are studying to become an English teacher.’

02:43:41.680 --> 02:43:43.280
The subject here is ‘you’,

02:43:44.080 --> 02:43:46.399
therefore the ‘be’ verb is ‘are’.

02:43:47.840 --> 02:43:51.680
Next, ‘Steven is preparing for the IELTS exam.’

02:43:52.800 --> 02:43:56.080
The subject here is ‘Steven’ which is a ‘he’,

02:43:56.800 --> 02:43:59.200
therefore we use the ‘be’ verb ‘is’.

02:44:00.399 --> 02:44:04.639
And finally,
‘John and June are working at a company.’

02:44:05.359 --> 02:44:10.479
If you look at the subject ‘John and June’,
the pronoun for that is ‘they’.

02:44:11.279 --> 02:44:13.359
That's why we use the ‘be’ verb ‘are’.

02:44:14.160 --> 02:44:16.240
‘They are working at a company.’

02:44:17.120 --> 02:44:18.960
Let's move on to the next usage.

02:44:19.520 --> 02:44:24.560
The present continuous is also used&nbsp;
to talk about near future plans.

02:44:24.560 --> 02:44:25.440
Let's take a look.

02:44:26.399 --> 02:44:28.479
‘She is meeting some friends tonight.’

02:44:29.200 --> 02:44:32.000
That's going to happen in the near future.

02:44:32.000 --> 02:44:36.080
You'll notice that we have 'she', so the ‘be’
verb is ‘is’.

02:44:36.080 --> 02:44:40.399
And then we added an ‘-ing’ to the end
of the verb ‘meet’.

02:44:41.200 --> 02:44:45.840
The next example says,
‘We are going on vacation in July.’

02:44:46.399 --> 02:44:50.719
The subject here is ‘we’, therefore we
use the ‘be’ verb ‘are’.

02:44:51.359 --> 02:44:57.200
We can also use a contraction and say,
‘We're going on vacation in July.’

02:44:57.200 --> 02:44:59.840
Again, another near future plan.

02:45:00.640 --> 02:45:02.241
The next example says,

02:45:02.240 --> 02:45:04.639
‘David is learning to drive tomorrow.’

02:45:05.279 --> 02:45:07.120
‘tomorrow’ is the near future.

02:45:07.920 --> 02:45:09.440
‘David’ is the subject.

02:45:10.319 --> 02:45:14.240
‘David’ is a ‘he’, so we use ‘is’.

02:45:14.240 --> 02:45:18.719
And lastly,
‘Vicki and I are teaching English next week.’

02:45:19.680 --> 02:45:23.680
‘Vicky and I’…
If we think about the subject pronoun is ‘we’.

02:45:24.399 --> 02:45:28.000
That's why we used ‘are’.
‘We are teaching.’

02:45:29.040 --> 02:45:29.840
Let's move on.

02:45:31.200 --> 02:45:35.679
Now let's talk about the negative&nbsp;
form of the present continuous tense.

02:45:36.240 --> 02:45:37.760
I have some examples here.

02:45:38.479 --> 02:45:44.240
These two examples are for actions that are
happening right now, or longer actions.

02:45:45.120 --> 02:45:48.160
These last two are for near future plans.

02:45:48.800 --> 02:45:49.680
Let's take a look.

02:45:50.319 --> 02:45:53.599
The first sentence says,
‘I am not having fun.’

02:45:54.399 --> 02:45:57.759
Now that's not true for me because I am having
fun,

02:45:57.760 --> 02:46:00.800
but in this example I am not having fun.

02:46:01.520 --> 02:46:07.121
You'll notice that the word ‘not’ goes&nbsp;
between the ‘be’ verb and the ‘verb -ing’.

02:46:08.080 --> 02:46:12.479
In the second example it says,
‘Jane isn't doing her homework.’

02:46:13.200 --> 02:46:17.599
Here we use the contraction ‘isn't’ for ‘is not’,

02:46:17.600 --> 02:46:23.840
so just like the first sentence, we put ‘not’
between ‘is’ and ‘verb -ing’.

02:46:24.560 --> 02:46:28.081
The next sentence says,
‘You're not seeing him tonight.’

02:46:29.120 --> 02:46:31.680
Here we have a contraction for ‘you are’.

02:46:32.319 --> 02:46:34.719
‘You're not seeing him tonight.’

02:46:35.439 --> 02:46:39.040
And finally,
‘We are not running tomorrow morning.’

02:46:39.680 --> 02:46:43.920
Here we have the subject ‘we’, therefore,
we use the ‘be’ verb ‘are’.

02:46:44.880 --> 02:46:49.040
Don’t forget to add a ‘not’ after that
to make it negative.

02:46:49.600 --> 02:46:50.800
Let's move on.

02:46:50.800 --> 02:46:56.240
Now let's talk about how to form ‘be’ verb&nbsp;
questions in the present continuous tense.

02:46:57.040 --> 02:46:58.960
The first example here says,

02:46:58.960 --> 02:47:02.319
‘Is he waiting for you?’

02:47:02.319 --> 02:47:03.040
or ‘Is he waiting for you?’

02:47:03.040 --> 02:47:04.560
We start with the ‘be’ verb.

02:47:05.359 --> 02:47:07.439
Take a look at the subject though.

02:47:07.439 --> 02:47:11.439
The subject is ‘he’ and that's why we
start with the ‘be’ verb ‘is’.

02:47:12.000 --> 02:47:13.200
‘Is he waiting for you?’

02:47:14.080 --> 02:47:18.399
You can answer, ‘Yes, he is.’ or ‘No he isn't.’

02:47:19.279 --> 02:47:20.960
The second sentence says,

02:47:20.960 --> 02:47:22.319
‘Are you coming to class?’

02:47:23.439 --> 02:47:27.359
The subject here is ‘you’ and&nbsp;
that's why we start with ‘are’.

02:47:27.920 --> 02:47:29.279
‘Are you coming to class?’

02:47:29.920 --> 02:47:33.840
You can answer, ‘Yes I am.’ or ‘No, I'm not.’

02:47:35.040 --> 02:47:39.279
The next question says,
‘Is he preparing to study in Canada?’

02:47:40.000 --> 02:47:43.359
The subject is ‘he’, and so we start with ‘is’.

02:47:44.000 --> 02:47:49.600
The answer can be, ‘Yes, he is.’
or it can also be ‘No, he isn't.’

02:47:50.720 --> 02:47:54.560
Finally the last question says,
‘Are they going out tonight?’

02:47:55.359 --> 02:47:59.359
The subject here is ‘they’,
and so we start with ‘are’.

02:48:00.240 --> 02:48:05.279
The answer can be ‘Yes, they are.’
or ‘No, they aren't.’

02:48:06.080 --> 02:48:07.359
Let's move on.

02:48:07.359 --> 02:48:12.639
Now let's talk about the WH question&nbsp;
form for the present continuous tense.

02:48:13.200 --> 02:48:15.279
I have some examples here

02:48:15.279 --> 02:48:19.279
and you'll notice that we start with the
WH questions:

02:48:19.279 --> 02:48:23.920
what, where, when, who, why, and how.

02:48:24.800 --> 02:48:25.680
What comes after?

02:48:26.240 --> 02:48:32.800
You'll notice it's the ‘be’ verbs: ‘are’,
‘is’, and if the subject is ‘I’, ‘am’.

02:48:33.600 --> 02:48:38.960
So after that you have the subject and then
the verb -ing.

02:48:39.760 --> 02:48:41.840
Let's take a look at the first sentence.

02:48:42.560 --> 02:48:44.081
‘What are you doing?’

02:48:44.080 --> 02:48:46.240
I'm asking about right now.

02:48:46.240 --> 02:48:48.559
For example, ‘I'm teaching English.’

02:48:49.840 --> 02:48:53.360
‘Where are you going?’
‘I'm going to the store.’

02:48:54.800 --> 02:48:58.560
‘When is it starting?’
‘It's starting at 3.’

02:48:59.200 --> 02:49:03.519
I can be talking about a movie a show anything
can be ‘it’.

02:49:04.880 --> 02:49:08.319
‘Who is she talking to?’
‘She's talking to Bob.’

02:49:09.840 --> 02:49:14.080
‘Why is she crying?’
‘She's crying because she's sad.’

02:49:15.040 --> 02:49:19.120
And finally, ‘How is it going?’
‘It's going well.’

02:49:20.240 --> 02:49:23.599
For this checkup of the present continuous tense,

02:49:23.600 --> 02:49:29.600
we'll look at how this tense can be used to&nbsp;
describe an action that's happening right now.

02:49:29.600 --> 02:49:31.520
Let's take a look at the first sentence.

02:49:32.160 --> 02:49:34.720
‘You -blank- learning English.’

02:49:35.359 --> 02:49:40.000
Remember for this tense, we start&nbsp;
with the subject and the ‘be’ verb

02:49:40.000 --> 02:49:41.920
and then the verb ‘-ing’.

02:49:42.640 --> 02:49:47.120
We already have the verb ‘-ing’ here,
so we need the ‘be’ verb.

02:49:47.840 --> 02:49:50.319
The subject in the first sentence is ‘you’.

02:49:51.200 --> 02:49:55.359
For ‘you’, ‘we’, and ‘they’,&nbsp;
we use the ‘be’ verb - ‘are’,

02:49:55.920 --> 02:49:57.440
so the correct answer is,

02:49:58.080 --> 02:50:01.040
‘You are learning English’ right now.

02:50:02.240 --> 02:50:03.760
The next sentence says,

02:50:03.760 --> 02:50:06.880
‘She _blank_ not watching TV.’

02:50:07.600 --> 02:50:11.920
This is the negative form of&nbsp;
the present continuous tense.

02:50:11.920 --> 02:50:15.680
We have the word ‘not’ before the verb ‘-ing’,

02:50:16.399 --> 02:50:18.879
However, we're missing the ‘be’ verb again.

02:50:19.600 --> 02:50:22.960
What is the be verb to use&nbsp;
if the subject is ‘she’?

02:50:23.760 --> 02:50:25.840
the correct answer is ‘is’.

02:50:27.200 --> 02:50:29.760
‘She is not watching TV.’

02:50:31.439 --> 02:50:34.719
This one says, ‘I _blank_ studying now.’

02:50:35.520 --> 02:50:37.201
The subject here is ‘I’.

02:50:38.080 --> 02:50:42.000
Again think of the ‘be’ verb that goes
before the subject ‘I’.

02:50:43.120 --> 02:50:44.960
The ‘be’ verb is ‘am’.

02:50:46.080 --> 02:50:48.000
‘I am studying now.’

02:50:48.720 --> 02:50:53.200
We can also use a contraction and say,
‘I'm studying now’

02:50:54.160 --> 02:50:57.599
If we wanted to turn this into the negative form,

02:50:57.600 --> 02:51:00.960
we can also say, ‘I'm not studying now.’

02:51:02.160 --> 02:51:06.000
Now, take a look at the next&nbsp;
sentence and find the mistake.

02:51:06.880 --> 02:51:09.520
‘Layla is watch a movie.’

02:51:10.479 --> 02:51:15.200
Here we have the subject and the subject pronoun
for Layla would be ‘she’.

02:51:16.080 --> 02:51:18.640
We have the correct ‘be’ verb - ‘is’,

02:51:19.359 --> 02:51:25.120
However, you'll notice we forgot&nbsp;
the ‘-ing’ at the end of the verb.

02:51:25.760 --> 02:51:28.320
We need to say, ‘watching’.

02:51:29.279 --> 02:51:31.840
‘Layla is watching a movie.’

02:51:33.040 --> 02:51:34.479
The next sentence says,

02:51:34.479 --> 02:51:36.479
‘They playing soccer now.’

02:51:37.359 --> 02:51:38.160
What's missing?

02:51:39.120 --> 02:51:43.279
If you got it the correct answer is we need
the ‘be’ verb – ‘are’

02:51:43.920 --> 02:51:45.840
because the subject is ‘they’.

02:51:46.800 --> 02:51:49.360
‘They are playing soccer now.’

02:51:50.560 --> 02:51:53.040
And finally,
‘What do you do?’

02:51:54.240 --> 02:51:57.679
If you want to ask somebody&nbsp;
what they're doing right now,

02:51:58.240 --> 02:52:08.880
you say, 'what’... and the ‘be’ verb – ‘are...
you.. doing?’

02:52:09.760 --> 02:52:11.200
‘What are you doing?’

02:52:12.319 --> 02:52:13.840
Let's move on to the next practice.

02:52:14.560 --> 02:52:18.480
For this checkup we'll talk about the present
continuous tense

02:52:18.479 --> 02:52:24.399
and how it can be used to describe an action
that started in the past and continues today.

02:52:24.399 --> 02:52:25.839
It's a longer action.

02:52:26.399 --> 02:52:28.399
Let's take a look at the first sentence.

02:52:29.040 --> 02:52:32.640
‘He _blank_ studying economics.’

02:52:32.640 --> 02:52:38.480
Remember for this tense, we take the&nbsp;
subject, a ‘be’ verb, and then verb ‘-ing’.

02:52:39.279 --> 02:52:42.800
Here we already have the verb ‘-ing’, ‘studying’.

02:52:43.359 --> 02:52:44.960
So what are we missing?

02:52:44.960 --> 02:52:45.840
The ‘be’ verb.

02:52:46.399 --> 02:52:50.160
The correct ‘be’ verb for&nbsp;
the subject ‘he’ is ‘is’.

02:52:51.120 --> 02:52:54.080
So, ‘He is studying economics.’

02:52:54.880 --> 02:52:58.640
The next sentence says,
‘They're _blank_ for the fight.’

02:52:59.359 --> 02:53:01.679
The verb we want to use is ‘train’.

02:53:02.560 --> 02:53:05.680
Now we already have the 'be' verb here.

02:53:05.680 --> 02:53:09.840
It's in the contraction ‘there’&nbsp;
because it's ‘they are’.

02:53:10.560 --> 02:53:14.000
All we have to do now is add ‘-ing’ to the verb.

02:53:14.720 --> 02:53:20.080
‘They're training for the fight these days.’

02:53:20.800 --> 02:53:24.400
And ‘We _blank_ teaching at the school.’

02:53:25.200 --> 02:53:27.519
Again we're missing the ‘be’ verb.

02:53:28.080 --> 02:53:29.920
What is the ‘be’ verb for ‘we’?

02:53:31.040 --> 02:53:33.600
The correct answer is ‘are’.

02:53:34.720 --> 02:53:37.840
‘We are teaching at the school.’

02:53:38.399 --> 02:53:42.160
Now let's look for the&nbsp;
mistakes in the next sentence.

02:53:43.120 --> 02:53:46.240
‘Ben is study to become a doctor.’

02:53:47.279 --> 02:53:48.559
Can you find the error?

02:53:49.760 --> 02:53:54.160
Well we have the subject
and we have the proper ‘be verb’.

02:53:54.160 --> 02:53:58.800
What we're missing is the ‘-ing’
at the end of ‘study’.

02:54:00.160 --> 02:54:06.160
The correct answer is,
‘Ben is studying to become a doctor’.

02:54:06.160 --> 02:54:07.840
Let's look at the next sentence.

02:54:08.720 --> 02:54:15.120
‘I don't reading that book.’

02:54:15.120 --> 02:54:15.202
hmm

02:54:15.202 --> 02:54:16.080
‘I don't reading that book.’

02:54:16.080 --> 02:54:21.840
To form the negative in the present continuous,
we don't use ‘do’ or ‘does’

02:54:21.840 --> 02:54:25.520
We use the ‘be’ verb.
What is the be verb for ‘I’?

02:54:26.160 --> 02:54:28.160
The correct answer is ‘am’.

02:54:28.960 --> 02:54:33.840
‘I am not reading that book.’

02:54:34.399 --> 02:54:37.120
There is no contraction for ‘am not’.

02:54:38.560 --> 02:54:42.000
Finally, ‘They are to learn English.’

02:54:42.640 --> 02:54:46.640
We have the subject and we have the correct
‘be’ verb,

02:54:46.640 --> 02:54:49.360
but remember we need verb ‘-ing’.

02:54:50.160 --> 02:54:52.880
Therefore, the correct answer is,

02:54:53.439 --> 02:54:56.799
‘They are learning English.’

02:54:57.680 --> 02:54:59.600
Let's move on to the next checkup.

02:55:00.479 --> 02:55:04.879
For this checkup we'll take a look at how
the present continuous tense

02:55:04.880 --> 02:55:07.840
can be used to talk about future plans.

02:55:07.840 --> 02:55:08.640
Let's take a look.

02:55:09.279 --> 02:55:13.920
The first sentence says,
‘They're play a game tonight.’

02:55:13.920 --> 02:55:16.160
The verb we want to use is ‘play’.

02:55:17.040 --> 02:55:20.880
Remember we start with the subject&nbsp;
and here we have it, ‘they’.

02:55:21.760 --> 02:55:24.000
Then we have the ‘be’ verb.

02:55:24.000 --> 02:55:28.960
In this case we used a contraction&nbsp;
for ‘they are – ‘they’re’.

02:55:28.960 --> 02:55:29.840
That's correct.

02:55:30.800 --> 02:55:35.520
After that we have to add ‘-ing’ to the
end of the verb,

02:55:35.520 --> 02:55:40.241
so the correct answer is,
‘They're playing a game tonight.’

02:55:41.359 --> 02:55:46.160
The next sentence says,
'We _blank_ not studying tomorrow.’

02:55:47.279 --> 02:55:49.679
Looks good but there's a word that's missing.

02:55:50.319 --> 02:55:53.519
This is the negative form because we have ‘not’.

02:55:53.520 --> 02:55:56.000
We simply need the ‘be’ verb for ‘we’.

02:55:56.880 --> 02:56:02.480
The correct ‘be’ verb is ‘are’.
‘We are not studying tomorrow.’

02:56:03.520 --> 02:56:08.000
The next sentence says,
‘Lynn is _blank_ out tonight.’

02:56:08.000 --> 02:56:10.160
and we want to use the verb ‘go’.

02:56:10.960 --> 02:56:15.279
Remember 'Lynn' and then the ‘be’ verb – ‘is’.

02:56:15.279 --> 02:56:19.359
That's correct.
All we have to do is add ‘-ing’.

02:56:21.520 --> 02:56:24.081
‘Lynn is going out tonight.’

02:56:24.640 --> 02:56:27.120
To make this negative you can say,

02:56:27.120 --> 02:56:32.080
‘Lynn is not going out tonight.’ or
‘Lynn isn't going out tonight.’

02:56:33.040 --> 02:56:37.680
The next sentence says,
‘Laura isn't study this evening.’

02:56:38.479 --> 02:56:39.839
Can you find the mistake?

02:56:41.200 --> 02:56:45.920
Remember we have to add&nbsp;
‘-ing’ to the end of the verb,

02:56:46.479 --> 02:56:48.160
so we need to say,

02:56:48.160 --> 02:56:53.840
‘Laura isn't studying this evening.’

02:56:54.479 --> 02:56:56.080
The next sentence says,

02:56:56.080 --> 02:56:59.040
‘My sons will playing chess later.’

02:56:59.840 --> 02:57:02.400
We are talking about a future plan,

02:57:02.399 --> 02:57:06.799
so you might be tempted to use ‘well’
or ‘will’, I'm sorry.

02:57:06.800 --> 02:57:11.120
However, instead of saying ‘will’, we
use the ‘be’ verb.

02:57:11.120 --> 02:57:16.559
‘My sons are playing chess later.’

02:57:17.600 --> 02:57:22.161
And finally, ‘She's not to eating dinner tonight.’

02:57:22.160 --> 02:57:24.960
There's an extra word in here that we don't need.

02:57:25.520 --> 02:57:26.161
What is it?

02:57:27.120 --> 02:57:27.920
It's ‘to’.

02:57:28.960 --> 02:57:34.560
Remember, subject - ‘be’ verb, not verb ‘-ing’.

02:57:34.560 --> 02:57:37.360
We do not need ‘to’ in this sentence.

