02:58:51.200 --> 02:58:54.479
Let's talk about one usage of the present
perfect tense.

02:58:55.200 --> 02:59:00.240
This tense can be used to talk about an action
that happened in the past.

02:59:00.240 --> 02:59:04.559
But when it happened is not important or not
known.

02:59:05.439 --> 02:59:09.599
However, this action is&nbsp;
important to the conversation&nbsp;

02:59:09.600 --> 02:59:10.241
right now.

02:59:10.800 --> 02:59:12.640
Let's take a look at some examples.

02:59:13.359 --> 02:59:17.120
The first one says, ‘I have been to Canada.’

02:59:17.840 --> 02:59:21.120
What we do here is we start with the subject,
‘I’.

02:59:22.000 --> 02:59:26.080
For ‘I’, ‘you’, ‘we’, and ‘they’,
we follow with ‘have’.

02:59:27.040 --> 02:59:30.319
After that we use the past participle of the
verb.

02:59:31.040 --> 02:59:33.200
In this case, the verb is ‘be’.

02:59:33.200 --> 02:59:35.599
And so the past participle is ‘been’.

02:59:36.399 --> 02:59:38.399
‘I have been to Canada.’

02:59:39.279 --> 02:59:43.040
The next sentence says, ‘My cousins have
seen the movie.’

02:59:43.920 --> 02:59:45.680
My cousins is a ‘they’.

02:59:46.240 --> 02:59:48.800
And so again, we follow with ‘have’.

02:59:49.680 --> 02:59:53.201
And the past participle of see is ‘seen’.

02:59:54.000 --> 02:59:56.000
‘They have seen the movie.’

02:59:56.000 --> 02:59:58.560
Or ‘My cousins have seen the movie.’

02:59:59.920 --> 03:00:02.720
The next example says, ‘Chad has gone home.’

03:00:03.600 --> 03:00:05.040
Chad is a ‘he’.

03:00:05.920 --> 03:00:09.840
For ‘he’, ‘she’, ‘it’, we follow
with ‘has’.

03:00:11.040 --> 03:00:15.279
Then, the past participle ‘gone’ is for
the verb ‘go’.

03:00:16.160 --> 03:00:17.680
‘Chad has gone home.’

03:00:18.720 --> 03:00:21.600
And finally, ‘My phone has been fixed.’

03:00:22.240 --> 03:00:24.000
My phone is an ‘it’.

03:00:24.720 --> 03:00:26.560
Therefore, I use ‘has’.

03:00:27.279 --> 03:00:30.960
And then I need the past participle of ‘be’
– ‘been’.

03:00:31.680 --> 03:00:33.440
‘My phone has been fixed.’

03:00:34.240 --> 03:00:36.160
Let's move on to the next usage.

03:00:36.720 --> 03:00:42.640
The present perfect tense is also used to
describe an action that started in the past

03:00:42.640 --> 03:00:44.400
and continues in the present.

03:00:45.279 --> 03:00:50.319
‘for’ and since’ are common expressions
used with the present perfect tense.

03:00:50.880 --> 03:00:52.720
Let's take a look at these examples.

03:00:53.760 --> 03:00:56.720
‘I have worked there since 2002.’

03:00:57.520 --> 03:01:00.161
You'll notice we start with the subject.

03:01:00.160 --> 03:01:03.519
If it's ‘I’, ‘you’ or ‘we’, we
have ‘have’.

03:01:04.399 --> 03:01:07.359
Then the past participle of the verb.

03:01:07.359 --> 03:01:08.799
In this case - ‘worked’.

03:01:09.600 --> 03:01:13.920
What you'll notice here is that we also have
‘since 2002’.

03:01:14.800 --> 03:01:20.720
This shows when the action started, so with
the expression ‘since’, you need to use

03:01:20.720 --> 03:01:22.640
a specific point in time.

03:01:23.439 --> 03:01:25.439
The next example does the same thing.

03:01:26.240 --> 03:01:28.960
‘You have had a car since last year.’

03:01:29.760 --> 03:01:36.000
Again, we use ‘since’, so we have a specific
point in time - ‘last year’.

03:01:36.800 --> 03:01:38.720
Take a look at the next example.

03:01:39.439 --> 03:01:41.439
‘Anna has liked him for weeks.’

03:01:42.160 --> 03:01:44.479
In this case the subject is ‘Anna’.

03:01:44.479 --> 03:01:48.080
Which is a ‘she’, and so we use ‘has’.

03:01:48.080 --> 03:01:50.479
Then the past participle ‘liked’.

03:01:51.359 --> 03:01:56.160
However, at the end of the sentence, we see
‘for weeks’.

03:01:56.160 --> 03:01:57.599
Not ‘since weeks’.

03:01:58.240 --> 03:02:01.840
When we use ‘for’, we talk about the duration.

03:02:01.840 --> 03:02:05.200
We explain how long this action has been true.

03:02:06.080 --> 03:02:10.240
And finally, ‘We have eaten lunch here for
3 months.’

03:02:11.120 --> 03:02:14.880
Again, the sentence ends with ‘for 3 months’.

03:02:14.880 --> 03:02:16.720
So we show the duration.

03:02:17.600 --> 03:02:19.440
Let's move on to the next usage.

03:02:20.720 --> 03:02:26.640
In addition, the present perfect tense can
be used to describe an action that recently

03:02:26.640 --> 03:02:27.120
stopped.

03:02:27.680 --> 03:02:29.840
Let’s take a look at some examples.

03:02:30.560 --> 03:02:33.040
‘I have just been to the doctor,’

03:02:33.600 --> 03:02:37.680
So just like for all the other usages, we
start with the subject,

03:02:37.680 --> 03:02:41.360
‘have’ or ‘has’, and the past participle.

03:02:41.359 --> 03:02:47.359
But you'll notice here, I used the word ‘just’
between ‘have’ and the verb.

03:02:47.359 --> 03:02:49.679
‘I have just been to the doctor.’

03:02:50.319 --> 03:02:53.279
This shows that it happened very recently.

03:02:54.160 --> 03:02:58.960
The next example says, ‘James has just seen
his new baby.’

03:02:59.680 --> 03:03:04.560
Again, just goes in between ‘have’ or
‘has’ and the verb.

03:03:05.680 --> 03:03:07.920
Take a look at the next example.

03:03:07.920 --> 03:03:11.920
It says, ‘She has already been to China.’

03:03:11.920 --> 03:03:17.440
‘already’ is another word you can use
to show that this action recently happened.

03:03:18.160 --> 03:03:23.439
However, ‘already’ can also be moved to
the end of the sentence.

03:03:23.439 --> 03:03:28.399
So it's perfectly fine to say, ‘She has
been to China already.’

03:03:29.359 --> 03:03:33.759
And in the last example, ‘We have recently
visited Tom.’

03:03:34.479 --> 03:03:39.519
Again, you can put this word between ‘have’
or ‘has’ and the verb.

03:03:39.520 --> 03:03:43.201
Or you can also put it at the end of the sentence.

03:03:43.200 --> 03:03:45.519
‘We have visited Tom recently.’

03:03:46.319 --> 03:03:47.599
Let's move on.

03:03:47.600 --> 03:03:52.000
Let's take a look at the negative form of
the present perfect tense.

03:03:52.000 --> 03:03:54.080
Here are some examples.

03:03:54.080 --> 03:03:57.279
The first one says, ‘I have not been to
Europe.’

03:03:58.000 --> 03:04:03.760
What you'll notice in the first sentence is
that we simply put a 'not' between ‘have’

03:04:03.760 --> 03:04:04.720
and ‘been’.

03:04:05.279 --> 03:04:07.840
‘I have not been to Europe.’

03:04:08.640 --> 03:04:13.600
You can also use a contraction and say ‘I
haven't been to Europe.’

03:04:14.479 --> 03:04:19.040
The next sentence says, ‘It has not rained
for 3 months.’

03:04:19.840 --> 03:04:24.160
Again, we put the ‘not’ between the ‘has’
and the verb.

03:04:24.880 --> 03:04:27.760
‘It has not rained for 3 months.’

03:04:28.399 --> 03:04:32.399
Here we have a time expression to show the
duration.

03:04:33.520 --> 03:04:38.241
The next example says, ‘Teddy hasn't driven
for 2 years.’

03:04:38.880 --> 03:04:43.040
We used the contraction here for ‘has’
and ‘not’ – ‘hasn't’.

03:04:43.680 --> 03:04:49.840
And then we use the time expression ‘for
2 years’ at the end of the sentence.

03:04:50.399 --> 03:04:57.120
And finally, the last sentence says, ‘My
sons haven't played soccer since 2010.’

03:04:57.760 --> 03:05:02.640
We see another contraction here for ‘have
not’ – ‘haven't’.

03:05:03.200 --> 03:05:06.960
‘My sons haven't played soccer since 2010.’

03:05:07.760 --> 03:05:10.480
This time expression uses ‘since’.

03:05:10.479 --> 03:05:13.599
And so we mention a specific point and time.

03:05:14.479 --> 03:05:15.279
Let's move on.

03:05:15.840 --> 03:05:21.279
Now let's take a look at the ‘have’ or
‘has’ question form of the present perfect

03:05:21.279 --> 03:05:21.679
tense.

03:05:22.240 --> 03:05:23.519
Take a look at the board.

03:05:24.319 --> 03:05:27.679
The first sentence says, ‘Mike has eaten
lunch.’

03:05:28.240 --> 03:05:29.599
That is a statement.

03:05:30.160 --> 03:05:33.040
Now to turn it into a question, it's quite
easy.

03:05:33.760 --> 03:05:36.640
All you have to do is put ‘has’ at the
beginning.

03:05:37.439 --> 03:05:42.319
Then you follow with the subject and then
the past participle.

03:05:42.319 --> 03:05:47.359
You'll notice that the placement of the past
participle doesn't change.

03:05:47.359 --> 03:05:50.799
We've simply changed the order of the first
2 words.

03:05:51.359 --> 03:05:53.040
‘Has Mike eaten lunch?’

03:05:54.000 --> 03:05:55.600
‘Has Mike eaten lunch?’

03:05:56.240 --> 03:06:01.439
And you can answer by saying ‘Yes, he has.’
or ‘No, he hasn't.’

03:06:02.479 --> 03:06:05.919
The next sentence says, ‘They have watched
the video.’

03:06:06.800 --> 03:06:08.640
This is a statement.

03:06:08.640 --> 03:06:14.560
If we want to turn it into a question, again,
we change the order of the first two words.

03:06:15.279 --> 03:06:15.920
‘Have they…?’

03:06:16.640 --> 03:06:20.400
And the past participle verb stays in the
same place.

03:06:21.200 --> 03:06:25.760
‘Have they watched the video?’

03:06:25.760 --> 03:06:26.560
‘Have they watched the video?’

03:06:26.560 --> 03:06:30.400
You can answer this question by saying, ‘Yes,
they have.’

03:06:30.399 --> 03:06:32.160
or ‘No, they haven't.’

03:06:32.880 --> 03:06:34.080
Good job, guys.

03:06:34.080 --> 03:06:35.200
Let's move on.

03:06:35.200 --> 03:06:40.800
Now, I'll briefly introduce how to ask WH
questions in the present perfect tense.

03:06:41.439 --> 03:06:42.719
Take a look at the board.

03:06:43.279 --> 03:06:46.880
I have ‘where’, ‘what’, ‘who’,
and ‘how’.

03:06:47.439 --> 03:06:49.919
These go at the beginning of the question.

03:06:50.720 --> 03:06:52.720
Let's take a look at the first example.

03:06:53.439 --> 03:06:54.799
‘Where has Tim been?’

03:06:55.520 --> 03:07:00.480
You'll notice we followed the WH word with
‘has’ or ‘have’.

03:07:01.120 --> 03:07:06.720
In this case, I used ‘has’ because the
subject is ‘Tim’, and Tim is a ‘he’.

03:07:07.359 --> 03:07:11.519
And then we followed that with the past participle
of the verb.

03:07:12.160 --> 03:07:14.000
‘Where has Tim been?’

03:07:14.000 --> 03:07:17.680
And I can answer by saying, ‘Tim has been
home.’

03:07:17.680 --> 03:07:20.480
or ‘Tim has been on vacation.’

03:07:20.479 --> 03:07:21.359
Something like that.

03:07:22.000 --> 03:07:25.760
The next question says, what countries have
you visited?

03:07:26.560 --> 03:07:30.320
I can answer by saying, ‘I have visited
China.’

03:07:30.319 --> 03:07:32.240
or ‘I have visited Mexico.’

03:07:32.800 --> 03:07:35.600
You can also use the contraction ‘I’ve’.

03:07:35.600 --> 03:07:38.000
‘I've visited China.’

03:07:38.000 --> 03:07:41.040
The next question says, ‘Who has she talked
to?’

03:07:41.840 --> 03:07:47.760
You can answer by saying, ‘She has talked
to her mom.’ or ‘She has talked to her

03:07:47.760 --> 03:07:48.160
teacher.’

03:07:49.279 --> 03:07:52.960
The next question says, ‘How long have you
been married?’

03:07:53.920 --> 03:07:55.920
‘I've been married for 3 years.’

03:07:56.479 --> 03:07:58.319
That's one answer that you can give.

03:07:59.040 --> 03:08:00.399
Great job, everybody.

03:08:00.399 --> 03:08:01.200
Let's move on.

03:08:02.000 --> 03:08:05.840
For this checkup, we'll take a look at the
present perfect tense.

03:08:05.840 --> 03:08:08.560
Which describes an action that happened at

03:08:08.560 --> 03:08:12.081
an unknown or indefinite time in the past.

03:08:12.080 --> 03:08:13.680
Let's look at the first sentence.

03:08:14.319 --> 03:08:16.960
‘She _blank_ read that book.’

03:08:17.600 --> 03:08:20.161
The subject in this sentence is ‘she’.

03:08:20.800 --> 03:08:25.279
For he/she/it, in this tense we say, ‘has’.

03:08:26.640 --> 03:08:27.520
‘She has’.

03:08:28.240 --> 03:08:30.080
Now, take a look at the verb.

03:08:30.640 --> 03:08:32.320
It looks like ‘read’.

03:08:32.319 --> 03:08:36.719
But remember we need to use the past participle
of the verb.

03:08:36.720 --> 03:08:38.241
So It's actually ‘read’.

03:08:38.960 --> 03:08:41.040
‘read’ and ‘read’ are spelled the
same.

03:08:41.760 --> 03:08:43.760
‘She has read that book.’

03:08:45.120 --> 03:08:48.800
The second sentence says, ‘They _blank_
visit China.’

03:08:49.439 --> 03:08:52.080
‘visit’ is the verb that you want to use
here.

03:08:52.800 --> 03:08:57.040
For ‘I’, ‘you’, ‘we’ and ‘they’,
we use ‘have’.

03:08:57.600 --> 03:08:58.720
Not ‘has’.

03:08:59.760 --> 03:09:00.560
‘They have’

03:09:01.120 --> 03:09:04.000
Now, what's the past participle of visit?

03:09:04.560 --> 03:09:06.560
The answer is ‘visited’.

03:09:07.200 --> 03:09:10.319
‘They have visited China.’

03:09:11.600 --> 03:09:16.080
Next, ‘We _blank_ see that concert.’

03:09:16.080 --> 03:09:20.559
Again, for ‘I’, ‘you’, we’ and ‘they’
– we use ‘have’.

03:09:21.520 --> 03:09:22.320
‘We have’.

03:09:22.960 --> 03:09:26.960
Now, the past participle of ‘see’ is 'seen'.

03:09:27.760 --> 03:09:30.560
‘We have seen that concert.’

03:09:31.680 --> 03:09:34.960
Now, let's look for the mistake in the next
sentence.

03:09:35.760 --> 03:09:38.000
‘Rick have been to Cuba.’

03:09:38.640 --> 03:09:40.960
Take a look at the subject, ‘Rick’.

03:09:41.680 --> 03:09:43.120
Rick is a ‘he’.

03:09:43.680 --> 03:09:48.800
So instead of ‘have’, we need to change
this to ‘has’.

03:09:49.359 --> 03:09:51.599
‘Rick has been to Cuba.’

03:09:53.439 --> 03:09:56.399
‘Sally and I hasn't finished work.’

03:09:57.520 --> 03:10:00.800
The subject in this sentence is ‘Sally’
and ‘I’.

03:10:01.760 --> 03:10:03.920
The pronoun for that is ‘we’.

03:10:05.279 --> 03:10:07.200
‘We hasn't finished work.’

03:10:07.840 --> 03:10:09.680
That still sounds weird, right?

03:10:10.319 --> 03:10:17.200
We have to change this to ‘have not’ or
the contraction ‘haven't’.

03:10:18.000 --> 03:10:21.439
And finally, ‘I did go to the doctor.’

03:10:22.160 --> 03:10:26.399
Now this sentence makes sense, but it's not
the present perfect tense.

03:10:26.960 --> 03:10:28.720
We have to change it.

03:10:28.720 --> 03:10:33.600
Remember, we use ‘have’ for the subject,
‘I’.

03:10:34.160 --> 03:10:35.359
But we're not done.

03:10:35.920 --> 03:10:40.480
What is the past participle of ‘go’?

03:10:42.000 --> 03:10:43.359
It is ‘gone’.

03:10:43.920 --> 03:10:46.080
‘I have gone to the doctor.’

03:10:46.880 --> 03:10:47.760
Great job.

03:10:47.760 --> 03:10:49.520
Let's move on to the next checkup.

03:10:50.160 --> 03:10:53.840
In this checkup, we'll talk about the present
perfect tense

03:10:53.840 --> 03:10:59.600
and how it can be used to describe an action
that started in the past and is still true

03:10:59.600 --> 03:11:00.080
today.

03:11:01.120 --> 03:11:06.399
The first sentence says, ‘I _blank_ known
Carly since 1994.’

03:11:06.960 --> 03:11:08.399
The subject is ‘I’.

03:11:08.960 --> 03:11:13.279
And we already have the past participle of
the verb, ‘know’.

03:11:13.279 --> 03:11:14.559
Which is ‘known’.

03:11:15.200 --> 03:11:16.080
What are we missing?

03:11:16.720 --> 03:11:18.800
The correct answer is ‘have’.

03:11:19.359 --> 03:11:25.040
For ‘I’, ‘you’, ‘we’ and ‘they’,
we use ‘have’ after the subject.

03:11:25.920 --> 03:11:27.600
The next sentence says,

03:11:27.600 --> 03:11:30.720
‘He has been here _blank_ 2 p.m.’

03:11:31.680 --> 03:11:34.480
Now the first part is all there.

03:11:34.479 --> 03:11:35.839
‘He has been’.

03:11:36.560 --> 03:11:40.000
However, remember that for the present perfect
tense,

03:11:40.000 --> 03:11:45.279
we use ‘for’ or ‘since’ to talk about
how long that action has been true.

03:11:45.920 --> 03:11:48.239
In this case, we use ‘since’.

03:11:48.800 --> 03:11:53.120
Because 2 p.m. is a specific period in time.

03:11:54.319 --> 03:11:58.799
Next it says, ‘She _blank_ liked Tom since
June.’

03:11:59.439 --> 03:12:01.599
The subject is ‘she’.

03:12:01.600 --> 03:12:06.640
And we have the past participle of the verb
‘like’, which is 'liked'.

03:12:07.279 --> 03:12:08.239
What are we missing?

03:12:08.880 --> 03:12:11.520
Again, we need ‘have’ or ‘has’.

03:12:12.239 --> 03:12:14.319
Because the subject is ‘she’...

03:12:14.960 --> 03:12:17.920
Can you figure out which one you need?

03:12:17.920 --> 03:12:19.920
The correct answer is ‘has’.

03:12:20.560 --> 03:12:23.840
‘She has liked Tom since June.’

03:12:24.800 --> 03:12:28.560
Now, I want you to find a mistake in the next
sentence.

03:12:29.279 --> 03:12:32.559
‘I have worked here six months ago.’

03:12:33.359 --> 03:12:34.799
Can you find a mistake here?

03:12:35.680 --> 03:12:38.320
‘I have worked’ - that's correct.

03:12:38.960 --> 03:12:43.439
However, in the present perfect tense, we
don't use ‘ago’.

03:12:44.479 --> 03:12:47.599
This is talking about more the past.

03:12:47.600 --> 03:12:51.280
We want to talk about ‘since’ or ‘for’
instead.

03:12:52.000 --> 03:12:55.600
Now ‘six months’ is not a specific time.

03:12:55.600 --> 03:12:57.360
So we don't use ‘since’.

03:12:58.319 --> 03:13:01.200
Instead, we talk about the duration.

03:13:01.200 --> 03:13:02.639
So we need ‘for’.

03:13:03.680 --> 03:13:07.760
We'll say, ‘I have worked here for six months.’

03:13:08.720 --> 03:13:10.640
Let's take a look at the next sentence.

03:13:11.439 --> 03:13:14.319
‘Jen have a cold for two weeks.’

03:13:15.600 --> 03:13:18.720
At first glance, this doesn't seem that wrong.

03:13:18.720 --> 03:13:22.000
But remember, Jen is a ‘she’.

03:13:22.560 --> 03:13:23.760
So we need ‘has’.

03:13:25.040 --> 03:13:26.080
‘Jen has’.

03:13:26.880 --> 03:13:29.760
But wait a minute, ‘Jen has have a cold’?

03:13:30.319 --> 03:13:32.080
That's not right either.

03:13:32.080 --> 03:13:34.640
We need the past participle of ‘have’.

03:13:35.359 --> 03:13:37.120
What is the past participle?

03:13:37.760 --> 03:13:39.840
The correct answer is ‘had’.

03:13:40.720 --> 03:13:44.880
‘Jen has had a cold for two weeks.’

03:13:45.600 --> 03:13:50.080
And finally, ‘We haven't went home since
Friday.’

03:13:50.800 --> 03:13:52.880
This one is a little tricky.

03:13:52.880 --> 03:13:54.239
The subject is ‘we’.

03:13:55.040 --> 03:13:56.640
‘We have... have not’.

03:13:56.640 --> 03:13:57.840
That's correct.

03:13:57.840 --> 03:13:59.760
The contraction is ‘haven't’.

03:13:59.760 --> 03:14:00.560
‘We haven't’.

03:14:01.200 --> 03:14:04.639
Now the problem is, we have this verb ‘went’.

03:14:05.200 --> 03:14:07.599
That's in the past simple tense.

03:14:08.319 --> 03:14:11.040
We need the past participle of ‘go’.

03:14:12.479 --> 03:14:14.719
The correct answer is ‘gone’.

03:14:16.560 --> 03:14:19.760
‘We haven't gone home since Friday.’

03:14:20.640 --> 03:14:21.760
Good job, guys.

03:14:21.760 --> 03:14:23.920
Let's move on to the next checkup.

03:14:23.920 --> 03:14:27.840
In this checkup, we'll take a look at the
present perfect tense.

03:14:27.840 --> 03:14:31.840
And how it is used to describe an action that
finished recently.

03:14:32.479 --> 03:14:37.919
We'll be focusing on the words, ‘just’,
‘already’ and ‘recently’ to show this.

03:14:37.920 --> 03:14:39.920
Let's take a look at the first sentence.

03:14:40.560 --> 03:14:43.520
‘She has just _blank_ that book.’

03:14:43.520 --> 03:14:45.360
And we're using the verb, ‘read’.

03:14:46.160 --> 03:14:48.639
Remember, we take the subject, ‘she’.

03:14:49.279 --> 03:14:53.200
And for ‘he’, ‘she’ and ‘it’,
we say ‘has’.

03:14:53.200 --> 03:14:54.720
So that's correct.

03:14:54.720 --> 03:14:57.840
Now we need the past participle of ‘read’.

03:14:58.399 --> 03:14:59.679
And that is ‘read’.

03:15:02.720 --> 03:15:04.960
‘She has just read that book.’

03:15:05.520 --> 03:15:10.240
You'll notice I use the word, ‘just’ right
before the past participle.

03:15:11.359 --> 03:15:16.319
Next it says, ‘They have already’ and
the verb is ‘wake up’.

03:15:17.680 --> 03:15:21.920
If the subject is ‘he’, ‘she’, or
‘it’, we use ‘has’.

03:15:22.560 --> 03:15:28.161
But if the subject is ‘I’, ‘you’,
‘we’ or ‘they’, we use ‘have’.

03:15:28.160 --> 03:15:29.439
So that's correct.

03:15:29.439 --> 03:15:30.160
‘They have’.

03:15:30.880 --> 03:15:36.080
Also we have the word ‘already’ here
to show that it happened recently

03:15:36.080 --> 03:15:37.920
or that it finished recently.

03:15:38.479 --> 03:15:40.399
Now the verb is ‘wake up’.

03:15:40.960 --> 03:15:44.399
We need the past participle of ‘wake up’,

03:15:44.399 --> 03:15:47.839
and that is ‘woken up’.

03:15:49.840 --> 03:15:51.920
So the answer is,

03:15:51.920 --> 03:15:54.319
‘They have already woken up.’

03:15:55.279 --> 03:15:56.880
The next sentence says,

03:15:56.880 --> 03:15:59.600
‘We have recently _blank_ work.’

03:16:00.160 --> 03:16:02.000
And the verb is ‘finish’.

03:16:02.960 --> 03:16:05.120
‘We have’, that's correct.

03:16:05.120 --> 03:16:09.040
And we have the word 'recently' to show when
the action finished.

03:16:09.040 --> 03:16:13.279
And now we need to find the past participle
of the verb ‘finish’.

03:16:13.920 --> 03:16:15.680
The correct answer is.

03:16:15.680 --> 03:16:21.600
‘We have recently finished, -ed, work.’

03:16:22.560 --> 03:16:26.400
Now try to find the mistake in the next sentence.

03:16:27.439 --> 03:16:29.839
‘Morty has eaten just.’

03:16:30.560 --> 03:16:32.560
This sounds a little strange, right?

03:16:33.279 --> 03:16:37.519
That's because ‘just’ needs to come before
the verb.

03:16:38.800 --> 03:16:42.560
Therefore, the answer is ‘Morty has just
eaten.’

03:16:43.760 --> 03:16:48.480
The next sentence says, ‘Karen has recently
be sick.’

03:16:49.760 --> 03:16:51.040
Karen is a ‘she’.

03:16:51.760 --> 03:16:53.680
So ‘has’ is correct.

03:16:54.239 --> 03:16:56.239
And there we have ‘recently’.

03:16:56.960 --> 03:17:00.239
Now we need the past participle of the verb.

03:17:01.520 --> 03:17:06.081
‘be’ is our verb and the past participle
of ‘be’ is ‘been’.

03:17:07.200 --> 03:17:09.760
‘Karen has recently been sick.’

03:17:10.720 --> 03:17:14.960
And finally, ‘I have gone already to the
dentist.’

03:17:15.600 --> 03:17:19.121
This is similar to another question we looked
at just before.

03:17:20.000 --> 03:17:22.880
‘I have gone already to the dentist.’

03:17:23.520 --> 03:17:28.000
The placement of ‘already’ is a little
awkward.

03:17:28.560 --> 03:17:32.880
So we can say, ‘I have already gone.’

03:17:32.880 --> 03:17:35.920
So we can put ‘already’ before the verb,

03:17:35.920 --> 03:17:38.720
‘I have already gone to the dentist’

03:17:38.720 --> 03:17:41.280
Or we can put this at the end,

03:17:42.160 --> 03:17:44.880
‘I have gone to the dentist already.’

03:17:45.520 --> 03:17:47.121
Both of those are correct.

03:17:48.000 --> 03:17:49.200
Now, good job.

03:17:49.200 --> 03:17:50.960
That is the end of the checkup.

03:17:50.960 --> 03:17:51.760
Let's move on.

03:17:52.720 --> 03:17:54.240
Excellent job, everyone.

03:17:54.239 --> 03:17:57.359
You just learned about the present perfect
tense.

03:17:57.359 --> 03:18:00.239
There was a lot to learn, but you did a wonderful
job.

