03:18:19.920 --> 03:18:24.640
In this video, I’ll introduce the Present
Perfect Continuous English Tense.

03:18:25.359 --> 03:18:28.399
This tense can be used to talk about an action

03:18:28.399 --> 03:18:31.759
that started in the past and continues in
the present.

03:18:32.319 --> 03:18:37.279
It can also be used to talk about an action
that hasn't happened recently.

03:18:38.000 --> 03:18:42.960
And finally, it can also be used to talk about
an action that recently stopped.

03:18:43.520 --> 03:18:45.760
There's a lot to learn, so keep watching.

03:18:49.040 --> 03:18:52.640
You can use the present perfect continuous
tense

03:18:52.640 --> 03:18:57.680
to talk about an action that started in the
past and continues in the present.

03:18:58.319 --> 03:19:00.639
We want to emphasize duration

03:19:00.640 --> 03:19:05.201
and you can do that by using ‘for’ or
‘since’ in your sentence.

03:19:05.200 --> 03:19:07.040
Let's take a look at some examples.

03:19:08.160 --> 03:19:11.439
‘Charles has been studying English for an
hour.’

03:19:12.319 --> 03:19:14.719
Take a look at the subject, ‘Charles’.

03:19:15.279 --> 03:19:17.840
The subject pronoun for Charles is ‘he’.

03:19:18.560 --> 03:19:20.320
And that's why we say ‘has’.

03:19:21.200 --> 03:19:25.760
After that, we add ‘been’ and then verb
‘-ing’.

03:19:25.760 --> 03:19:27.360
In this case, ‘studying.’

03:19:28.319 --> 03:19:32.719
You'll also notice that at the end of the
sentence we have for an hour.

03:19:33.359 --> 03:19:36.639
That shows how long this&nbsp;
action has been happening.

03:19:37.279 --> 03:19:42.239
When you use ‘for’, you emphasize the
duration. ‘for an hour’.

03:19:42.960 --> 03:19:46.160
‘Charles has been studying English for an
hour.’

03:19:47.279 --> 03:19:49.279
Let's take a look at the next sentence.

03:19:50.080 --> 03:19:53.439
‘Lily has been playing the piano for 2 years.’

03:19:54.080 --> 03:20:00.080
In this case, Lily is a ‘she’ and that's
why, again, we say ‘has’.

03:20:00.080 --> 03:20:04.160
You'll notice again, we have ‘been’ and
then verb ‘-ing’.

03:20:04.720 --> 03:20:06.080
In this case, ‘playing’.

03:20:07.040 --> 03:20:10.160
At the end of this sentence, we also used
‘for’.

03:20:10.800 --> 03:20:12.880
and then ‘two years’.

03:20:12.880 --> 03:20:16.720
So again, we're showing how long this has
been happening.

03:20:17.760 --> 03:20:19.840
The next sentence is a little different.

03:20:20.479 --> 03:20:22.799
‘It has been growing since June.’

03:20:23.359 --> 03:20:26.000
So it can be something like a plant.

03:20:26.640 --> 03:20:30.720
The plant or it has been growing since June.

03:20:31.520 --> 03:20:34.320
Here we use ‘since’, not ‘for’.

03:20:35.120 --> 03:20:36.080
What's the difference?

03:20:36.720 --> 03:20:39.840
We use a specific point in time with since.

03:20:40.399 --> 03:20:43.120
We don't say ‘Since two hours’.

03:20:43.120 --> 03:20:47.120
No, we say ‘When the action started since
June.’

03:20:47.920 --> 03:20:52.800
And finally, ‘Dan and I have been working
since 6 a.m.’

03:20:53.680 --> 03:20:56.560
The subject pronoun for ‘Dan and I’ is
‘We’.

03:20:57.279 --> 03:20:58.800
Therefore we use ‘have’.

03:20:59.840 --> 03:21:03.840
At the end of the sentence, we have ‘since
6 a.m.’

03:21:04.560 --> 03:21:10.081
Remember that with ‘since’, we talked
about a specific point in time when the action

03:21:10.080 --> 03:21:10.559
started.

03:21:11.279 --> 03:21:12.080
Let's move on.

03:21:12.800 --> 03:21:18.160
The present perfect continuous can also be
used without emphasizing duration.

03:21:18.880 --> 03:21:21.520
In this case, we mean ‘lately’.

03:21:21.520 --> 03:21:23.840
This action has been happening ‘lately’,

03:21:24.560 --> 03:21:29.520
and so we can use the word ‘lately’ or
‘recently’ to explain this.

03:21:30.080 --> 03:21:31.920
Let's take a look at some examples.

03:21:32.560 --> 03:21:35.840
‘You have been missing many classes lately.’

03:21:36.399 --> 03:21:40.879
You'll notice that at the end of the sentence
I use the word ‘lately'

03:21:40.880 --> 03:21:43.760
to describe when this action has been happening.

03:21:44.399 --> 03:21:48.080
You can also use lately at the beginning of
the sentence.

03:21:48.080 --> 03:21:52.399
For example, ‘Lately, you have been missing
many classes.’

03:21:53.520 --> 03:21:58.480
The next example says, ‘Recently, Toby has
been running every day.’

03:21:59.279 --> 03:22:02.800
In this sentence, we used ‘recently’ at
the beginning

03:22:02.800 --> 03:22:06.080
to show when does action has been happening.

03:22:06.080 --> 03:22:09.760
You can also use ‘recently’ at the end
of the sentence.

03:22:09.760 --> 03:22:12.480
‘Toby has been running everyday recently.’

03:22:13.439 --> 03:22:19.439
In this example, the subject is Toby and so
we use ‘has’ after Toby.

03:22:19.439 --> 03:22:21.439
Because Toby is a ‘he’.

03:22:22.560 --> 03:22:26.800
The next example says, ‘Lately, Dana has
been swimming a lot.’

03:22:27.439 --> 03:22:31.359
Again, we use ‘lately’ at the beginning
of this sentence,

03:22:31.359 --> 03:22:33.839
but you can also use it at the end.

03:22:34.479 --> 03:22:38.719
Dana is a ‘she’ and so we followed this
subject with ‘has’.

03:22:39.760 --> 03:22:44.720
And finally, ‘We've been practicing English
together recently.’

03:22:45.600 --> 03:22:49.280
‘We’ is the subject of this sentence and
so we use ‘have’.

03:22:49.920 --> 03:22:53.440
Here, we use the contraction ‘We’ve’.

03:22:53.439 --> 03:22:56.239
‘We have’ become ‘We've’.

03:22:56.240 --> 03:22:59.680
‘We've been practicing English together
recently.’

03:22:59.680 --> 03:23:02.080
We can put ‘recently’ at the end,

03:23:02.080 --> 03:23:06.880
or we can say ‘Recently we've been practicing
English together.’

03:23:07.680 --> 03:23:08.480
Let's move on.

03:23:09.600 --> 03:23:15.520
The present perfect continuous tense and also
be used to talk about an action that recently

03:23:15.520 --> 03:23:18.000
stopped and has a present result.

03:23:18.640 --> 03:23:20.400
Let's take a look at the example.

03:23:21.120 --> 03:23:24.000
‘I'm tired because I have been running.’

03:23:24.640 --> 03:23:27.440
The second part of the sentence, ‘I have
been running’

03:23:28.000 --> 03:23:30.880
is using the present perfect continuous tense.

03:23:31.439 --> 03:23:34.239
This is the action that recently stopped.

03:23:34.239 --> 03:23:37.279
And as a result, ‘I'm tired’.

03:23:37.279 --> 03:23:39.519
This is the present result.

03:23:39.520 --> 03:23:42.161
What's happening now, because of this.

03:23:42.160 --> 03:23:44.160
‘I'm tired.’.

03:23:44.160 --> 03:23:48.960
The next example says, ‘The street is wet
because it has been raining.’

03:23:49.600 --> 03:23:52.560
This is very similar to the first sentence.

03:23:52.560 --> 03:23:55.121
Here, we know that it has been raining.

03:23:55.120 --> 03:23:58.080
And this action recently stopped.

03:23:58.080 --> 03:24:02.239
As a result, in the present, The street is
wet.

03:24:02.239 --> 03:24:06.160
The street is wet right now because of this
action.

03:24:07.600 --> 03:24:13.201
The next example says, ‘You don't understand
because you haven't been listening.’

03:24:13.920 --> 03:24:16.880
You'll notice here that we use the negative.

03:24:16.880 --> 03:24:20.160
Here's the contractions, ‘haven't’ or
‘have not’

03:24:20.960 --> 03:24:24.480
because of this action,&nbsp;
you haven't been listening,

03:24:24.479 --> 03:24:26.879
now you don't understand.

03:24:27.920 --> 03:24:31.040
In the last example, we switch the order a
little bit.

03:24:31.760 --> 03:24:33.920
‘I've been studying all night.’

03:24:34.479 --> 03:24:37.679
There is the present perfect continuous tense.

03:24:37.680 --> 03:24:39.840
This is the action that stopped recently.

03:24:40.399 --> 03:24:42.239
And here is the result.

03:24:42.239 --> 03:24:44.239
‘Now, I'm exhausted.’

03:24:44.960 --> 03:24:46.239
Great job, everyone.

03:24:46.239 --> 03:24:47.040
Let's move on.

03:24:47.840 --> 03:24:52.720
Let's take a look at the negative form of
the present perfect continuous tense.

03:24:52.720 --> 03:24:53.840
Here are some examples.

03:24:54.960 --> 03:24:57.760
‘I have not been feeling well these days.’

03:24:58.560 --> 03:25:04.000
At the end of the sentence we have ‘these
days’ to show that this is an action that's

03:25:04.000 --> 03:25:05.520
been happening recently.

03:25:06.160 --> 03:25:09.279
In the negative form, we have to have ‘not’.

03:25:10.080 --> 03:25:13.680
The ‘not’ goes after have or has.

03:25:13.680 --> 03:25:17.520
In this case, the subject is ‘I’, so I
use ‘have’.

03:25:18.239 --> 03:25:22.080
‘I have not been feeling well these days.’

03:25:22.080 --> 03:25:26.239
We can also use a contraction ‘haven't’
or ‘have not’.

03:25:26.239 --> 03:25:29.200
‘I haven't been feeling well these days.’

03:25:30.160 --> 03:25:34.000
The next sentence says, ‘Sue has not been
cooking lately.’

03:25:34.720 --> 03:25:37.920
We have ‘lately’ at the end of this sentence,

03:25:37.920 --> 03:25:41.200
We can also put ‘lately’ at the beginning
of the sentence.

03:25:41.760 --> 03:25:45.920
The important part of this sentence is to
put ‘not’ after ‘has’.

03:25:46.640 --> 03:25:48.320
Why did we use ‘has’?

03:25:48.319 --> 03:25:51.840
Because the subject is ‘Sue’ which is
a 'she'.

03:25:51.840 --> 03:25:54.480
For ‘he’, ‘she’, ‘it’, we use
‘has’.

03:25:55.120 --> 03:25:59.279
Again, we can use a contraction ‘hasn't’
for has not.

03:25:59.840 --> 03:26:02.560
‘Sue hasn't been cooking lately.’

03:26:03.520 --> 03:26:09.121
The next sentence says, ‘Jeff hasn't been
eating healthy food recently.’

03:26:09.760 --> 03:26:15.120
Again, the ‘recently’ can be used at the
beginning or end of this sentence.

03:26:15.920 --> 03:26:18.960
We have the contestant ‘hasn't’ here for
you.

03:26:19.680 --> 03:26:22.240
‘hasn't’ is a contraction for ‘has not’.

03:26:22.800 --> 03:26:26.880
We have ‘has’ because the subject is Jeff
which is ‘he’.

03:26:27.680 --> 03:26:32.320
And finally, ‘They haven't been speaking
for over a year.’

03:26:33.120 --> 03:26:36.640
In this case, ‘for over a year’ shows
duration.

03:26:37.279 --> 03:26:41.679
Remember with ‘for’, you show how long
something has been happening.

03:26:42.319 --> 03:26:46.399
In this case, we have a contraction ‘haven't’
or ‘have not’.

03:26:47.200 --> 03:26:48.559
Great job, everybody.

03:26:48.560 --> 03:26:49.920
let's move on.

03:26:49.920 --> 03:26:54.160
Now, let's take a look at how to form the
‘have’ or ‘has’ question

03:26:54.160 --> 03:26:56.559
for the present perfect continuous tense.

03:26:57.359 --> 03:27:01.359
The first sentence says, ‘He has been reading
for an hour,’

03:27:02.000 --> 03:27:04.720
Now, to turn this into a question,

03:27:04.720 --> 03:27:08.720
all we have to do is change the order of the
first two words.

03:27:09.279 --> 03:27:12.319
So ‘He has’ becomes ‘Has he’.

03:27:13.200 --> 03:27:15.439
‘Has he been reading for an hour?’

03:27:16.239 --> 03:27:19.920
You'll notice that the second part of the
sentence doesn't change.

03:27:20.640 --> 03:27:22.640
‘Has he been reading for an hour?’

03:27:23.520 --> 03:27:28.640
To answer, you can simply say, ‘Yes, he
has.’ or ‘No, he hasn't.’

03:27:29.359 --> 03:27:33.279
The next sentence says, ‘They have been
sleeping since 8 p.m.’

03:27:34.000 --> 03:27:38.000
Again, the second part of the sentence stays
the same,

03:27:38.000 --> 03:27:41.120
and in the beginning, we just switch the first
two words.

03:27:41.680 --> 03:27:43.840
‘They have’ become ‘Have they’.

03:27:44.560 --> 03:27:46.640
‘Have they been sleeping since 8 p.m.?’

03:27:47.520 --> 03:27:51.041
To answer, you can say, ‘Yes, they have.’

03:27:51.040 --> 03:27:53.040
or ‘No. they haven't.’

03:27:53.840 --> 03:27:55.120
Great job, everybody.

03:27:55.120 --> 03:27:55.840
Let's move on.

03:27:56.640 --> 03:28:02.800
Now, let's take a look at how to form WH questions
in the present perfect continuous tense.

03:28:03.439 --> 03:28:06.719
Here, we have some WH question words.

03:28:06.720 --> 03:28:10.080
‘what’, ‘where’, ‘why’ and ‘how’.

03:28:10.080 --> 03:28:12.000
Let's take a look at the first question.

03:28:12.880 --> 03:28:14.640
‘What have you been doing lately?’

03:28:15.439 --> 03:28:18.639
I can answer by saying,
‘I have been working.’

03:28:18.640 --> 03:28:20.800
or ‘I have been studying.’

03:28:20.800 --> 03:28:23.147
I can also use the contraction ‘I've’.

03:28:23.146 --> 03:28:25.359
‘I've been working.’

03:28:25.359 --> 03:28:26.399
‘I've been studying.’

03:28:27.120 --> 03:28:30.319
The next question says, ‘Where have you
been traveling?’

03:28:31.120 --> 03:28:33.359
‘I have been traveling in Europe.’

03:28:33.359 --> 03:28:35.759
or ‘I've been traveling in Europe.’

03:28:37.120 --> 03:28:39.359
‘Why has he been feeling sad?’

03:28:40.080 --> 03:28:43.760
You can answer by saying, ‘He's been feeling
sad.’

03:28:43.760 --> 03:28:49.440
That's the contraction ‘he has’, he's
been feeling sad because his pet died.

03:28:50.319 --> 03:28:55.200
or ‘He has been feeling sad because he broke
up with his girlfriend.’

03:28:55.200 --> 03:28:56.080
Something like that.

03:28:56.640 --> 03:28:58.880
And ‘How has she been doing?’

03:28:59.600 --> 03:29:01.360
‘How has she been doing?’

03:29:01.359 --> 03:29:03.679
I can say, ‘She's been doing well.’

03:29:04.640 --> 03:29:07.120
‘She's’ is a contraction for ‘she has’.

03:29:07.920 --> 03:29:09.200
Great job, everyone.

