The lately is placed wrong in this sentence.

03:34:16.800 --> 03:34:17.840
We have to say,

03:34:20.080 --> 03:34:23.200
‘Lately, Jenny hasn't been helping me.’

03:34:23.760 --> 03:34:28.000
or we can also say,

03:34:28.000 --> 03:34:30.640
‘Jenny hasn't been helping me lately.’

03:34:31.520 --> 03:34:33.840
Let's move on to the next checkup.

03:34:33.840 --> 03:34:38.480
In this checkup, we'll talk about the present
perfect continuous tense

03:34:38.479 --> 03:34:42.080
and how it expresses an action that stopped
recently

03:34:42.080 --> 03:34:43.840
but has a present result.

03:34:44.720 --> 03:34:46.080
The first sentence says,

03:34:46.080 --> 03:34:49.359
‘I _blank_ . That's why I'm so sweaty.’

03:34:50.399 --> 03:34:52.639
The verb here is ‘exercise’.

03:34:52.640 --> 03:34:54.161
And the subject is ‘I’.

03:34:54.960 --> 03:34:58.239
Do we use ‘has’ or ‘have’ for the
subject ‘I’?

03:34:58.880 --> 03:35:00.800
The correct answer is ‘have’.

03:35:03.359 --> 03:35:09.839
Then, we put ‘been’ and then verb ‘-ing’.

03:35:14.080 --> 03:35:16.880
Okay, so the correct answer is,

03:35:16.880 --> 03:35:19.120
‘I have been exercising.

03:35:19.120 --> 03:35:21.120
That's why I'm so sweaty.’

03:35:21.120 --> 03:35:22.160
That's the result.

03:35:22.960 --> 03:35:24.480
The next sentence says,

03:35:24.479 --> 03:35:28.000
‘I'm covered in flour because I _blank_.’

03:35:28.000 --> 03:35:29.439
And the verb is ‘bake’.

03:35:30.640 --> 03:35:31.201
Take a look.

03:35:31.840 --> 03:35:35.600
I have ‘I'm covered in flour because’

03:35:35.600 --> 03:35:38.320
So this first part is the result.

03:35:38.319 --> 03:35:44.000
I need to show the action that stopped recently
in the present perfect continuous tense.

03:35:44.640 --> 03:35:46.880
Again, the subject is ‘I’.

03:35:46.880 --> 03:35:48.800
So we use ‘have been’.

03:35:51.120 --> 03:35:55.439
Then, all we do is add ‘-ing’ to the end
of baking.

03:35:59.120 --> 03:36:00.640
‘I have been baking.’

03:36:00.640 --> 03:36:01.520
So again,

03:36:02.080 --> 03:36:06.000
‘I'm covered in flour because
I have been baking.’

03:36:06.000 --> 03:36:08.720
And we can use the contraction and say,

03:36:08.720 --> 03:36:10.240
‘I've been baking.’

03:36:11.439 --> 03:36:14.160
Now, find the mistake in the next sentence.

03:36:16.560 --> 03:36:20.240
‘She has think a lot, so she has a headache.’

03:36:21.200 --> 03:36:21.840
Take a look.

03:36:23.279 --> 03:36:26.239
The result is that ‘she has a headache.’

03:36:26.239 --> 03:36:30.559
So we need to use the present perfect continuous
for the first part.

03:36:31.520 --> 03:36:33.201
‘She has’ is correct.

03:36:33.760 --> 03:36:34.480
What's missing?

03:36:35.359 --> 03:36:36.880
Don't forget the ‘been’.

03:36:38.560 --> 03:36:42.880
Also don't forget that we need to add ‘-ing’
to the verb.

03:36:46.000 --> 03:36:49.760
‘She has been thinking a lot, so she has
a headache.’

03:36:50.399 --> 03:36:52.799
Look at the next sentence and find the mistake.

03:36:54.080 --> 03:36:57.920
‘I'm so hungry because I have been diet.’

03:36:59.120 --> 03:37:05.680
The only mistake here is that someone forgot
to put the ‘-ing’ at the end of the verb, ‘diet’.

03:37:08.720 --> 03:37:10.400
The correct answer is,

03:37:10.399 --> 03:37:14.080
‘I'm so hungry because I have been dieting.’

03:37:15.040 --> 03:37:15.840
Great job, everyone.

03:37:16.399 --> 03:37:17.200
Let's move on.

03:37:18.160 --> 03:37:21.920
Thank you so much for watching this&nbsp;
grammar course on the present tense.&nbsp;

03:37:22.560 --> 03:37:26.640
Now, I want you to watch the next&nbsp;
grammar course on the past tense.&nbsp;

03:37:26.640 --> 03:37:29.840
I’ll see you there.

03:37:36.080 --> 03:37:37.359
Hi, everyone.

03:37:37.359 --> 03:37:41.679
In this video, I will introduce the past simple
English tense.

03:37:42.479 --> 03:37:48.879
This grammar tense can help you explain a
past general state, action, or habit.

03:37:49.439 --> 03:37:53.919
There's a lot to learn and it's a very important
tense, so keep watching.

03:37:57.680 --> 03:38:00.720
In this video, I will talk about the 'be'
verb

03:38:00.720 --> 03:38:02.320
in the past simple tense.

03:38:02.960 --> 03:38:08.640
The 'be' verb in the past simple tense can
be used to describe a past general state.

03:38:09.279 --> 03:38:13.599
We use the 'be' verbs, ‘was’ and ‘were’
in this tense.

03:38:14.239 --> 03:38:15.840
Take a look at the examples.

03:38:16.479 --> 03:38:17.839
‘I was scared.’

03:38:18.640 --> 03:38:21.680
‘James', or he 'was a teacher.’

03:38:22.720 --> 03:38:24.080
‘She was sad.’

03:38:25.120 --> 03:38:27.439
‘My dog was hungry.’

03:38:27.439 --> 03:38:28.879
‘My dog’ can be ‘it’.

03:38:29.520 --> 03:38:36.161
So for ‘I’, ‘he’, ‘she’, ‘it’,
we use the past tense 'be' verb, ‘was’.

03:38:37.199 --> 03:38:41.920
However, for ‘you’, ‘we’ and ‘they’,
we use ‘were’.

03:38:42.560 --> 03:38:44.560
‘You were a good student.’

03:38:45.359 --> 03:38:54.160
‘Your parents, or they were at the park.’
and ‘We were at home for two hours.’

03:38:54.160 --> 03:38:58.160
In this last sentence, you see that the duration
is emphasized.

03:38:58.720 --> 03:38:59.600
Great job.

03:38:59.600 --> 03:39:00.400
Let's move on.

03:39:01.439 --> 03:39:05.599
Now I will talk about regular verbs in the
past simple tense.

03:39:06.160 --> 03:39:07.840
Take a look at these examples.

03:39:08.800 --> 03:39:10.560
‘Liam played a game.’

03:39:11.439 --> 03:39:12.879
Liam is a ‘he’,

03:39:13.520 --> 03:39:18.320
but really it doesn't matter for regular verbs
in the past simple tense.

03:39:18.319 --> 03:39:24.719
Because no matter what the subject is, all
we have to do is add ‘d’ or ‘ed’

03:39:24.720 --> 03:39:26.080
to the end of the verb.

03:39:26.800 --> 03:39:30.239
Here the verb is ‘play’, so I added ‘-ed’.

03:39:30.880 --> 03:39:32.800
‘Liam played a game.’

03:39:33.920 --> 03:39:37.279
‘The car, or it needed gas.’

03:39:37.840 --> 03:39:39.920
The verb here is ‘need’.

03:39:39.920 --> 03:39:42.720
For the past simple tense, I added ‘-ed’.

03:39:44.000 --> 03:39:45.760
‘We watched a movie.’

03:39:46.319 --> 03:39:49.840
Again, an ‘ed’ at the of ‘watch’.

03:39:50.479 --> 03:39:52.879
‘You exercised for an hour.’

03:39:53.600 --> 03:39:56.240
In this case, the verb is ‘exercise’.

03:39:56.239 --> 03:40:00.000
I only need to add a ‘d’ to make it the
past tense.

03:40:00.640 --> 03:40:03.840
And finally, ‘They usually worked after
school.’

03:40:04.880 --> 03:40:06.400
The verb is ‘work’.

03:40:06.399 --> 03:40:09.920
And I added an ‘ed’
to make it in the past tense.

03:40:10.479 --> 03:40:14.639
The word ‘usually’ shows that this was
a habit.

03:40:14.640 --> 03:40:19.760
Remember, the past simple tense can be used
to show past habits.

03:40:20.479 --> 03:40:21.679
Let's move on.

03:40:21.680 --> 03:40:25.920
Now, I'll talk about irregular verbs in the
past simple tense.

03:40:26.479 --> 03:40:32.959
Remember, for regular verbs, we only add ‘d’
or ‘ed’ to make a verb into the past tense.

03:40:33.600 --> 03:40:38.480
However, for irregular verbs, we have to change
the verb in a different way.

03:40:39.040 --> 03:40:41.120
Let's take a look at some examples.

03:40:42.160 --> 03:40:43.920
‘I ate with my friend.’

03:40:44.720 --> 03:40:46.560
The verb here is ‘ate’.

03:40:47.279 --> 03:40:50.479
‘ate’ is the past simple tense of ‘eat’.

03:40:51.520 --> 03:40:55.041
The next example says, ‘Nara wrote a story.’

03:40:55.600 --> 03:40:57.600
The verb is ‘write’.

03:40:57.600 --> 03:41:03.920
And because it's irregular to change it into
the past tense, we change the verb to ‘wrote’.

03:41:05.199 --> 03:41:07.439
‘You often came home late.’

03:41:08.239 --> 03:41:12.719
The verb here is ‘come’ and it's been
changed to ‘came’.

03:41:13.600 --> 03:41:17.680
You'll notice that we had the word ‘often’
to show a habit.

03:41:19.040 --> 03:41:20.640
‘We bought a camera.’

03:41:21.439 --> 03:41:27.839
The verb here is ‘buy’ and it's been changed
to ‘bought’ to show the past simple tense.

03:41:28.720 --> 03:41:32.880
And finally, ‘My parents sent me money for
a year.’

03:41:33.600 --> 03:41:38.000
Here the verb ‘sent’ is the past tense
of ‘send’.

03:41:38.960 --> 03:41:43.520
Here we also see ‘for a year’, this shows
duration.

03:41:44.479 --> 03:41:45.679
Let's move on.

03:41:45.680 --> 03:41:51.520
Now I will talk about the negative form for
the 'be' verb in the past simple tense.

03:41:51.520 --> 03:41:52.960
Here are some examples.

03:41:53.600 --> 03:41:56.800
The first one says, ‘I was not hungry.’

03:41:57.840 --> 03:42:01.360
For the past simple tense, the negative 'be'
verb

03:42:01.359 --> 03:42:07.120
I f the subject is ‘I’, ‘he’, ‘she’
or ‘it’, we say ‘was not’.

03:42:07.680 --> 03:42:14.640
For example, ‘I was not’ or ‘she was
not’ or the contraction ‘wasn't’.

03:42:14.640 --> 03:42:16.161
‘I wasn't’.

03:42:16.160 --> 03:42:17.199
‘She wasn't’.

03:42:17.760 --> 03:42:21.280
So let's look again, ‘I was not hungry.’

03:42:22.399 --> 03:42:24.399
‘She wasn't home today.’

03:42:25.359 --> 03:42:29.439
Now, if the subject is ‘you’, ‘we’
or ‘they’,

03:42:29.439 --> 03:42:32.960
We say ‘were not’ or the contraction ‘weren't’.

03:42:33.760 --> 03:42:37.840
‘The children, or they were not quiet.’

03:42:38.640 --> 03:42:41.520
‘The children were not quiet.’

03:42:42.319 --> 03:42:48.559
And then, ‘The dog', or it was not, or 'wasn't
playful.’

03:42:49.439 --> 03:42:50.719
Let's move on.

03:42:50.720 --> 03:42:56.880
Now, let's talk about how to form the negative
in the past simple tense for non-'be' verbs,

03:42:56.880 --> 03:42:59.279
regular or irregular.

03:42:59.279 --> 03:43:00.719
Here are some examples.

03:43:01.359 --> 03:43:03.359
‘I did not like him.’

03:43:04.160 --> 03:43:10.239
What we do for non-'be' verbs is simply put
‘did not’ after the subject.

03:43:10.880 --> 03:43:15.520
And you'll notice that for the verb, we don't
make any changes.

03:43:15.520 --> 03:43:17.360
We keep the base verb.

03:43:18.479 --> 03:43:20.399
‘He didn't catch the ball.’

03:43:21.120 --> 03:43:26.319
Again, it's ‘he did not’,
but here we used a contraction,

03:43:26.319 --> 03:43:28.239
‘He didn't catch the ball.’

03:43:29.520 --> 03:43:31.680
‘They didn't dance.’

03:43:31.680 --> 03:43:34.560
Again, here's the contraction for ‘did not’.

03:43:35.120 --> 03:43:39.120
And you'll notice that for the verb, we didn't
change it at all.

03:43:39.760 --> 03:43:45.440
Here's an irregular verb, and here's a regular
verb, we keep them in the base form.

03:43:46.160 --> 03:43:49.760
And finally, ‘We didn't think about that.’

03:43:49.760 --> 03:43:53.360
Again, we simply say ‘did not’ or ‘didn't’.

03:43:54.080 --> 03:43:55.120
Let's move on.

03:43:55.120 --> 03:44:00.319
Now I will introduce two ways to form questions
for the past simple tense.

03:44:00.880 --> 03:44:02.720
Take a look at the first example.

03:44:03.520 --> 03:44:05.041
‘He was angry.’

03:44:05.920 --> 03:44:09.040
In this first sentence, we see the 'be' verb
‘was’.

03:44:09.840 --> 03:44:11.279
It's quite easy.

03:44:11.279 --> 03:44:16.719
All you have to do to turn this into a question
is switch the order the first two words.

03:44:17.279 --> 03:44:18.479
‘Was he angry?’

03:44:19.199 --> 03:44:24.239
You can answer by saying ‘Yes, he was.’
or ‘No, he wasn't.’

03:44:25.040 --> 03:44:28.239
The next sentence also has a 'be' verb.

03:44:28.239 --> 03:44:30.319
‘They were comfortable.’

03:44:30.880 --> 03:44:33.600
So again, switch the first two words.

03:44:34.239 --> 03:44:35.519
‘Were they comfortable?’

03:44:36.160 --> 03:44:39.120
The answers can be, ‘Yes, they were.’

03:44:39.120 --> 03:44:40.800
or ‘No, they weren't.’

03:44:41.680 --> 03:44:43.840
However, look at the third sentence.

03:44:44.399 --> 03:44:45.679
‘Sam lived here.’

03:44:46.319 --> 03:44:49.279
There is no 'be' verb in this sentence.

03:44:49.279 --> 03:44:52.239
Instead, we see the action verb ‘lived’.

03:44:52.800 --> 03:44:56.320
So what we do is no matter what the subject,

03:44:56.319 --> 03:44:58.239
we start the question with ‘did’.

03:44:59.120 --> 03:45:01.439
‘Did Sam live here?’

03:45:01.439 --> 03:45:06.160
You'll notice that the verb no longer is in
the past tense.

03:45:06.160 --> 03:45:08.399
We use the base form of the verb.

03:45:09.040 --> 03:45:10.880
‘Did Sam live here?’

03:45:11.520 --> 03:45:14.000
You can say ‘Yes, he did.’

03:45:14.000 --> 03:45:15.760
or ‘No, he didn't.’

03:45:16.640 --> 03:45:18.800
The last sentence is similar.

03:45:18.800 --> 03:45:21.120
‘They won the contest last year.’

03:45:21.840 --> 03:45:26.160
The verb here is ‘won’, that's not a 'be'
verb.

03:45:26.160 --> 03:45:29.519
So again, we start the question with ‘did’
.

03:45:29.520 --> 03:45:36.161
And then the subject ‘they’, we use the
base form of the verb and that's ‘win’.

03:45:36.880 --> 03:45:39.840
‘Did they win the contest last year?’

03:45:39.840 --> 03:45:42.000
You can say, ‘Yes, they did.’

03:45:42.000 --> 03:45:43.600
or ‘No, they didn't.’

03:45:44.319 --> 03:45:45.439
Let's move on.

03:45:45.439 --> 03:45:52.080
Now I'll introduce how to create an answer
WH questions in the past simple tense.

03:45:52.640 --> 03:45:54.320
Take a look at the board.

03:45:54.319 --> 03:45:56.559
We have some WH words here.

03:45:57.279 --> 03:45:58.479
‘What’
‘When’

03:45:59.040 --> 03:46:00.160
‘Where’
and ‘Why’

03:46:00.960 --> 03:46:05.199
You'll notice that after each WH word comes
the word ‘did’.

03:46:05.840 --> 03:46:08.160
‘What did’
‘When did’

03:46:08.160 --> 03:46:10.160
‘Where did’
and ‘Why did’.

03:46:11.040 --> 03:46:16.720
What comes after that the subject and then
the base form of the verb.

03:46:16.720 --> 03:46:18.320
So, let's take a look.

03:46:19.120 --> 03:46:21.840
‘What did you do last night?’

03:46:22.560 --> 03:46:24.000
‘What did you do last night?’

03:46:24.800 --> 03:46:28.960
I can answer by saying something like, ‘I
watched a movie.’

03:46:28.960 --> 03:46:30.480
Or ‘I read a book.’

03:46:31.199 --> 03:46:36.080
You'll notice that the answer is in the past
simple tense.

03:46:36.080 --> 03:46:37.840
‘When did you get home last night?’

03:46:38.560 --> 03:46:40.560
‘I got home at 10 p.m.’

03:46:42.080 --> 03:46:44.160
‘Where did they eat lunch?’

03:46:44.160 --> 03:46:46.000
‘They ate lunch at home.’

03:46:46.640 --> 03:46:50.161
Again, ‘ate’ is the past tense of ‘eat’.

03:46:50.160 --> 03:46:52.319
Answer in the past simple tense.

03:46:52.880 --> 03:46:56.080
And finally, ‘Why did the company hire him?’

03:46:56.880 --> 03:47:00.560
‘The company hired him because he's a hard
worker.’

03:47:01.439 --> 03:47:02.239
Let's move on.

03:47:02.800 --> 03:47:05.440
In this first checkup, we'll take a look at

03:47:05.439 --> 03:47:09.439
practice questions
using the 'be' verb in the past simple tense.

03:47:10.160 --> 03:47:15.120
Remember the 'be' verbs in the past simple
tense are ‘was’ or ‘were’.

03:47:15.680 --> 03:47:18.240
Let's take a look at the first sentence.

03:47:18.239 --> 03:47:20.559
‘He __ at work earlier.’

03:47:21.199 --> 03:47:22.720
The subject here is ‘we’.

03:47:23.359 --> 03:47:26.319
So do we use ‘was’ or ‘were’?

03:47:26.319 --> 03:47:28.639
The correct answer is ‘was’.

03:47:29.439 --> 03:47:32.239
‘He was at work earlier.’

03:47:32.880 --> 03:47:34.400
The next sentence says,

03:47:34.399 --> 03:47:37.439
‘We _____ very happy yesterday.’

03:47:38.080 --> 03:47:42.479
If the subject is ‘we’, remember the be
verb is ‘were’.

03:47:44.880 --> 03:47:47.520
‘We were very happy yesterday.’

03:47:48.399 --> 03:47:53.439
Next, ‘My parents or they __ worried about
me.’

03:47:54.479 --> 03:47:58.319
If it's 'they', remember we have to say ‘were’.

03:47:59.279 --> 03:48:01.519
‘My parents were worried about me.’

03:48:02.239 --> 03:48:07.760
If I want to use the negative, I can also
say ‘My parents weren't worried about me.’

03:48:07.760 --> 03:48:08.800
And that's possible.

03:48:09.600 --> 03:48:13.840
Now I want you to find the mistake in the
next sentence.

03:48:14.720 --> 03:48:16.720
‘We wasn't good students.’

03:48:17.680 --> 03:48:19.520
We wasn't good students.

03:48:20.160 --> 03:48:21.760
Can you figure out what's wrong?

03:48:22.640 --> 03:48:27.200
The subject here is ‘we’, so we don't
say ‘was not’.

03:48:27.199 --> 03:48:31.359
We need to say ‘were not’ or the contraction
‘weren't’.

03:48:34.000 --> 03:48:38.640
‘We weren't good students,’ is the correct
answer.

03:48:39.279 --> 03:48:41.840
The next one says, ‘Were she a teacher?’

03:48:42.960 --> 03:48:47.120
Now, this is a question so the be verb comes
at the beginning.

03:48:47.120 --> 03:48:50.559
That's correct, but the subject here is ‘she’.

03:48:51.359 --> 03:48:54.719
Therefore, we need to start with ‘was’.

03:48:55.439 --> 03:48:56.799
‘Was she a teacher?’

03:48:57.920 --> 03:48:58.720
And finally,

03:48:59.279 --> 03:49:01.120
‘They wasn't at school.’

03:49:02.080 --> 03:49:10.080
The subject is ‘they’, so the answer is

03:49:10.080 --> 03:49:12.640
‘They weren't at school.’

03:49:12.640 --> 03:49:16.240
You can use the contraction ‘weren't’
or ‘were not’.

03:49:16.960 --> 03:49:18.720
Let's move on to the next checkup.

03:49:19.920 --> 03:49:24.720
Now, let's practice regular verbs in the past
simple tense.

03:49:24.720 --> 03:49:26.480
Take a look at the first sentence.

03:49:27.040 --> 03:49:28.720
‘He ____ at home.’

03:49:29.359 --> 03:49:31.040
The verb is ‘study’.

03:49:31.840 --> 03:49:34.800
Remember, when changing a regular verb into

03:49:34.800 --> 03:49:39.040
the past tense,
we add ‘d’ or ‘ed’ to the end of the

03:49:39.040 --> 03:49:39.359
verb.

03:49:39.920 --> 03:49:44.319
However, there's a separate rule for words
that end in ‘y’.

03:49:44.319 --> 03:49:45.599
Such as, ‘study’.

03:49:46.160 --> 03:49:49.359
We drop the ‘y’ and we add ‘ied’.

03:49:50.000 --> 03:49:52.080
So the correct answer is,

03:49:52.080 --> 03:49:56.080
‘He studied at home.’

03:49:57.040 --> 03:50:00.399
The next sentence says, ‘We __ pencils.’

03:50:01.120 --> 03:50:04.720
We want to use negative because it says ‘not
use’.

03:50:05.520 --> 03:50:11.440
Remember for the negative, we always use ‘did
not’, no matter what the subject.

03:50:15.040 --> 03:50:17.519
You can also use the contraction ‘didn't’.

03:50:18.319 --> 03:50:20.719
Now, what do we do to the verb?

03:50:20.720 --> 03:50:22.640
We keep it as ‘is’.

03:50:22.640 --> 03:50:24.080
We do not change it.

03:50:25.120 --> 03:50:28.960
‘We didn't’ or ‘We did not’ use pencils.

03:50:30.000 --> 03:50:35.600
The next sentence says, ‘His friends or
they walk to the gym.’

03:50:36.479 --> 03:50:38.479
What's the past tense of ‘walk’?

03:50:39.040 --> 03:50:43.359
We simply have to add ‘ed’ because it's
a regular verb.

03:50:47.439 --> 03:50:49.599
‘His friends walked to the gym.’

03:50:50.640 --> 03:50:53.440
Now, find a mistake in the next sentence.

03:50:56.239 --> 03:50:58.479
‘She didn't likes math.’

03:50:59.520 --> 03:51:01.200
‘didn't’ is correct.

03:51:01.760 --> 03:51:07.040
However, remember we keep the verb as ‘is’
in the base form.

03:51:07.040 --> 03:51:09.279
So we don't say ‘likes’.

03:51:09.279 --> 03:51:10.719
We say ‘like’.

03:51:11.439 --> 03:51:12.960
‘She didn't like math.’

03:51:13.840 --> 03:51:17.279
The next sentence says, ‘Did it rained this
morning?’

03:51:17.840 --> 03:51:19.279
Now this is a question.

03:51:19.920 --> 03:51:23.359
In a question, it’s right to start the sentence
with ‘Did’.

03:51:24.319 --> 03:51:25.279
‘Did it rained?’

03:51:26.160 --> 03:51:27.439
Do you notice the mistake?

03:51:28.319 --> 03:51:34.000
Remember, we do not use the past tense form
in the question.

03:51:34.000 --> 03:51:36.640
We use the base form of the verb.

03:51:36.640 --> 03:51:38.161
‘Did it rain this morning?’

03:51:39.040 --> 03:51:42.479
And finally, ‘They not play the piano.’

03:51:43.279 --> 03:51:45.599
The verb is an action verb.

03:51:45.600 --> 03:51:48.640
So we need a ‘did’ in front of ‘not’.

03:51:50.560 --> 03:51:53.200
‘They did not play the piano.’

03:51:54.080 --> 03:51:55.920
Let's move on to the next checkup.

03:51:56.640 --> 03:52:01.280
Now, I'll talk about irregular verbs in the
past simple tense.

03:52:01.279 --> 03:52:03.120
Take a look at the first sentence.

03:52:03.680 --> 03:52:05.360
‘He __ to school.’

03:52:06.000 --> 03:52:07.359
And the verb is ‘run’.

03:52:08.239 --> 03:52:13.199
‘run’ is an irregular verb, so the past
tense form is ‘ran’.

03:52:15.199 --> 03:52:16.960
‘He ran to school.’

03:52:18.080 --> 03:52:21.279
The next sentence says, ‘We __ flowers.’

03:52:21.840 --> 03:52:25.840
We want to use the negative because here it
says ‘not grow’.

03:52:26.479 --> 03:52:30.719
Remember, no matter what the subject in the
negative form,

03:52:30.720 --> 03:52:32.240
we say ‘did not’

03:52:35.680 --> 03:52:36.960
or ‘didn't’.

03:52:37.920 --> 03:52:41.040
Then we keep the verb in its base form.

03:52:44.239 --> 03:52:48.399
‘We did not grow’ or ‘We didn't grow
flowers.’

03:52:49.279 --> 03:52:54.319
The next sentence says, ‘Where __ you teach
last year?’

03:52:54.319 --> 03:52:55.679
This is a question.

03:52:56.399 --> 03:53:00.399
Again, all we need to put is ‘did’.

03:53:01.199 --> 03:53:03.679
‘Where did you teach last year?’

03:53:03.680 --> 03:53:06.160
It doesn't matter what the subject is.

03:53:06.160 --> 03:53:08.000
We always go with ‘did’.

03:53:09.040 --> 03:53:12.319
Next, try to find the mistake in the next
sentence.

03:53:12.960 --> 03:53:15.120
‘He didn't sold newspapers.’

03:53:16.399 --> 03:53:22.239
Remember, in the negative, ‘didn't’ is
correct for whatever subject there is.

03:53:22.960 --> 03:53:26.480
However, we need to keep the verb in its base
form.

03:53:27.439 --> 03:53:32.080
So the correct answer is, ‘He didn't sell
newspapers.’

03:53:32.960 --> 03:53:36.560
The next sentence says, ‘Did she sing a
song?’

03:53:37.279 --> 03:53:39.840
You'll notice it's a similar problem here.

03:53:40.640 --> 03:53:44.080
‘sang’ is the irregular past tense form
of ‘sing’.

03:53:44.720 --> 03:53:48.400
But in a question, if it starts with ‘did’,

03:53:48.399 --> 03:53:49.839
we use the base form.

03:53:50.640 --> 03:53:53.600
‘Did she sing a song?’

03:53:54.720 --> 03:53:57.520
And finally, ‘We taked it home.’

03:53:58.479 --> 03:53:59.679
Does that sound right?

03:54:00.640 --> 03:54:02.560
‘taked’ is not correct.

03:54:03.120 --> 03:54:07.120
The past tense of ‘take’ is ‘took’.

03:54:08.160 --> 03:54:09.840
‘We took it home.’

03:54:10.720 --> 03:54:12.080
Great job, everyone.

03:54:12.080 --> 03:54:13.199
Let's move on.

03:54:13.199 --> 03:54:16.080
Wow, we learned a lot in this video.

03:54:16.720 --> 03:54:20.320
Keep studying and reviewing the past simple
tense.

03:54:20.319 --> 03:54:24.239
It's an essential tense that will help you
talk about the past.

03:54:24.880 --> 03:54:28.239
Keep studying English and I'll see you in
the next video.

03:54:28.239 --> 03:54:31.840
Bye.&nbsp;

03:54:37.680 --> 03:54:38.800
Hi, everybody.

03:54:38.800 --> 03:54:40.080
I'm Esther.

03:54:40.080 --> 03:54:41.199
In this video.

03:54:41.199 --> 03:54:44.000
I will introduce the past continuous
tense.

03:54:44.720 --> 03:54:49.760
This tense can be used to describe an action
that was ongoing in the past.

03:54:50.319 --> 03:54:55.920
It can also be used to describe two actions
happening at the same time in the past.

03:54:56.560 --> 03:54:59.840
There's a lot to learn so let's get started.

03:55:02.800 --> 03:55:06.880
Let's take a look at the first usage of the
past continuous tense.

03:55:07.680 --> 03:55:12.720
This tense can be used to describe an action
that was ongoing in the past.

03:55:13.279 --> 03:55:15.199
Let's take a look at these examples.

03:55:15.920 --> 03:55:18.960
‘I was walking in the park in the evening.’

03:55:19.920 --> 03:55:22.640
So first we start with the subject, ‘I’.

03:55:23.600 --> 03:55:28.240
For I, he, she, and it, we follow with ‘was’.

03:55:28.960 --> 03:55:29.760
‘I was’

03:55:30.479 --> 03:55:34.319
And then we add an ‘ING’ to the end of
the verb.

03:55:34.960 --> 03:55:36.480
‘I was walking’

03:55:37.279 --> 03:55:39.199
Now take a look at the whole sentence.

03:55:39.840 --> 03:55:42.640
‘I was walking in the park in the evening.’

03:55:43.359 --> 03:55:48.960
You can see that this was an ongoing action
and it happened in the past.

03:55:50.080 --> 03:55:51.840
Let's look at the next example.

03:55:52.720 --> 03:55:56.160
‘She was living here last year.’

03:55:56.160 --> 03:55:58.080
Here, the subject is ‘she’.

03:55:58.080 --> 03:56:01.840
So again we use ‘was’ and then ‘verb-ing’.

03:56:02.800 --> 03:56:09.840
Here we have another expression that shows
that this action was happening in the past.

03:56:09.840 --> 03:56:15.120
‘The dog,’ or ‘it’, ‘was eating
dinner five minutes ago.’

03:56:16.000 --> 03:56:21.359
The subject here is ‘the dog’ which can
be replaced by the pronoun ‘it’.

03:56:21.359 --> 03:56:23.839
And so we follow with ‘was’.

03:56:24.479 --> 03:56:29.839
And finally, ‘Andy and Jim,’ we can replace
this with ‘they’.

03:56:30.800 --> 03:56:34.960
For ‘you’, ‘we’ and ‘they’, we
use ‘were’.

03:56:35.760 --> 03:56:40.880
‘They were’, or ‘Andy and Jim were working
at 9:00 p.m.’

03:56:42.080 --> 03:56:42.800
Let's move on.

03:56:43.359 --> 03:56:47.920
The past continuous tense is also used to
describe an ongoing

03:56:47.920 --> 03:56:51.840
action in the past that was interrupted by
another action.

03:56:52.640 --> 03:56:57.920
This interrupting action is used in the past
simple tense with the word ‘when’.

03:56:58.720 --> 03:57:00.400
Let's take a look at this example.

03:57:01.120 --> 03:57:03.599
‘I was playing cards when you called.’

03:57:04.479 --> 03:57:08.639
Again we start with the subject ‘was’
or ‘were’,

03:57:08.640 --> 03:57:10.240
and then ‘verb-ing’,

03:57:11.199 --> 03:57:15.439
so this is the action that was ongoing in
the past,

03:57:15.439 --> 03:57:16.799
‘I was playing cards’

03:57:17.439 --> 03:57:21.599
The interrupting action in this sentence is
‘you called’.

03:57:22.239 --> 03:57:27.040
You'll notice I use the word ‘when’ to
show the interrupting action’

03:57:27.040 --> 03:57:30.640
And I used it in the past simple tense, ‘called’.

03:57:32.080 --> 03:57:33.840
Let's take a look at the next sentence.

03:57:34.479 --> 03:57:38.959
‘The cat' or 'it' was eating when Eric came
home.’

03:57:39.920 --> 03:57:44.480
Again the action in progress is ‘the cat
was eating’.

03:57:45.199 --> 03:57:50.000
And ‘Eric came home’, you'll notice the
past simple tense.

03:57:50.000 --> 03:57:53.840
This is the interrupting action used with
the word ‘when’.

03:57:55.279 --> 03:57:57.759
‘We were sleeping when Anne arrived.’

03:57:58.479 --> 03:58:01.839
Again we have the ongoing action in the past.

03:58:02.560 --> 03:58:04.161
The subject here is ‘we’.

03:58:04.160 --> 03:58:08.639
And so we used ‘were’ and then ‘verb-ing’.

03:58:09.760 --> 03:58:12.960
‘When Anne arrived’ is the interrupting
action.

03:58:13.840 --> 03:58:20.400
And finally, ‘Alicia and I’, or ‘We'
were walking when we saw Mark.’

03:58:21.439 --> 03:58:27.120
‘When we saw Mark’ is the interrupting
action that interrupted the ongoing ‘Alicia

03:58:27.120 --> 03:58:28.559
and I were walking’.

03:58:29.359 --> 03:58:35.279
It's also important to note that we can also
switch the order of the sentence around and

03:58:35.279 --> 03:58:35.840
say,

03:58:35.840 --> 03:58:38.960
‘When you called, I was playing cards,’

03:58:38.960 --> 03:58:42.560
or ‘When Eric came home, the cat was eating.’

03:58:43.520 --> 03:58:44.320
Let's move on.

03:58:45.199 --> 03:58:50.720
Another usage for the past continuous tense
is to talk about two actions that were

03:58:50.720 --> 03:58:53.199
happening at the same time in the past.

03:58:53.920 --> 03:58:58.880
We use the past continuous tense for both
actions with the word ‘while’.

03:58:59.760 --> 03:59:01.680
Let's take a look at some examples.

03:59:02.560 --> 03:59:07.520
The first sentence says,
‘While I was playing soccer, she was watching

03:59:07.520 --> 03:59:07.680
me.’

03:59:08.399 --> 03:59:12.879
You'll notice that both actions are in the
past continuous tense.

03:59:13.439 --> 03:59:16.799
‘I was playing soccer’ and ‘She was
watching me’.

03:59:17.520 --> 03:59:23.200
The word ‘while’ at the beginning shows
that these actions were happening at the sametime.

03:59:24.800 --> 03:59:28.000
‘While you were reading, I was preparing
dinner.’

03:59:28.800 --> 03:59:33.360
Again both actions are expressed in the past
continuous tense.

03:59:34.080 --> 03:59:38.000
The word ‘while’ shows that they were
happening at the same time.

03:59:39.600 --> 03:59:43.040
‘While Her husband’ or ‘he’, ‘was
driving

03:59:43.680 --> 03:59:45.520
she was taking pictures.’

03:59:46.479 --> 03:59:49.679
Both actions are in the past continuous tense.

03:59:50.399 --> 03:59:51.120
And finally,

03:59:51.760 --> 03:59:55.040
‘While we were eating, the music was playing.’

03:59:56.000 --> 03:59:58.800
Both actions were happening at the same time.

03:59:59.840 --> 04:00:05.440
Now, you'll notice that in my examples the
word ‘while’ comes at the beginning,

04:00:06.080 --> 04:00:11.199
however, it's important to note that you can
move the word ‘while’ around in several

04:00:11.199 --> 04:00:11.599
ways.

04:00:12.239 --> 04:00:15.120
For example, instead of saying this,

04:00:15.120 --> 04:00:18.479
‘While I was playing soccer, she was watching
me.’

04:00:18.479 --> 04:00:21.120
I can move ‘while’ to the middle of the
sentence.

04:00:21.760 --> 04:00:24.880
‘I was playing soccer while she was watching
me.’

04:00:25.600 --> 04:00:28.240
I can put the ‘while’ between the two
actions.

04:00:29.040 --> 04:00:32.720
Or I can also change the sentence around and
say,

04:00:32.720 --> 04:00:35.840
‘While she was watching me, I was playing
soccer.’

04:00:36.479 --> 04:00:41.519
So it doesn't matter which action comes first
with the ‘while’ if you put it in the

04:00:41.520 --> 04:00:42.000
beginning.

04:00:42.960 --> 04:00:43.760
Let's move on.

04:00:44.319 --> 04:00:49.519
Now let's talk about the negative form of
the past continuous tense.

04:00:49.520 --> 04:00:50.960
Here are some examples.

04:00:51.520 --> 04:00:53.840
‘She was not reading last night.’

04:00:54.560 --> 04:00:57.920
The subject is ‘she’ and so we use ‘was’.

04:00:58.800 --> 04:01:02.880
However, before the ‘verb-ing’, we add
‘not’.

04:01:03.439 --> 04:01:05.839
‘She was not reading last night.’

04:01:06.479 --> 04:01:09.040
I can use a contraction and say,

04:01:09.040 --> 04:01:11.359
‘She wasn't reading last night.’

04:01:12.720 --> 04:01:27.600
‘We were not listening to music this morning.’

04:01:27.600 --> 04:01:27.848
In this case, the subject is ‘we’ and
so we use ‘were’.

04:01:27.847 --> 04:01:28.039
Again ‘not’ comes before the ‘verb-ing’.

04:01:28.039 --> 04:01:28.239
‘We were not listening to music this morning.’

04:01:28.239 --> 04:01:31.120
Again I can use a contraction and say,

04:01:31.120 --> 04:01:33.760
‘We weren't listening to music this morning.’

04:01:34.720 --> 04:01:39.760
And the next one says,
‘He wasn't watching TV when his dad came

04:01:39.760 --> 04:01:40.000
home.’

04:01:40.960 --> 04:01:44.800
In this example, the contraction is already
there for you,

04:01:44.800 --> 04:01:46.400
‘He wasn't watching TV’.

04:01:47.279 --> 04:01:48.960
You'll notice the word ‘when’.

04:01:49.920 --> 04:01:55.760
Remember ‘when’ + ‘a past simple tense
verb’ shows an interrupting action,

04:01:56.319 --> 04:02:00.239
so, ‘When his dad came home he wasn't watching
TV.’

04:02:00.880 --> 04:02:02.160
He was doing something else.

04:02:03.040 --> 04:02:04.239
And finally,

04:02:04.239 --> 04:02:07.199
‘They weren't talking while the game was
playing.’

04:02:08.000 --> 04:02:10.880
The word ‘while’ is in this sentence.

04:02:10.880 --> 04:02:17.279
Remember that shows 2 past ongoing actions
happening at the same time,

04:02:17.279 --> 04:02:21.040
so ‘While the game was playing they weren't
talking’.

04:02:21.040 --> 04:02:22.319
They were doing something else.

04:02:23.120 --> 04:02:25.120
Let's move on now.

04:02:25.120 --> 04:02:30.080
Let's talk about how to form ‘be’ verb
questions for the past continuous tense.

04:02:30.720 --> 04:02:32.880
Take a look at the first statement.

04:02:32.880 --> 04:02:34.000
It says,

04:02:34.000 --> 04:02:35.600
‘It was raining this morning.’

04:02:36.399 --> 04:02:40.000
In order to turn this into a question, it's
quite easy,

04:02:40.560 --> 04:02:44.240
all we have to do is change the order of the
first two words.

04:02:44.800 --> 04:02:49.760
Instead of ‘It was’, I now say ‘Was
it’ to make it a question.

04:02:50.399 --> 04:02:54.160
You'll notice that the rest of the words stay
in the same place.

04:02:54.960 --> 04:02:56.560
‘Was it raining this morning?’

04:02:57.359 --> 04:03:01.920
You can answer by saying,
‘Yes, it was.’ or ‘No, it wasn't.’

04:03:02.960 --> 04:03:04.640
The next statement says,

04:03:04.640 --> 04:03:07.280
‘They were living there when the fire happened.’

04:03:07.920 --> 04:03:14.000
To turn this into a big question, again we
just switched the order of the first two words.

04:03:14.560 --> 04:03:17.440
Instead of ‘They were’, we say ‘Were
they’.

04:03:18.239 --> 04:03:21.920
And again, the rest of the words can stay
in the same place.

04:03:22.720 --> 04:03:25.280
‘Were they living there when the fire happened?’

04:03:26.000 --> 04:03:27.600
And you can answer by saying,

04:03:27.600 --> 04:03:30.400
‘Yes, they were’ or ‘No, they weren't.’

04:03:31.040 --> 04:03:32.080
Let's continue on.

04:03:33.120 --> 04:03:38.720
Now I'll go into how to make WH questions
for the past continuous tense.

04:03:39.279 --> 04:03:44.559
You'll notice that the examples here all begin
with some WH words.

04:03:44.560 --> 04:03:49.280
For example,
‘what’, ‘where’, ‘why’, and ‘who’.

04:03:50.080 --> 04:03:51.840
Let's take a look at the first question.

04:03:52.800 --> 04:03:54.720
‘What were they doing last night?”

04:03:55.600 --> 04:03:58.240
The subject of this sentence is ‘they’.

04:03:59.199 --> 04:04:04.720
So what you do is after the WH word you put
the proper ‘be’ verb.

04:04:04.720 --> 04:04:06.080
In this case, ‘were’.

04:04:06.960 --> 04:04:08.880
‘What were they doing last night?’

04:04:09.520 --> 04:04:13.200
You'll notice that after the subject comes
the ‘verb-ing’.

04:04:14.160 --> 04:04:16.000
‘What were they doing last night?’

04:04:16.720 --> 04:04:20.800
I can answer by saying,
‘They were playing games’ or

04:04:20.800 --> 04:04:22.080
‘They were reading a book’.

04:04:23.120 --> 04:04:24.399
The next question says,

04:04:25.040 --> 04:04:36.560
‘Where was he working last week?’

04:04:45.920 --> 04:04:49.024
In this case the subject is ‘he’ and so
the be verb to use is ‘was’.

04:04:49.024 --> 04:04:49.061
‘Where was he working last week?’

04:04:49.061 --> 04:04:49.103
I can say, ‘He was working in Canada.’

04:04:49.103 --> 04:04:49.154
‘Why was she crying when she finished the
book?’

04:04:49.154 --> 04:04:51.439
In this case, the subject is ‘she’ and
so I put ‘was’ after ‘why’.

04:04:52.479 --> 04:04:55.199
‘Why was she crying when she finished the
book?’

04:04:55.920 --> 04:05:00.319
I can say, ‘She was crying because the ending
was sad.’

04:05:01.199 --> 04:05:01.840
And finally,

04:05:02.479 --> 04:05:06.639
‘Who were the children staying with while
their mom was working?’

04:05:07.359 --> 04:05:11.199
In this case, ‘the children’ is a ‘they’

04:05:11.199 --> 04:05:13.519
so we follow 'who' with ‘were’.

04:05:14.160 --> 04:05:16.399
‘Who were they’ or

04:05:16.399 --> 04:05:20.639
‘Who were the children staying with while
their mom was working?’

04:05:21.520 --> 04:05:24.720
To answer, I can say, ‘The children’ or

04:05:24.720 --> 04:05:27.040
‘They were staying with their dad.’

04:05:27.840 --> 04:05:28.640
Let's move on.

04:05:29.199 --> 04:05:33.519
In this section, let's do a checkup for the
past continuous tense.

04:05:34.399 --> 04:05:36.239
Take a look at the first sentence.

04:05:37.120 --> 04:05:40.080
‘Last night they were blank at school.’

04:05:40.960 --> 04:05:45.680
I want you to try to fill in the blank with
the negative for the verb ‘stay’.

04:05:46.239 --> 04:05:46.960
‘not stay’

04:05:47.760 --> 04:05:48.880
What do you think it is?

04:05:50.000 --> 04:05:53.279
Remember, for the negative of the past continuous,

04:05:53.840 --> 04:05:59.760
all you have to do is put ‘not’ and then
‘verb-ing’ after the 'be' verb.

04:06:00.479 --> 04:06:09.799
‘They were not staying at school last.’

04:06:09.800 --> 04:06:12.480
‘Last night, they were not staying at school.’

04:06:13.600 --> 04:06:14.800
The next sentence says,

04:06:15.439 --> 04:06:18.639
‘Two days ago you blank soccer.’

04:06:19.359 --> 04:06:22.559
Again try the negative for the verb ‘play’.

04:06:23.840 --> 04:06:27.840
‘Two days ago blank not play soccer.’

04:06:28.640 --> 04:06:32.480
In this case, the first thing that's missing
is the ‘be’ verb.

04:06:33.120 --> 04:06:38.479
If the subject is ‘you’, can you think
of which be verb needs to be put in there?

04:06:39.359 --> 04:06:41.519
The correct answer is ‘were’.

04:06:42.560 --> 04:06:44.800
And then, we say ‘not’.

04:06:45.920 --> 04:06:47.199
What happens after that?

04:06:48.000 --> 04:06:50.079
Remember, ‘verb-ing’.

04:06:51.040 --> 04:06:54.479
So ‘you were not playing’

04:06:55.359 --> 04:06:58.479
‘two days ago, you were not playing soccer’

04:06:59.040 --> 04:07:01.359
You can also use a contraction and say,

04:07:01.359 --> 04:07:03.199
‘You weren't playing soccer.’

04:07:04.080 --> 04:07:08.000
Now try to find the mistake in the next sentence.

04:07:08.000 --> 04:07:10.720
‘Yesterday, she were reading at home.’

04:07:11.800 --> 04:07:12.800
hmmm

04:07:12.800 --> 04:07:19.840
The subject of this sentence is ‘she’
so the ‘be’ verb to use is not ‘were’.

04:07:19.840 --> 04:07:21.840
It's 'was'.

04:07:22.399 --> 04:07:25.279
‘Yesterday, she was reading at home.’

04:07:26.399 --> 04:07:31.279
In the next sentence it says, ‘Tomorrow,
they were seeing their friends.’

04:07:32.600 --> 04:07:33.600
hmmm

04:07:33.600 --> 04:07:35.200
‘They’ and ‘were’

04:07:35.199 --> 04:07:35.840
That's correct.

04:07:36.399 --> 04:07:38.559
And we have the ‘verb-ing’

04:07:39.279 --> 04:07:40.479
So what's the mistake?

04:07:41.279 --> 04:07:44.800
Remember the past continuous is for the past.

04:07:45.359 --> 04:07:48.159
‘Tomorrow’ is not the past.

04:07:48.159 --> 04:07:52.800
So instead, we need to put a word that shows
the past.

04:07:52.800 --> 04:07:55.920
For example, I can say, ‘yesterday’.

04:07:58.080 --> 04:08:00.559
‘Yesterday, they were seeing their friends.’

04:08:01.520 --> 04:08:02.320
Let's move on.

04:08:02.960 --> 04:08:06.319
Now, let's start a checkup of the ‘when’
usage

04:08:06.319 --> 04:08:08.159
of the past continuous tense.

04:08:08.720 --> 04:08:10.480
Take a look at the first example.

04:08:11.120 --> 04:08:16.159
It says, ‘Andrea and John’ blank when
they bank hurt.’

04:08:17.040 --> 04:08:21.120
Remember ‘when’ shows an interrupting
action.

04:08:21.120 --> 04:08:24.479
It needs to be used with the past simple tense.

04:08:24.479 --> 04:08:27.359
So let's first look at the second blank.

04:08:27.359 --> 04:08:29.120
‘When they blank hurt’

04:08:29.840 --> 04:08:32.159
What's the past tense of the verb ‘get’?

04:08:32.800 --> 04:08:34.960
The answer is ‘got’.

04:08:36.319 --> 04:08:41.040
Now let's take a look at the action that was
in progress in the past.

04:08:41.680 --> 04:08:44.000
‘Andrea and John’ or ‘they’

04:08:44.880 --> 04:08:46.480
Well what comes after ‘they’?

04:08:47.520 --> 04:08:48.000
‘were’.

04:08:48.960 --> 04:08:50.800
‘Andrea and John were’

04:08:51.600 --> 04:08:54.960
Then remember we need to add -ing to the verb.

04:08:56.239 --> 04:09:03.040
‘They were skiing’ or ‘Andrea and John
were skiing when they got hurt’.

04:09:04.000 --> 04:09:09.199
The next example says, ‘It blank not raining
when the game blank’.

04:09:09.760 --> 04:09:13.440
And I want you to use the verb ‘start’
for the second blank.

04:09:14.479 --> 04:09:19.199
Take a look ‘when the game blank’ what's
the past tense of ‘start’?

04:09:20.960 --> 04:09:21.600
‘started’

04:09:22.800 --> 04:09:26.239
Now let's look at the first part of the sentence.

04:09:26.239 --> 04:09:27.840
The subject is ‘it’.

04:09:28.960 --> 04:09:31.760
So what ‘be’ verb do we use for 'it'?

04:09:33.520 --> 04:09:33.840
‘was’

04:09:34.640 --> 04:09:37.360
‘It was not raining when the game started.’

04:09:38.159 --> 04:09:41.840
Now find the mistake in the next sentence.

04:09:44.000 --> 04:09:48.000
‘I wasn't study at the library yesterday’.

04:09:48.720 --> 04:09:53.840
The subject here is ‘I’ and so the ‘be’
verb ‘was’ is correct.

04:09:54.560 --> 04:09:59.200
Here there's a contraction, ‘I wasn't’
for ‘I was not’.

04:10:00.159 --> 04:10:02.399
Now the problem is with the verb.

04:10:02.960 --> 04:10:08.159
Remember we need to put ‘–ing’ at the
end of the verb.

04:10:08.159 --> 04:10:11.599
‘I wasn't studying at the library yesterday.’

04:10:12.319 --> 04:10:17.120
And finally,
‘We did meet our friends last weekend.’

04:10:18.159 --> 04:10:24.000
That sounds right, but remember we're doing
the past continuous tense.

04:10:24.000 --> 04:10:24.960
Take a look again.

04:10:25.600 --> 04:10:27.121
The subject is ‘we’.

04:10:27.920 --> 04:10:29.120
We need a ‘be’ verb.

04:10:29.840 --> 04:10:30.319
‘were’

04:10:32.080 --> 04:10:33.040
Then what happens?

04:10:33.760 --> 04:10:38.640
Remember, we need to add an ‘-ing’ to
the end of the verb,

04:10:39.199 --> 04:10:44.239
so we take out ‘did’ and say,
‘We were meeting our friends last weekend.’

04:10:45.040 --> 04:10:46.159
Let's move on.

04:10:46.159 --> 04:10:51.840
Now, for this checkup, we'll look at the ‘while’
usage of the past continuous tense.

04:10:52.479 --> 04:10:54.239
Take a look at the first example.

04:10:54.800 --> 04:10:58.159
‘While I blank someone blank my bike.’

04:10:58.960 --> 04:11:02.640
When we use ‘while’ in the past continuous
tense,

04:11:02.640 --> 04:11:07.280
we're showing that two actions happened at
the same time in the past

04:11:07.279 --> 04:11:10.880
or they were happening at the same time in
the past.

04:11:10.880 --> 04:11:15.359
So we need to use the past continuous for
both actions.

04:11:16.479 --> 04:11:18.239
‘While I blank’

04:11:18.800 --> 04:11:21.600
I want you to use ‘shop’ in the first
blank.

04:11:22.239 --> 04:11:27.679
Remember, the subject here is ‘I’ so I
need to use the ‘be’ verb ‘was’.

04:11:29.600 --> 04:11:33.680
Then ‘verb-ing’.

04:11:35.760 --> 04:11:37.199
‘While I was shopping’

04:11:38.239 --> 04:11:41.199
Now ‘someone’ can be a ‘he’ or ‘she’.

04:11:41.840 --> 04:11:44.400
Therefore, again we need to use ‘was’

04:11:46.399 --> 04:11:50.080
and then the ‘verb-ing’ of ‘steal’.

04:11:51.120 --> 04:11:54.720
‘While I was shopping, someone was stealing
my bike.’

04:11:55.760 --> 04:11:57.120
The next sentence says,

04:11:57.680 --> 04:11:59.120
‘While he blank’

04:11:59.920 --> 04:12:02.080
I want you to use the verb ‘cook’.

04:12:03.040 --> 04:12:08.640
The subject is ‘he’ and so I need to use
‘was cooking’.

04:12:10.720 --> 04:12:18.960
‘While he was cooking, his girlfriend was
cleaning.’

04:12:20.080 --> 04:12:20.880
Did you get that?

04:12:22.080 --> 04:12:22.880
Let's move on.

04:12:23.439 --> 04:12:26.080
Try to find the mistake in the next sentence.

04:12:29.199 --> 04:12:33.519
‘Jane was looking for us while we get off
the plane.’

04:12:34.720 --> 04:12:37.199
The first part of the sentence is correct.

04:12:37.760 --> 04:12:39.120
‘Jane was looking’

04:12:40.319 --> 04:12:43.120
Now the second part of the sentence.

04:12:43.120 --> 04:12:46.159
Notice it's not in the past continuous tense.

04:12:46.800 --> 04:12:49.279
‘While we get off the plane’

04:12:49.279 --> 04:12:54.319
So what we need to do is say, ‘were getting’.

04:12:56.640 --> 04:13:00.800
‘Jane was looking for us while we were getting
off the plane.’

04:13:02.000 --> 04:13:07.520
The next sentence says, 'I was watching TV
while my wife sleep’

04:13:08.800 --> 04:13:13.760
Again this part of the sentence did not use
the past continuous tense.

04:13:14.560 --> 04:13:22.720
My wife is a ‘she’ and so I need to say
‘was sleeping’.

04:13:23.279 --> 04:13:26.639
‘I was watching TV while my wife was sleeping.’

04:13:27.520 --> 04:13:28.800
Great job, everyone.

04:13:28.800 --> 04:13:29.600
Let's move on.

04:13:30.560 --> 04:13:33.121
Good job, everybody in learning the past&nbsp;&nbsp;

04:13:33.120 --> 04:13:34.159
continuous
tense.

04:13:34.800 --> 04:13:38.720
This tense can be a little difficult and a
little tricky.

04:13:39.279 --> 04:13:42.559
Especially when it comes to the ‘when’
and ‘while’ usage.

04:13:43.120 --> 04:13:46.880
It'll take some practice to really master
it, but I know you can do it.

04:13:47.439 --> 04:13:53.839
Keep studying English and I'll see you in
the next video.&nbsp;

04:13:59.120 --> 04:14:00.080
Hi, everybody.

04:14:00.080 --> 04:14:01.279
I'm Esther.

04:14:01.279 --> 04:14:04.800
In this video, I will introduce the past perfect
tense.

04:14:05.439 --> 04:14:11.359
This tense is used to describe an action that
took place at a specific time in the past.

04:14:12.080 --> 04:14:16.960
This tense can be a little tricky,
but don't worry I will guide you through it.

04:14:16.960 --> 04:14:20.159
There's so much to learn and it's a very important
tense.

04:14:20.159 --> 04:14:21.840
So keep watching.

04:14:24.560 --> 04:14:28.400
Let's take a look at the first usage of the
past perfect tense.

04:14:29.120 --> 04:14:32.960
This tense can be used to describe an action
in the past

04:14:32.960 --> 04:14:35.840
that happened before another action in the
past.

04:14:36.479 --> 04:14:37.759
Here are some examples.

04:14:38.640 --> 04:14:41.600
‘I have visited China before I moved there.’

04:14:42.399 --> 04:14:45.679
No matter what the subject you follow with
‘had’,

04:14:45.680 --> 04:14:46.640
So that's easy.

04:14:47.199 --> 04:14:49.679
‘I had’
‘Steve had’

04:14:49.680 --> 04:14:51.840
‘The plane had’
and ‘We had’.

04:14:52.800 --> 04:14:56.239
Then, we follow with the past participle of
the verb.

04:14:56.800 --> 04:14:58.560
In this case, it's ‘visited’.

04:14:59.359 --> 04:15:00.960
‘I had visited China.’

04:15:01.680 --> 04:15:06.080
Now you'll notice that the second verb is
in the past simple tense.

04:15:06.080 --> 04:15:07.199
‘I moved there.’

04:15:07.760 --> 04:15:10.640
And I'll talk about that a little bit more
later on.

04:15:11.760 --> 04:15:13.199
‘Steve had bought the book.’

04:15:13.760 --> 04:15:18.080
Again, ‘subject’, ‘had’ and ‘past
participle’.

04:15:18.080 --> 04:15:19.840
In this case, the verb is ‘buy’.

04:15:20.800 --> 04:15:24.320
‘Steve had bought the book before he read
it.’

04:15:25.040 --> 04:15:28.880
Again, we have the simple tense of ‘read’
which is ‘read’.

04:15:29.920 --> 04:15:34.720
And finally, ‘The plane had left by the
time I got to the airport.’

04:15:35.359 --> 04:15:40.239
Again, the first part of this sentence is
in the past perfect tense.

04:15:40.239 --> 04:15:41.679
‘The plane had left’.

04:15:42.319 --> 04:15:45.040
This is the past participle of ‘leave’.

04:15:45.760 --> 04:15:49.360
The second verb says, ‘I got to the airport.’

04:15:49.359 --> 04:15:51.759
‘got’ is the past tense of ‘get’.

04:15:52.640 --> 04:15:58.560
Now what these three sentences have in common
is that you'll see, ‘before’.

04:15:59.359 --> 04:16:01.199
‘before’ or ‘by the time’.

04:16:01.760 --> 04:16:03.280
They all mean the same thing.

04:16:04.399 --> 04:16:08.559
The verb that is in the past perfect tense
happened first.

04:16:09.359 --> 04:16:12.719
The verb that's in the past simple tense happen
after.

04:16:13.359 --> 04:16:16.000
So again, for the first example.

04:16:16.000 --> 04:16:19.520
‘before I move there’
That happened later.

04:16:20.239 --> 04:16:23.359
Before that, ‘I had already visited China.’

04:16:24.000 --> 04:16:25.520
Do you understand how that works?

04:16:26.239 --> 04:16:28.319
Let's take a look at the last example.

04:16:29.040 --> 04:16:32.479
‘When they arrived, we had already started
the game.’

04:16:33.120 --> 04:16:36.239
So maybe they were late or something had happened.

04:16:36.239 --> 04:16:40.719
But ‘When they arrived’, this is the past
simple tense.

04:16:40.720 --> 04:16:43.199
So this happened second.

04:16:43.199 --> 04:16:45.439
‘We had already started the game.’

04:16:46.319 --> 04:16:49.279
This action had already started.

04:16:49.279 --> 04:16:51.679
It started before this action.

04:16:52.720 --> 04:16:53.520
Let's move on.

04:16:54.080 --> 04:16:59.519
Earlier I mentioned that the past perfect
tense can be used to describe an action

04:16:59.520 --> 04:17:03.520
that happened in the past before another action
in the past.

04:17:04.080 --> 04:17:08.399
We can do the same thing but also emphasize
the duration.

04:17:08.399 --> 04:17:10.719
How long that first action happened.

04:17:11.279 --> 04:17:14.479
We do this by using four and a duration.

04:17:15.120 --> 04:17:16.000
Let's take a look.

04:17:16.960 --> 04:17:21.199
‘I had owned my computer for two months
before it broke.’

04:17:22.000 --> 04:17:24.479
This is very similar to the first usage.

04:17:25.359 --> 04:17:29.519
‘I had’ and the past participle of the
verb.

04:17:30.399 --> 04:17:34.159
This part shows the action that happened earlier
in the past.

04:17:34.880 --> 04:17:36.880
The second part, ‘it broke’.

04:17:37.520 --> 04:17:41.600
The past simple tense verb shows the action
in the past

04:17:41.600 --> 04:17:44.080
that happened later than the first action.

04:17:44.960 --> 04:17:50.080
However, you'll notice that this sentence
has a duration, ‘for two months’.

04:17:50.800 --> 04:17:54.640
‘I had owned my computer for two months
before it broke.’

04:17:55.439 --> 04:18:00.399
All I'm doing here is showing how long the
first action had been true.

04:18:01.120 --> 04:18:03.199
Let's take a look at the next example.

04:18:04.080 --> 04:18:08.880
‘Jim had been lonely for a long time until
he got a puppy.’

04:18:09.600 --> 04:18:14.480
Again, we have subject ‘had’, past participle.

04:18:14.479 --> 04:18:18.879
And then we have the past simple ‘he got
a puppy’.

04:18:19.760 --> 04:18:25.040
All we're doing here is emphasizing
how long first action had been true.

04:18:25.600 --> 04:18:28.400
He had been lonely for a long time.

04:18:29.120 --> 04:18:34.000
That is until the later action, ‘he got
a puppy.’

04:18:34.000 --> 04:18:40.239
And finally, ‘She and I had been friends
for many years before she became my wife.’

04:18:41.520 --> 04:18:44.960
The first part of the sentence is the past
perfect.

04:18:44.960 --> 04:18:48.399
It happened before she became my wife.

04:18:49.120 --> 04:18:54.000
But I want to explain how long that had been
true for many years.

04:18:54.800 --> 04:18:56.000
Let's move on.

04:18:56.000 --> 04:19:00.800
Now I'll introduce how to form the negative
in the past perfect tense.

04:19:01.359 --> 04:19:02.399
Take a look at the board.

04:19:03.040 --> 04:19:09.120
The first sentence says, ‘I had not eaten
at the restaurant before I went yesterday.’

04:19:09.840 --> 04:19:16.239
Again, we have the past perfect tense here
and the past simple tense here.

04:19:16.239 --> 04:19:20.080
This one is the action that happened earlier
in the past

04:19:20.080 --> 04:19:24.720
And this one over here is the action that
happened later in the past.

04:19:25.439 --> 04:19:31.599
However, because this is the negative,
what I'm going to do is add a 'not' between

04:19:31.600 --> 04:19:35.040
the ‘had’ and the past participle of the
verb.

04:19:35.760 --> 04:19:38.640
So I say, ‘I have not eaten’.

04:19:39.199 --> 04:19:41.279
Or I can use the contraction

04:19:41.279 --> 04:19:46.479
and say, ‘I hadn't eaten at the restaurant
before I went yesterday.’

04:19:47.199 --> 04:19:49.279
The next sentence is very similar.’

04:19:49.840 --> 04:19:53.920
‘She had not been to the circus before she
went last week.’

04:19:54.720 --> 04:19:58.320
Here's the action that happened earlier in
the past,

04:19:58.319 --> 04:20:02.000
and here's the action that happened later
in the past.

04:20:02.560 --> 04:20:05.680
However, again, because it's negative,

04:20:05.680 --> 04:20:10.800
I put a 'not' between ‘had’ and the past
participle of the verb.

04:20:11.520 --> 04:20:16.800
Also, I can use the contraction and say,
‘She hadn't been to the circus.’

04:20:18.159 --> 04:20:19.680
The next sentence says,

04:20:19.680 --> 04:20:24.800
‘The cat hadn't chased the bird for very
long before it flew away.’

04:20:25.520 --> 04:20:28.000
Remember, we can show duration,

04:20:28.000 --> 04:20:30.960
or how long the first action was true.

04:20:30.960 --> 04:20:33.439
by using 'for' and a duration.

04:20:34.399 --> 04:20:36.639
Because this is the negative form,

04:20:36.640 --> 04:20:43.920
again, I use 'had not' after the subject and
before the past participle of the verb

04:20:43.920 --> 04:20:47.920
In this case, the contraction ‘hadn't’
is already there for you.

04:20:49.040 --> 04:20:53.840
‘We hadn't known each other for three months
before we married.’

04:20:54.399 --> 04:20:56.319
That's a pretty short time.

04:20:56.319 --> 04:21:00.080
It shows the duration by saying ‘for’,
How long?

04:21:00.080 --> 04:21:00.880
‘three months’

04:21:01.680 --> 04:21:02.480
Let's move on.

04:21:03.120 --> 04:21:08.239
Now, let's take a look at questions using
‘had’ in the past perfect tense.

04:21:08.880 --> 04:21:11.040
Take a look at the first sentence.

04:21:11.040 --> 04:21:14.399
It says, ‘She had eaten lunch by noon.’

04:21:15.199 --> 04:21:18.960
Now, to turn this into a question is quite
easy.

04:21:18.960 --> 04:21:22.399
All you have to do is change the order of
the first two words.

04:21:22.960 --> 04:21:26.319
So instead of ‘she had’, we say ‘Had
she’.

04:21:27.040 --> 04:21:29.040
‘Had she eaten lunch by noon?’

04:21:30.000 --> 04:21:32.319
You can say,
‘Yes, she had.’

04:21:32.319 --> 04:21:34.000
or ‘No, she hadn't.’

04:21:34.880 --> 04:21:38.560
The next sentence says,
‘It had rained before they left.’

04:21:39.279 --> 04:21:43.599
Again simply switched the order of the first
two words.

04:21:43.600 --> 04:21:47.520
Instead of ‘It had’, say ‘Had it’
to make a question.

04:21:48.399 --> 04:21:50.319
‘Had it rained before they left?’

04:21:51.199 --> 04:21:54.479
To reply you can say,
‘Yes, it had.’

04:21:54.479 --> 04:21:56.399
or ‘No, it hadn't.’

04:21:57.120 --> 04:21:59.199
Let's move on now.

04:21:59.199 --> 04:22:03.840
I'll go into how to form ‘WH’ questions
in the past perfect tense.

04:22:04.399 --> 04:22:05.199
Let's take a look.

04:22:06.239 --> 04:22:10.639
Here we see at the beginning
of each question a 'WH' word.

04:22:11.359 --> 04:22:15.040
‘where’, ‘who’, ‘what’,
and ‘how’.

04:22:16.399 --> 04:22:18.399
Let's take a look at the first question.

04:22:19.359 --> 04:22:21.599
‘Where had he traveled before?’

04:22:22.399 --> 04:22:26.799
You'll notice that after each ‘WH’ word,
we have ‘had’.

04:22:27.760 --> 04:22:32.720
And then the subject and then the
past participle of the verb.

04:22:33.439 --> 04:22:35.599
‘Where had he traveled before?’

04:22:36.880 --> 04:22:40.800
The next question says,
‘Who had she talked to before?’

04:22:41.600 --> 04:22:44.800
This is the same thing the ‘WH’ word

04:22:45.359 --> 04:22:48.239
‘had she’ and then the past participle.

04:22:49.040 --> 04:22:55.439
You'll notice here that we have the word ‘before’,
but we didn't write a specific point in time.

04:22:56.239 --> 04:22:59.840
If you see that it simply means before now.

04:23:00.399 --> 04:23:04.799
The next question says,
‘What had he eaten before lunch?’

04:23:05.760 --> 04:23:11.280
Again we follow the same formula, however,
here it says ‘lunch for you'.

04:23:12.239 --> 04:23:13.679
The last one says,

04:23:13.680 --> 04:23:17.600
‘How long had she known him before she dated
him?’

04:23:18.560 --> 04:23:24.640
Again how long ‘had’ + ‘subject’ and
then the past participle.

04:23:25.439 --> 04:23:27.839
Let's take a look at how&nbsp;
to answer these questions.

04:23:29.359 --> 04:23:31.359
‘Where had he traveled before?’

04:23:32.239 --> 04:23:34.399
‘He had traveled to Europe.’

04:23:34.399 --> 04:23:35.839
is one possible answer.

04:23:37.199 --> 04:23:39.279
‘Who had she talked to before?’

04:23:40.159 --> 04:23:43.599
Here I can say, ‘She had talked to her brother.’

04:23:45.199 --> 04:23:47.599
‘What had he eaten before lunch?’

04:23:48.479 --> 04:23:51.040
‘He had eaten sushi before lunch.’

04:23:51.760 --> 04:23:56.560
And finally, ‘How long had she known him
before she dated him?’

04:23:57.279 --> 04:23:59.840
‘She had known him for three years.’

04:23:59.840 --> 04:24:01.680
That is one possible answer.

04:24:02.399 --> 04:24:03.279
Let's move on.

04:24:04.239 --> 04:24:10.479
Now let's take a look at some practice exercises
for the basic usage of the past perfect tense.

04:24:11.040 --> 04:24:12.720
Take a look at the first sentence.

04:24:13.359 --> 04:24:17.279
‘I blank for six hours before I had a break.’

04:24:17.920 --> 04:24:19.600
The verb here is ‘work’.

04:24:20.399 --> 04:24:23.519
Remember, we need to say ‘I had’.

04:24:23.520 --> 04:24:26.240
No matter what the subject is, say ‘had’.

04:24:28.720 --> 04:24:32.080
And then, you take the past participle of
the verb.

04:24:32.640 --> 04:24:38.080
In this case, we would say ‘worked’.

04:24:38.080 --> 04:24:41.920
‘I had worked for six hours before I had
a break.’

04:24:42.720 --> 04:24:46.080
For the next sentence, I want you to try the
negative form.

04:24:47.120 --> 04:24:51.840
‘We blank TV before we listened to the radio.’

04:24:53.040 --> 04:24:56.880
Remember, for the negative form, we say ‘had
not’

04:24:56.880 --> 04:24:59.199
or we use the contraction, ‘hadn't’.

04:25:01.359 --> 04:25:02.479
‘We hadn’t’.

04:25:03.199 --> 04:25:05.840
And then, we need the past participle.

04:25:08.960 --> 04:25:13.600
‘We hadn't watched TV before we listened
to the radio.’

04:25:14.479 --> 04:25:17.120
Now find the mistake in the next sentence.

04:25:19.680 --> 04:25:24.159
‘Reggie had it be to Mexico before he went
to Peru.’

04:25:24.880 --> 04:25:30.400
Well, we have the subject here
and for the negative, ‘hadn't’ is correct.

04:25:31.120 --> 04:25:35.760
However, we need the past participle of the
verb ‘be’.

04:25:36.560 --> 04:25:38.320
So the correct answer is,

04:25:38.319 --> 04:25:42.559
‘Reggie hadn't been to Mexico before he
went to Peru.’

04:25:43.520 --> 04:25:49.520
And finally, ‘Sally and Jan or they had
do their job.’

04:25:50.040 --> 04:25:51.040
Hmm.

04:25:51.040 --> 04:25:53.519
Remember, we need the past participle.

04:25:54.159 --> 04:25:55.599
We don't say do.

04:25:55.600 --> 04:25:56.880
We say ‘done’.

04:25:57.920 --> 04:26:02.480
‘Sally and Jan had done their job before
they watched TV.’

04:26:03.520 --> 04:26:04.560
Let's move on.

04:26:04.560 --> 04:26:08.400
In this checkup, we'll take a look at some
practice exercises

04:26:08.399 --> 04:26:12.319
for the past perfect tense that describes
how long.

04:26:12.319 --> 04:26:14.239
Let's take a look at the first sentence.

04:26:15.040 --> 04:26:19.760
‘You blank at the park for three hours before
you came home.’

04:26:20.720 --> 04:26:23.760
Remember, we start with the subject and then
‘had’.

04:26:24.560 --> 04:26:26.240
So I'm going to add that here,

04:26:27.040 --> 04:26:30.479
then we need the past participle of the verb
‘be’.

04:26:31.279 --> 04:26:32.719
And that is ‘been’.

04:26:34.159 --> 04:26:38.479
‘You had been at the park for three hours
before you came home.’

04:26:39.520 --> 04:26:40.720
The next sentence says,

04:26:41.279 --> 04:26:45.199
‘They blank for six hours before they took
a break.’

04:26:46.080 --> 04:26:51.519
Again, no matter what the subject,
we have ‘had’ and then the past participle.

04:26:52.080 --> 04:26:54.239
So the answer is,

04:26:54.239 --> 04:27:00.080
‘They had studied for six hours before they
took a break.’

04:27:00.960 --> 04:27:04.080
Now, find the mistake in the next sentence.

04:27:04.080 --> 04:27:06.960
It's a little bit longer so it might take
you a while.

04:27:08.640 --> 04:27:14.000
‘They had been known each other for ten
years before they had their first fight.’

04:27:14.960 --> 04:27:16.239
Can you find the mistake?

04:27:17.199 --> 04:27:21.120
Well, we have the subject and ‘had’,
but check this out.

04:27:21.120 --> 04:27:24.000
There are two past participles here.

04:27:24.000 --> 04:27:25.840
We need to get rid of one of them.

04:27:27.279 --> 04:27:33.599
We can take out this verb and say,
‘They had known each other for ten years

04:27:33.600 --> 04:27:35.520
before they had their first fight.’

04:27:36.800 --> 04:27:43.360
The next sentence says, ‘I have played soccer
for many years before I scored my first goal.’

04:27:44.560 --> 04:27:47.920
This sentence doesn't look wrong at first.

04:27:47.920 --> 04:27:51.760
But remember, in the past perfect tense, we
need to say ‘had’.

04:27:52.479 --> 04:27:59.040
‘I had played soccer for many years before
I scored my first goal.’

04:28:00.080 --> 04:28:01.279
Good job, everybody.

