04:28:34.159 --> 04:28:38.479
In this video, I will introduce the past perfect
continuous tense.

04:28:39.040 --> 04:28:42.800
It's a great tense that helps you express
an ongoing action

04:28:42.800 --> 04:28:46.720
in the past continuing up to another point
in the past.

04:28:46.720 --> 04:28:49.840
There's a lot to learn, so keep watching.

04:28:52.319 --> 04:28:58.639
One usage of the past perfect continuous tense
is to talk about an ongoing action in the

04:28:58.640 --> 04:29:01.920
past
that continued up to another point in the

04:29:01.920 --> 04:29:02.319
past.

04:29:02.880 --> 04:29:06.480
You can use ‘for’ and a duration to talk
about

04:29:06.479 --> 04:29:08.879
how long that action was in progress.

04:29:09.439 --> 04:29:10.719
Here are some examples.

04:29:11.359 --> 04:29:16.159
‘I had been waiting for the bus for two
hours before it arrived.’

04:29:16.800 --> 04:29:18.640
You'll notice that at the beginning.

04:29:18.640 --> 04:29:23.040
It doesn't matter what the subject is, we
follow with ‘had been’.

04:29:23.600 --> 04:29:27.520
For example, ‘I had been’,
‘Chuck had been’,

04:29:27.520 --> 04:29:29.680
And ‘Tom and Kim had been.’

04:29:30.479 --> 04:29:33.199
And then we follow with the verb ‘-ing’.

04:29:33.920 --> 04:29:34.399
‘waiting’.

04:29:35.040 --> 04:29:36.880
‘I had been waiting.’

04:29:36.880 --> 04:29:40.319
Now this is the ongoing action that happened
first.

04:29:41.040 --> 04:29:44.880
Again, four and two hours shows the duration.

04:29:45.680 --> 04:29:48.720
The second part says, ‘it arrived’.

04:29:48.720 --> 04:29:51.680
This verb is in the past simple tense.

04:29:51.680 --> 04:29:54.240
Therefore, that is the second action.

04:29:54.239 --> 04:30:00.960
It's the action that this first action happened
until this action happened,

04:30:00.960 --> 04:30:04.399
so again,
‘I had been waiting for the bus,’ happened

04:30:04.399 --> 04:30:05.279
first.

04:30:05.279 --> 04:30:08.880
And then, it happened until the bus arrived.

04:30:10.399 --> 04:30:14.639
‘Chuck had been cooking,’
Again, that part's easy.

04:30:14.640 --> 04:30:19.360
No matter what’s the subject, we say ‘had
been’ and then verb ‘-ing’.

04:30:20.239 --> 04:30:26.800
Again, I can show how long Chuck had been
cooking by saying ‘for an hour’, showing

04:30:26.800 --> 04:30:28.320
the
duration.

04:30:28.319 --> 04:30:32.000
And then, I finished by saying, ‘before
he finished’.

04:30:32.000 --> 04:30:35.760
He had been cooking up to this point in the
past.

04:30:36.880 --> 04:30:43.120
Finally, ‘Tom and Kim had been walking,’
This part should be familiar to you by now,

04:30:43.760 --> 04:30:46.880
‘for an hour’
Again, that shows duration.

04:30:47.439 --> 04:30:48.879
‘before they rested.’

04:30:49.439 --> 04:30:55.040
So they had been walking for an hour before
they took a break.

04:30:55.040 --> 04:30:56.399
Before they rested.

04:30:56.960 --> 04:30:57.760
Let's move on.

04:30:58.640 --> 04:31:04.800
The past perfect continuous tense is also
used to express cause and effect in the

04:31:04.800 --> 04:31:05.279
past.

04:31:05.920 --> 04:31:10.880
The verb that's in the past perfect continuous
tense shows the cause,

04:31:10.880 --> 04:31:12.239
why something happened.

04:31:12.800 --> 04:31:17.840
We can use ‘because’ or ‘so’ to show
the cause and effect.

04:31:17.840 --> 04:31:18.960
Here, I'll explain.

04:31:19.840 --> 04:31:23.840
‘Jason was tired because he had been jogging.’

04:31:24.560 --> 04:31:27.760
The first part of the sentence is in the past
tense.

04:31:28.399 --> 04:31:33.040
‘Jason was tired,’
However, we see ‘why?’

04:31:33.040 --> 04:31:36.640
Well, because, ‘he had been jogging’.

04:31:36.640 --> 04:31:41.120
The second part of this sentence is in the
past perfect continuous tense.

04:31:41.680 --> 04:31:45.040
‘he had been’, remember no matter what
the subject,

04:31:45.040 --> 04:31:49.519
we follow with ‘had been’ and jogging
– ‘verb -ing’.

04:31:50.159 --> 04:31:55.359
‘he had been jogging’
This shows why Jason was tired.

04:31:56.319 --> 04:32:01.840
The next sentence says,
‘The pavement’ or it ‘was wet because

04:32:01.840 --> 04:32:02.960
it had been raining.’

04:32:03.840 --> 04:32:09.120
Similar to the first sentence, ‘it had been
raining’ shows the cause.

04:32:09.120 --> 04:32:10.800
Why was the pavement wet?

04:32:11.439 --> 04:32:15.359
‘The pavement was wet because it had been
raining.’

04:32:16.640 --> 04:32:19.520
In this sentence, we see a little difference.

04:32:19.520 --> 04:32:25.200
‘The children had been playing’
Again, this is the past perfect continuous

04:32:25.199 --> 04:32:25.519
tense.

04:32:26.239 --> 04:32:31.439
‘had been playing’
The second part says, ‘the room was a mess’.

04:32:31.439 --> 04:32:35.679
So here, instead of ‘because’ like the
first two sentences,

04:32:35.680 --> 04:32:37.200
I used ‘so’.

04:32:37.199 --> 04:32:40.960
So the order has been changed but the meaning
is the same.

04:32:41.840 --> 04:32:47.920
This, ‘the children had been playing’
is why the room was a mess.

04:32:47.920 --> 04:32:51.680
This is the cause and this is the effect.

04:32:52.479 --> 04:32:53.279
Let's move on.

04:32:54.319 --> 04:32:59.120
Now let's go into the negative form of the
past perfect continuous tense.

04:32:59.760 --> 04:33:01.920
Here are some examples.

04:33:01.920 --> 04:33:05.520
‘I had not been working for a day before
I quit.’

04:33:06.240 --> 04:33:11.119
So no matter what the subject ‘I’, ‘you’,
‘she’, or ‘it’,

04:33:11.760 --> 04:33:18.000
just like in the affirmative, we say ‘had’,
but after the ‘had’, in the negative form,

04:33:18.000 --> 04:33:20.320
we add ‘not’.
‘had not’

04:33:20.879 --> 04:33:25.359
‘had not’
or you can use the contraction ‘hadn't’.

04:33:25.359 --> 04:33:28.638
Which is a combination of ‘had’ and ‘not’
together.

04:33:29.680 --> 04:33:34.401
‘I had not been working’
The rest of the sentence is the same.

04:33:34.400 --> 04:33:40.240
‘been + verb -ing’
‘I had not been working for a day before

04:33:40.240 --> 04:33:40.799
I quit.’

04:33:41.920 --> 04:33:46.799
The next sentence says,
‘You had not been cutting onions for long

04:33:46.799 --> 04:33:47.920
before you cried.’

04:33:48.561 --> 04:33:52.081
Again, the ‘not’ goes between ‘had’
and ‘been’.

04:33:53.520 --> 04:33:57.920
‘She hadn't been studying for long when
she fell asleep.’

04:33:57.920 --> 04:33:59.600
Here, we have the contraction.

04:34:00.719 --> 04:34:04.160
And finally,
‘It hadn't been snowing for long when it

04:34:04.160 --> 04:34:04.560
stopped.’

04:34:05.199 --> 04:34:08.240
Again, we have the contraction for ‘had
not’ here.

04:34:09.039 --> 04:34:12.639
You'll notice that in the first two sentences,
I used ‘before’.

04:34:13.199 --> 04:34:15.279
And in the last two, I used ‘when’.

04:34:16.240 --> 04:34:20.400
Either one can be used to show when the first
action stopped.

04:34:21.119 --> 04:34:21.920
Let's move on.

04:34:22.639 --> 04:34:28.639
Now let's go into how to form basic questions
in the past perfect continuous tense.

04:34:29.279 --> 04:34:30.879
Here is the first example.

04:34:31.680 --> 04:34:35.280
‘He had been driving all day before he arrived.’

04:34:35.840 --> 04:34:41.520
Now, to turn this into a question, all we
have to do is change the order of the first

04:34:41.520 --> 04:34:42.241
two words.

04:34:42.799 --> 04:34:48.401
Instead of ‘He had’, now I can say, ‘Had
he’, in order to form a question.

04:34:49.199 --> 04:34:53.840
‘Had he been driving all day before he arrived?’

04:34:53.840 --> 04:34:58.639
The next sentence says,
‘The dog had been barking because it was

04:34:58.639 --> 04:34:59.119
scared.’

04:34:59.840 --> 04:35:02.401
In this case, the subject is ‘The dog’.

04:35:03.199 --> 04:35:04.879
And then we follow with ‘had’.

04:35:05.680 --> 04:35:09.520
To turn this into a question, again, we switch
the order.

04:35:10.240 --> 04:35:14.000
‘Had the dog been barking because it was
scared?’

04:35:14.639 --> 04:35:20.080
You'll notice that in the question, the rest
of the words stay in the same place.

04:35:20.959 --> 04:35:26.160
Now, in the first question, we're asking how
long an action happened,

04:35:26.160 --> 04:35:28.879
or how long it was ongoing in the past.

04:35:29.439 --> 04:35:33.119
And in this question, we ask about cause and
effect.

04:35:33.760 --> 04:35:34.561
Let's move on.

04:35:35.279 --> 04:35:41.519
Now, I'll introduce how to form WH questions
in the past perfect continuous tense.

04:35:42.080 --> 04:35:44.240
Take a look at these examples.

04:35:44.240 --> 04:35:47.519
You'll notice that they all start with a WH
word.

04:35:48.080 --> 04:35:51.279
Why, where, what, and who.

04:35:52.160 --> 04:35:55.760
You might also have noticed that after we
have ‘had’.

04:35:56.400 --> 04:35:58.718
‘Why had’
‘Where had’

04:35:58.719 --> 04:36:00.719
‘What had’
and ‘Who had’

04:36:01.680 --> 04:36:05.520
In the first question, after that comes the
subject.

04:36:06.240 --> 04:36:10.799
‘Why had you’
And then ‘been + verb -ing’

04:36:11.520 --> 04:36:15.200
And that's the same pattern we follow for
all of these sentences.

04:36:15.760 --> 04:36:19.280
So ‘Why had you been studying so much?’

04:36:19.279 --> 04:36:24.080
I can answer by saying,
‘I had been studying so much because I have

04:36:24.080 --> 04:36:24.560
a test.’

04:36:26.080 --> 04:36:29.359
‘Where had you been traveling before you
came here?’

04:36:30.160 --> 04:36:33.680
I can say,
‘I had been traveling through Asia.’

04:36:35.279 --> 04:36:39.039
‘What had they been playing before they
played soccer?’

04:36:39.760 --> 04:36:42.879
I can answer, ‘They had been playing baseball.’

04:36:43.600 --> 04:36:48.321
And finally,
‘Who had she been talking to before she

04:36:48.320 --> 04:36:49.039
left home?’

04:36:49.680 --> 04:36:53.200
I can answer, ‘She had been talking to her
boyfriend.’

04:36:54.000 --> 04:36:54.799
Let's move on.

04:36:55.600 --> 04:36:59.920
Let's start a checkup for the past perfect
continuous tense.

04:36:59.920 --> 04:37:02.080
Take a look at the first sentence.

04:37:02.080 --> 04:37:07.039
It says, ‘They __ for a long time before
they went home.’

04:37:07.920 --> 04:37:11.760
Try to fill in the blank with the verb ‘work’
in this tense.

04:37:13.520 --> 04:37:18.799
Remember, no matter what the subject,
we follow the subject with ‘had been’.

04:37:19.840 --> 04:37:22.719
So we say, ‘They had been’.

04:37:23.840 --> 04:37:25.199
What happens to the verb?

04:37:25.760 --> 04:37:27.840
Remember, we add ‘-ing’.

04:37:30.400 --> 04:37:36.798
So the sentence is, ‘They had been working
for a long time before they went home.’

04:37:37.840 --> 04:37:40.401
Now, take a look at the second sentence.

04:37:40.959 --> 04:37:42.959
I want you to use the negative.

04:37:43.760 --> 04:37:48.561
‘I __ TV for a year before I started again.’

04:37:49.680 --> 04:37:54.321
Remember, the negative form for this tense
starts with the subject

04:37:54.320 --> 04:37:56.320
and then ‘had not been’.

04:37:59.039 --> 04:38:01.439
Or I can use the contraction ‘hadn't’.

04:38:02.080 --> 04:38:07.840
‘I hadn't been’
And then again, verb ‘-ing’.

04:38:09.039 --> 04:38:14.160
‘I hadn't been watching TV for a year before
I started again.’

04:38:15.119 --> 04:38:18.639
Now, try to find the mistake in this next
sentence.

04:38:21.279 --> 04:38:26.400
‘Gina and I hadn't been do any work before
we started.’

04:38:27.359 --> 04:38:28.240
What's the error?

04:38:29.279 --> 04:38:33.119
You'll notice that the verb does not have
an ‘-ing’.

04:38:36.719 --> 04:38:42.401
To make the sentence correct,
we must say, ‘Gina and I hadn't been doing

04:38:42.400 --> 04:38:44.480
any work before we started.’

04:38:45.439 --> 04:38:47.199
Now, find the mistake here.

04:38:48.320 --> 04:38:53.279
‘He had be watching YouTube because he had
some free time.’

04:38:55.279 --> 04:39:01.519
‘He had’, that's correct, but we need
to change ‘be’ to been’.

04:39:02.400 --> 04:39:04.000
And ‘watching’ is correct.

04:39:04.000 --> 04:39:09.279
So, ‘He had been watching YouTube because
he had some free time.’

04:39:10.000 --> 04:39:10.799
Let's move on.

04:39:11.600 --> 04:39:16.561
Now, let's move on to another checkup of the
past perfect continuous tense.

04:39:17.119 --> 04:39:18.959
Take a look at the first example.

04:39:19.600 --> 04:39:24.241
It says, ‘The company __ employees because
they worked hard.’

04:39:25.039 --> 04:39:29.279
Use the verb ‘promote’ in the past perfect
continuous tense.

04:39:30.480 --> 04:39:34.959
Remember, no matter what the subject, we follow
with ‘had been’.

04:39:35.680 --> 04:39:43.520
So we say, ‘The company had been’ and
then verb ‘-ing’, so ‘promoting’.

04:39:46.959 --> 04:39:51.520
‘The company had been promoting employees
because they worked hard.’

04:39:52.320 --> 04:39:58.638
The next example says, ‘I __ your emails
for a while because they went to the spam

04:39:58.639 --> 04:39:59.119
folder.’

04:39:59.840 --> 04:40:03.440
Here, try to use the negative form with the
verb ‘get’.

04:40:05.199 --> 04:40:10.080
Remember, in the negative form, we say ‘had
not been getting’

04:40:10.959 --> 04:40:15.840
Or the contraction ‘hadn't been getting’.

04:40:17.520 --> 04:40:23.360
‘I hadn't been getting your emails for a
while because they went to the spam folder.’

04:40:24.240 --> 04:40:27.119
Now look for the mistake in the next sentence.

04:40:29.840 --> 04:40:33.840
‘I had been work a lot because I needed
the money.’

04:40:34.480 --> 04:40:35.519
What's the mistake?

04:40:36.240 --> 04:40:41.439
Remember, we need to add ‘-ing’ to the
verb.

04:40:42.400 --> 04:40:46.160
‘I had been working a lot because I needed
the money.’

04:40:47.039 --> 04:40:52.560
The last sentence says,
‘He has been smoking because he was stressed.’

04:40:53.439 --> 04:40:54.638
Can you find the mistake?

04:40:55.920 --> 04:40:59.440
Remember, we're practicing the past perfect
continuous.

04:41:00.000 --> 04:41:05.359
In this case, we need ‘had’ after the
subject, not ‘has’.

