04:42:29.439 --> 04:42:31.599
After that, you have the base verb.

04:42:32.320 --> 04:42:35.840
You can use the ‘be’ verb to talk about
a confirmed plan.

04:42:36.639 --> 04:42:39.039
‘I will be at the library tomorrow.’

04:42:40.320 --> 04:42:43.199
The economy will get better next year.

04:42:43.920 --> 04:42:46.639
In this case, the subject is ‘the economy’.

04:42:47.439 --> 04:42:50.959
Again, we follow with ‘will’ and the base
verb ‘get’.

04:42:51.680 --> 04:42:54.719
‘The economy will get better next year.’

04:42:54.719 --> 04:42:58.879
I'm making a prediction here about something
that will happen in the future.

04:42:59.680 --> 04:43:02.719
And finally, ‘I will help you with your
homework.’

04:43:03.439 --> 04:43:05.839
I'm making a future plan to help you.

04:43:06.561 --> 04:43:09.360
‘I will help you with your homework.’

04:43:09.359 --> 04:43:12.879
It doesn't say when but I am talking about
the future.

04:43:13.439 --> 04:43:14.240
Let's move on.

04:43:15.119 --> 04:43:20.000
You can also use ‘be going to’ to express
a future action.

04:43:20.000 --> 04:43:22.080
It's almost the same as ‘will’.

04:43:22.639 --> 04:43:24.000
Here are some examples.

04:43:24.879 --> 04:43:26.080
‘There's no milk.

04:43:26.719 --> 04:43:28.401
I'm going to buy some.’

04:43:29.119 --> 04:43:33.599
So what you see here is the subject and then
the ‘be’ verb - ‘am’.

04:43:34.320 --> 04:43:35.119
‘I am’

04:43:35.840 --> 04:43:39.119
And then here we used a contraction
‘I'm’.

04:43:39.920 --> 04:43:42.000
‘I'm going to buy some.’

04:43:42.000 --> 04:43:45.840
I made a decision to buy some because there's
no milk.

04:43:46.561 --> 04:43:51.120
The next sentence says,
‘It looks like it's going to snow tomorrow.’

04:43:51.920 --> 04:43:56.535
Here the subject is ‘it’ and so I use
the ‘be’ verb – ‘is’.

04:43:56.535 --> 04:43:56.879
‘it is’

04:43:57.439 --> 04:44:00.638
‘It's’ is the contraction.

04:44:01.520 --> 04:44:05.600
‘It's going to’
And then we use the base verb ‘snow’.

04:44:06.719 --> 04:44:10.639
The word ‘tomorrow’ shows that this is
a future action.

04:44:12.080 --> 04:44:14.879
‘He's going to take a trip in the summer.’

04:44:15.840 --> 04:44:20.160
Because the subject is ‘he’, we use the
‘be’ verb – is.

04:44:20.160 --> 04:44:26.560
And we can use the contraction ‘he's’.
‘he is’ or ‘he's’ going to

04:44:26.561 --> 04:44:28.481
And then the base verb ‘take’

04:44:29.199 --> 04:44:31.519
‘take a trip in the summer’

04:44:31.520 --> 04:44:34.321
Again an action happening in the future.

04:44:34.879 --> 04:44:35.680
Let's move on.

04:44:36.320 --> 04:44:39.279
Now, let's take a look at the negative form
of

04:44:39.279 --> 04:44:40.718
the future simple tense.

04:44:41.359 --> 04:44:45.920
The first example says,
‘Stan will not like his English score.’

04:44:46.561 --> 04:44:51.680
No matter what the subject is,
we follow with ‘will not’ and then the

04:44:51.680 --> 04:44:52.959
base form of the verb.

04:44:53.680 --> 04:44:56.799
‘Stan will not like his English score.’

04:44:58.000 --> 04:45:00.639
‘We won't give you money anymore.’

04:45:01.199 --> 04:45:03.840
In this case, the subject is ‘we’.

04:45:03.840 --> 04:45:06.320
And we follow with the contraction ‘won't’.

04:45:07.039 --> 04:45:10.959
It sounds really different and it's different
from other contractions,

04:45:10.959 --> 04:45:14.080
but ‘won't’ is the contraction for ‘will
not’

04:45:14.639 --> 04:45:18.799
so you can say ‘we will not’ or ‘we
won't’.

04:45:18.799 --> 04:45:19.520
They're the same.

04:45:20.320 --> 04:45:22.560
‘We won't give you money anymore.’

04:45:23.119 --> 04:45:26.959
Again, you notice the base verb ‘give’
after ‘not’.

04:45:28.320 --> 04:45:31.840
‘He is not going to fly until next week.’

04:45:32.719 --> 04:45:35.039
This sentence uses ‘be going to’.

04:45:35.840 --> 04:45:38.160
The subject is ‘he’.

04:45:38.160 --> 04:45:41.119
And therefore the ‘be’ verb we use is
– ‘is’

04:45:42.080 --> 04:45:45.600
However we put a ‘not’ after the ‘be’
verb.

04:45:46.320 --> 04:45:50.638
‘He is not going to …’
And then the base verb.

04:45:51.680 --> 04:45:55.600
‘He is not going to fly until next week.’

04:45:56.561 --> 04:46:01.760
The last sentence says,
‘You are not going to go to the party tonight.’

04:46:02.719 --> 04:46:06.561
The subject is ‘you’ and so we use the
‘be’ verb – ‘are’.

04:46:07.279 --> 04:46:11.359
‘You are not going to go …’
That's the base verb.

04:46:11.359 --> 04:46:13.039
‘… to the party tonight.’

04:46:13.840 --> 04:46:14.959
Let's move on.

04:46:14.959 --> 04:46:20.080
Now let's take a look at how to form basic
questions in the future simple tense.

04:46:21.119 --> 04:46:23.760
The first sentence says,
‘He will play with us.’

04:46:24.879 --> 04:46:29.520
To turn this into a question,
all we have to do is change the order of the

04:46:29.520 --> 04:46:30.481
first two words.

04:46:31.039 --> 04:46:34.240
So ‘He will becomes ‘Will he’.

04:46:34.240 --> 04:46:35.599
‘Will he play with us?’

04:46:36.959 --> 04:46:40.400
‘The next sentence says,
‘He is going to play with us.’

04:46:41.199 --> 04:46:43.119
This one uses ‘be going to’.

04:46:43.840 --> 04:46:45.760
The subject is ‘he’.

04:46:45.760 --> 04:46:48.481
And so the ‘be’ verb to use is – ‘is’.

04:46:49.439 --> 04:46:52.560
Then we have ‘going to’ and then the base
verb.

04:46:53.199 --> 04:46:54.799
‘He is going to play with us.’

04:46:55.760 --> 04:47:00.959
When I make a question, I simply again change
the order of the first two words.

04:47:01.680 --> 04:47:03.840
‘Is he going to play with us?’

04:47:04.719 --> 04:47:09.199
Now if the subject were to be ‘you’ or
‘we’ or ‘they’,

04:47:09.199 --> 04:47:11.039
we would say ‘they are’.

04:47:11.039 --> 04:47:13.600
And so the question would say,
‘Are they'.

04:47:14.400 --> 04:47:16.638
'Are they going to play with them?’

04:47:16.639 --> 04:47:17.440
for example.

04:47:18.240 --> 04:47:23.039
So again, remember, for ‘will’ in the
future simple tense,

04:47:23.039 --> 04:47:27.359
just say ‘will’ subject and then the base
form of the verb.

04:47:28.080 --> 04:47:34.160
However for ‘be going to’ questions,
make sure that you pay attention to the proper

04:47:34.160 --> 04:47:36.959
'be' verb to use
at the beginning of the question.

04:47:37.760 --> 04:47:41.280
To answer the first question,
‘Will he play with us?’

04:47:41.279 --> 04:47:45.199
You can say ‘Yes, he will’ or ‘No, he
won't’.

04:47:46.400 --> 04:47:48.400
‘Is he going to play with us?’

04:47:48.400 --> 04:47:53.439
You can say, ‘Yes, he's going to’ or ‘No,
he isn't going to’.

04:47:54.320 --> 04:47:55.599
Let's move on.

04:47:55.600 --> 04:48:00.481
Let's look at how to form ‘WH’ questions
in the future simple tense.

04:48:01.439 --> 04:48:05.839
If you notice each question begins with a
‘WH’ word.

04:48:05.840 --> 04:48:06.160
Who

04:48:06.799 --> 04:48:07.119
When

04:48:07.680 --> 04:48:08.321
Where

04:48:08.320 --> 04:48:08.959
And What

04:48:10.080 --> 04:48:14.400
The first two sentences use ‘will’ for
the future simple tense.

04:48:15.039 --> 04:48:16.240
‘Who will win the game?’

04:48:17.199 --> 04:48:20.400
To answer I can say,
‘My team will win the game.’

04:48:21.680 --> 04:48:23.360
‘When will they arrive?’

04:48:24.240 --> 04:48:26.240
‘They will arrive in two hours.’

04:48:27.840 --> 04:48:31.279
Now these two sentences have ‘be going to’.

04:48:32.400 --> 04:48:34.400
‘Where is he going to study?’

04:48:35.119 --> 04:48:39.840
In this case, I have the ‘be’ verb – ‘is’
because the subject is ‘he’.

04:48:40.561 --> 04:48:42.481
‘Where is he going to study?’

04:48:43.119 --> 04:48:46.560
I can say, ‘He is going to study at the
library.’

04:48:47.119 --> 04:48:50.400
And finally,
‘What are you going to do?’

04:48:51.119 --> 04:48:55.599
In this case, I use the ‘be’ verb – ‘are’
because the subject is ‘you’.

04:48:56.400 --> 04:48:57.759
‘What are you going to do?’

04:48:58.639 --> 04:49:00.481
‘I am going to take a shower.’

04:49:01.279 --> 04:49:02.080
Let's move on.

04:49:02.639 --> 04:49:07.840
For this checkup let's take a look at the
will usage for the future simple tense.

04:49:08.561 --> 04:49:13.600
The first example says,
‘Jen and Paul [blank] home soon’

04:49:13.600 --> 04:49:14.799
with the verb ‘go’.

04:49:15.760 --> 04:49:19.760
Remember, when using ‘will’ for the future
simple tense,

04:49:19.760 --> 04:49:22.401
it doesn't matter what the subject is.

04:49:22.400 --> 04:49:25.359
We say ‘will’ and then the base verb.

04:49:25.359 --> 04:49:31.759
So here we can say, ‘Jen and Paul’ or
‘They will go home soon’.

04:49:33.119 --> 04:49:36.320
‘I [blank] a scientist after I graduate.’

04:49:37.359 --> 04:49:39.199
Try filling in the blank with ‘be’.

04:49:40.320 --> 04:49:43.679
Again, we simply say ‘will be’.

04:49:44.719 --> 04:49:48.160
‘I will be a scientist after I graduate.’

04:49:49.199 --> 04:49:55.119
Now try this one,
‘We [blank] that because it smells bad.’

04:49:55.119 --> 04:49:58.560
I want you to use the negative form with the
verb ‘eat’.

04:50:00.879 --> 04:50:09.520
Here we say, ‘will not eat’ or remember
we can use the contraction ‘won't’.

04:50:10.400 --> 04:50:16.080
‘We will not eat that’ or ‘We won't
eat that because it smells bad’.

04:50:17.119 --> 04:50:19.840
Now look for the mistake in this sentence.

04:50:22.719 --> 04:50:25.440
‘I will eat a pizza for lunch.’

04:50:26.480 --> 04:50:29.599
Remember, we need the base form of the verb.

04:50:30.320 --> 04:50:33.599
‘I will eat a pizza for lunch.’

04:50:34.879 --> 04:50:37.760
‘Angie and I will playing a game.’

04:50:38.719 --> 04:50:41.760
Again we need the base form of the verb.

04:50:42.480 --> 04:50:46.560
Angie and I will play a game.’

04:50:46.561 --> 04:50:49.840
And finally, ‘Will she be cook dinner?’

04:50:50.719 --> 04:50:51.840
This is a question.

04:50:52.719 --> 04:50:58.719
However we need to say,
‘Will she cook dinner.’

04:50:58.719 --> 04:51:00.879
We do not need a ‘be’ verb here.

04:51:01.600 --> 04:51:02.401
Let's move on.

04:51:03.199 --> 04:51:07.599
Let's practice the ‘be going to’ usage
of the future simple tense.

04:51:08.639 --> 04:51:11.920
‘We [blank] going to _blank_ soccer.’

04:51:12.561 --> 04:51:14.639
I want you to use the verb ‘watch’.

04:51:15.680 --> 04:51:19.680
Remember, for ‘be going to’ in the future
simple tense,

04:51:19.680 --> 04:51:22.719
we start with the subject and then the ‘be’
verb.

04:51:23.439 --> 04:51:25.359
The subject here is ‘we’.

04:51:25.359 --> 04:51:27.359
So we need the ‘be’ verb – ‘are’.

04:51:28.160 --> 04:51:32.879
‘We are going to’ and then the base verb
‘watch’.

04:51:35.199 --> 04:51:37.599
‘We are going to watch soccer.’

04:51:38.879 --> 04:51:41.920
‘I [blank] going to [blank].’

04:51:41.920 --> 04:51:43.440
The verb is ‘talk’.

04:51:43.439 --> 04:51:45.759
And I want you to use the negative form.

04:51:47.039 --> 04:51:49.439
In this case, the subject is ‘I’.

04:51:49.439 --> 04:51:51.679
And so I use the ‘be’ verb – ‘am’.

04:51:52.959 --> 04:51:55.840
‘I am’ and then we need ‘not’.

04:51:56.799 --> 04:51:58.401
‘I am not going to’

04:52:00.799 --> 04:52:02.719
Then the base verb ‘talk’.

04:52:04.160 --> 04:52:06.639
‘Why [blank] you going to [blank]?’

04:52:07.199 --> 04:52:08.560
The verb here is ‘go’.

04:52:09.680 --> 04:52:15.440
In a question, especially a ‘WH’ question,
we start with the ‘WH’ word,

04:52:15.439 --> 04:52:16.718
and then the ‘be’ verb.

04:52:17.680 --> 04:52:21.039
‘are’ is the correct ‘be’ verb because
the subject is ‘you’.

04:52:21.920 --> 04:52:24.240
Then we have ‘going to’.

04:52:24.240 --> 04:52:27.199
And again, the base form of the verb.

04:52:27.840 --> 04:52:29.360
‘Why are you going to go?’

04:52:30.480 --> 04:52:33.519
Now try to find the mistake in the next sentence.

04:52:35.439 --> 04:52:37.839
‘You are going to studying at home.’

04:52:38.799 --> 04:52:40.080
Can you find the mistake?

04:52:41.359 --> 04:52:44.400
‘You are going to’ that's correct.

04:52:44.400 --> 04:52:46.798
But we need the base form of the verb.

04:52:48.000 --> 04:52:51.840
‘You are going to study at home.’

04:52:52.639 --> 04:52:55.360
‘You will be going to learn English.’

04:52:56.879 --> 04:52:58.320
‘You will be going’

04:52:59.600 --> 04:53:01.039
That sounds a little strange.

04:53:01.840 --> 04:53:04.401
Remember, we don't need the ‘will’ here.

04:53:04.400 --> 04:53:10.959
We're using ‘be going to’ and we need
to change the ‘be’ verb to match the subject.

04:53:12.080 --> 04:53:15.039
‘You are going to learn English’.

04:53:15.039 --> 04:53:20.320
Or remember, you can also say,
‘You will learn English.

04:53:20.320 --> 04:53:24.320
and finally
‘Is he going to do play soccer.’

04:53:25.119 --> 04:53:27.439
uh-oh
We have two verbs here.

04:53:28.000 --> 04:53:30.799
‘Is he going to’ - that's correct.

04:53:30.799 --> 04:53:33.279
But we have ‘do’ and ‘play’.

04:53:33.279 --> 04:53:38.638
We don't need both, so we say,
