04:54:29.439 --> 04:54:32.480
One usage of the future continuous tense

04:54:32.480 --> 04:54:36.718
is to talk about an ongoing action that will
happen in the future.

04:54:37.279 --> 04:54:40.080
We include when this action will be happening.

04:54:40.719 --> 04:54:44.561
We can use ‘will be’ or ‘be going to
be’.

04:54:44.561 --> 04:54:47.520
To do this, let's take a look at some examples.

04:54:48.480 --> 04:54:51.279
‘I will be taking the test soon.’

04:54:52.000 --> 04:54:56.240
So you can see here we have the subject and
then ‘will be’.

04:54:57.119 --> 04:54:59.840
After that, we include verb +ing.

04:55:00.719 --> 04:55:06.639
The word ‘soon’ at the end of this sentence
indicates when this action will be happening.

04:55:07.760 --> 04:55:11.840
‘I am going to be taking the test soon.’

04:55:11.840 --> 04:55:15.680
This sentence means the same thing as the
first sentence,

04:55:15.680 --> 04:55:19.360
but instead of ‘will be’, we used ‘be
going to be’.

04:55:20.080 --> 04:55:21.680
Here the subject is ‘I’.

04:55:22.320 --> 04:55:24.718
And therefore we have the ‘be’ verb ‘am’.

04:55:25.279 --> 04:55:29.679
‘I am going to be’
And then verb +ing.

04:55:30.400 --> 04:55:32.959
‘I am going to be taking the test soon.’

04:55:33.760 --> 04:55:36.401
I can also use the contraction and say.

04:55:36.400 --> 04:55:39.839
‘I'm going to be taking the test soon.’

04:55:40.400 --> 04:55:44.480
The next sentence says,
‘He will be sleeping by 10 p.m.’

04:55:45.439 --> 04:55:49.439
And the last sentence says,
‘They are going to be …’

04:55:49.439 --> 04:55:52.400
Here, because the subject is ‘they’, we
use ‘are’.

04:55:52.959 --> 04:55:56.879
‘They are going to be studying …’
There's the verb +ing

04:55:56.879 --> 04:55:58.639
‘… next October.’

04:55:59.600 --> 04:56:05.840
‘by 10 pm’ and ‘next October’ show
when these actions will be happening.

04:56:06.400 --> 04:56:07.920
Let's move on.

04:56:07.920 --> 04:56:11.600
The future continuous tense is also used to
show

04:56:11.600 --> 04:56:15.440
that a short action in the future is happening

04:56:15.439 --> 04:56:20.240
during or while a longer action is in progress
in the future,.

04:56:20.799 --> 04:56:25.279
We can use the word ‘when’
to show when the shorter action occurs.

04:56:25.920 --> 04:56:27.680
Take a look at the first example,

04:56:28.480 --> 04:56:31.119
‘I will be sleeping when they arrive.’

04:56:31.760 --> 04:56:33.920
Here we see two actions,

04:56:33.920 --> 04:56:36.959
‘I will be sleeping’ and ‘they arrive’.

04:56:38.080 --> 04:56:43.519
The part of the sentence that's in the future
continuous tense is the longer action

04:56:43.520 --> 04:56:45.520
that's in progress in the future.

04:56:46.160 --> 04:56:48.560
‘I will be sleeping.’

04:56:48.561 --> 04:56:52.081
Remember, ‘I will be’ and then verb +ing.

04:56:53.039 --> 04:56:56.480
This is the action that is ongoing in the
future.

04:56:57.279 --> 04:56:59.599
Then we see ‘when they arrive’.

04:57:00.240 --> 04:57:02.480
This is in the present tense.

04:57:02.480 --> 04:57:04.080
‘they arrive’

04:57:04.080 --> 04:57:09.840
This is the shorter action
that happens while this action is ongoing.

04:57:11.279 --> 04:57:14.560
‘We will be having dinner when the movie
starts.’

04:57:15.199 --> 04:57:17.840
This is very similar to the first sentence.

04:57:18.400 --> 04:57:20.480
‘We will be having dinner …’

04:57:20.480 --> 04:57:24.080
That's the ongoing action that will happen
in the future.

04:57:24.799 --> 04:57:28.959
And while this is happening,
the movie will start.

04:57:28.959 --> 04:57:31.680
But again, we use the present tense here.

04:57:31.680 --> 04:57:33.360
‘the movie starts’

04:57:33.359 --> 04:57:36.798
So we will be having dinner when the movie
starts.

04:57:38.160 --> 04:57:41.840
‘Tina is going to be working when you leave.’

04:57:41.840 --> 04:57:46.639
Remember, we can use ‘be going to be’
in this tense so,

04:57:47.359 --> 04:57:50.000
‘She is going to be working when you leave.’

04:57:50.561 --> 04:57:55.920
This shorter action will happen while this
ongoing action is in progress.

04:57:56.639 --> 04:58:00.719
And finally, ‘It will be raining when you
go shopping’.

04:58:01.279 --> 04:58:04.400
Again, this is the ongoing action.

04:58:04.400 --> 04:58:06.400
And this is the shorter action.

04:58:07.199 --> 04:58:08.480
Let's move on.

04:58:08.480 --> 04:58:12.878
Now, I'll talk about the negative form of
the future continuous tense.

04:58:13.439 --> 04:58:14.718
Here are some examples:

04:58:15.520 --> 04:58:18.241
‘He will not be reading before bed.’

04:58:19.039 --> 04:58:24.639
For the negative form, after the subject and
‘will’, we say ‘not be’.

04:58:24.639 --> 04:58:26.481
And then verb +ing.

04:58:27.359 --> 04:58:30.160
‘He will not be reading before bed.’

04:58:30.719 --> 04:58:32.160
He'll be doing something else.

04:58:33.279 --> 04:58:34.799
The next sentence says,

04:58:34.799 --> 04:58:38.160
‘My dad won't be cheering when the game
ends.’

04:58:38.799 --> 04:58:41.680
So this is very similar to the first sentence.

04:58:41.680 --> 04:58:43.760
We have the subject, ‘my dad,’

04:58:44.480 --> 04:58:48.000
and instead of ‘will not’ we use the contraction
‘won't’.

04:58:48.561 --> 04:58:52.000
Remember, ‘won't’ is a contraction for
‘will not’.

04:58:52.799 --> 04:58:57.440
‘My dad won't …’
and then we have ‘be’ verb +ing.

04:58:58.400 --> 04:59:01.439
‘My dad won't be cheering when the game
ends.’

04:59:02.480 --> 04:59:06.878
The next sentence says,
‘He is not going to be working tomorrow.’

04:59:07.680 --> 04:59:10.160
Here we have the ‘be going to be’.

04:59:10.959 --> 04:59:14.959
So ‘he’ is the subject and so we use the
‘be’ verb ‘is’.

04:59:15.920 --> 04:59:18.080
After the ‘be’ verb, we say ‘not’.

04:59:23.119 --> 04:59:24.617
He is not going to ‘be’ verb +ing.

04:59:24.617 --> 04:59:26.401
‘He is not going to be working tomorrow.’

04:59:27.199 --> 04:59:31.199
Remember, we can also use a contraction here
and say,

04:59:31.199 --> 04:59:34.560
‘He isn't going to be working tomorrow.’

04:59:34.561 --> 04:59:35.680
That's okay as well.

04:59:36.799 --> 04:59:39.760
‘We aren't going to be shopping on Sunday.’

04:59:40.561 --> 04:59:42.879
Here the subject is ‘we’.

04:59:42.879 --> 04:59:45.359
And so the ‘be’ verb to use is ‘are’.

04:59:46.320 --> 04:59:49.679
I use the contraction here ‘aren't’ for
‘are not’.

04:59:50.400 --> 04:59:55.759
‘We are not …’ or ‘We aren't going
to be shopping on Sunday.’

04:59:56.400 --> 04:59:57.279
Great job.

04:59:57.279 --> 04:59:58.560
Let's move on.

04:59:58.561 --> 05:00:04.161
Now let's talk about how to form basic questions
in the future continuous tense.

05:00:04.719 --> 05:00:07.039
Take a look at this first sentence.

05:00:07.039 --> 05:00:10.240
It says,
‘He will be traveling next month.’

05:00:10.959 --> 05:00:13.760
Now, to turn this into a question,

05:00:13.760 --> 05:00:18.000
all you have to do is change the order of
the first two words.

05:00:18.000 --> 05:00:20.879
So ‘He will’ becomes ‘Will he’.

05:00:21.760 --> 05:00:23.680
‘Will he be traveling next month?’

05:00:24.561 --> 05:00:27.840
You'll notice that the rest of the words don't
change.

05:00:28.400 --> 05:00:30.160
Only the first two words.

05:00:30.719 --> 05:00:34.080
So, ‘Will he be traveling next month?’

05:00:34.080 --> 05:00:37.279
To answer you can say,
‘Yes, he will.’

05:00:37.279 --> 05:00:38.879
or ‘No, he won't.’

05:00:39.920 --> 05:00:43.520
The next sentence says,
‘They are going to be living there.’

05:00:44.561 --> 05:00:50.481
Again to turn this into a question, simply
switch the order of the first two words.

05:00:51.199 --> 05:00:53.119
‘They are’ becomes ‘Are they’.

05:00:53.920 --> 05:00:55.920
‘Are they going to be living there?’

05:00:56.719 --> 05:01:00.080
To reply you can say,
‘Yes, they are.’

05:01:00.080 --> 05:01:01.840
or ‘No, they aren't.’

05:01:02.480 --> 05:01:05.679
Now, you'll notice in these two sentences,

05:01:05.680 --> 05:01:11.360
there is no exact point in time that shows
when this action will be happening in the

05:01:11.359 --> 05:01:12.320
future.

05:01:12.320 --> 05:01:16.240
There is no ‘next month’ or anything like
that.

05:01:16.240 --> 05:01:20.320
In that case, it simply means sometime in
the future.

05:01:20.320 --> 05:01:25.199
So, they are going to be living there sometime
in the future.

05:01:25.199 --> 05:01:26.240
That's what that means.

05:01:26.799 --> 05:01:28.080
Great job, everyone.

05:01:28.080 --> 05:01:29.279
Let's move on.

05:01:29.279 --> 05:01:34.959
Now, I'll go into how to form ‘WH’ questions
in the future continuous tense.

05:01:35.520 --> 05:01:36.799
Take a look at the board.

05:01:37.520 --> 05:01:42.879
First, you'll notice that all of these questions
begin with the ‘Wh’ words -

05:01:42.879 --> 05:01:46.080
‘Where,’ ‘What,’ ‘Who,’ and ‘When’.

05:01:46.879 --> 05:01:48.879
Let's take a look at the first question.

05:01:49.600 --> 05:01:51.680
‘Where will he be working?’

05:01:52.561 --> 05:01:56.799
When we use ‘will be’, we start with ‘Where’
and then ‘will’.

05:01:57.840 --> 05:02:02.000
After that, we have the subject + be and then
verb +ing.

05:02:03.039 --> 05:02:04.879
‘Where will he be working?’

05:02:05.760 --> 05:02:07.520
I can answer by saying,

05:02:07.520 --> 05:02:11.840
‘He will’ or ‘He'll be working at the
factory.’

05:02:12.480 --> 05:02:15.839
The next question says,
‘What will she be watching?’

05:02:16.719 --> 05:02:19.680
This is very similar to the first question.

05:02:19.680 --> 05:02:24.401
The only difference is that the subject is
now ‘she’ and the verb is different.

05:02:25.359 --> 05:02:26.798
‘What will she be watching?’

05:02:27.680 --> 05:02:33.280
I can say, ‘She'll be watching’ or ‘She
will be watching her favorite tv show’.

05:02:34.799 --> 05:02:36.561
‘Who will they be talking to?’

05:02:37.199 --> 05:02:39.760
Again, very similar.

05:02:39.760 --> 05:02:41.920
To answer,I can say,

05:02:41.920 --> 05:02:44.080
‘They will be talking to their mom.’

05:02:45.359 --> 05:02:48.160
The last question has ‘be going to be’.

05:02:48.959 --> 05:02:52.080
‘When are we …’ here the subject is
’we’.

05:02:52.080 --> 05:02:53.840
So we start with the ‘be verb’ – ‘are’.

05:02:54.639 --> 05:02:57.520
‘When are we going to be meeting Casey?’

05:02:58.320 --> 05:02:59.359
I can say,

05:02:59.359 --> 05:03:02.718
‘We are going to be meeting Casey
later tonight.’

05:03:03.600 --> 05:03:04.799
Good job, everybody.

05:03:04.799 --> 05:03:05.600
Let’s move on.

05:03:06.240 --> 05:03:09.840
Let's start a checkup for the future continuous
tense.

05:03:09.840 --> 05:03:12.080
Take a look at the first sentence.

05:03:12.080 --> 05:03:15.279
It says, ‘They _blank_ at school tomorrow.’

05:03:15.840 --> 05:03:20.160
I want you to use ‘will' and then the verb
‘study’, for this tense.

05:03:21.840 --> 05:03:24.639
Remember, in the future continuous
tense,

05:03:24.639 --> 05:03:29.680
no matter what the subject, we say ‘will
be’ and then verb +ing.

05:03:30.320 --> 05:03:35.840
So the correct answer for this sentence is
‘they will be studying’

05:03:37.439 --> 05:03:40.240
‘They will be studying at school tomorrow.’

05:03:41.039 --> 05:03:42.480
The next sentence says.

05:03:42.480 --> 05:03:45.439
‘Jesse _blank_ a TV show later.’

05:03:46.320 --> 05:03:50.480
Here, instead of ‘will’ try to use ‘be
going to be’.

05:03:52.561 --> 05:03:56.481
‘Jesse _blank_ watch a TV show later.’

05:03:56.480 --> 05:03:58.320
I want you to use the verb ‘watch’.

05:03:59.199 --> 05:04:03.359
So, Jessie is a ‘he’ or it can be a ‘she’.

05:04:03.359 --> 05:04:06.080
Sometimes the name is used for a boy or a
girl.

05:04:06.719 --> 05:04:09.119
Either way I need to use the ‘be’ verb
– ‘is’.

05:04:09.840 --> 05:04:14.160
‘Jesse is going to be’

05:04:15.920 --> 05:04:18.160
and then we need verb +ing.

05:04:19.600 --> 05:04:24.241
‘Jesse is going to be watching a TV show
later.’

05:04:25.359 --> 05:04:28.400
The next sentence, I want you to find the
mistake.

05:04:31.039 --> 05:04:34.400
‘We willn’t be studying at the library
today.’

05:04:36.480 --> 05:04:38.718
‘We will not …’

05:04:38.719 --> 05:04:41.199
What's the contraction for ‘will not’?

05:04:41.840 --> 05:04:44.481
Well it definitely isn't ‘willn’t’.

05:04:45.680 --> 05:04:48.080
The contraction is ‘won't’.

05:04:48.879 --> 05:04:52.080
‘We won't be studying at the library today.’

05:04:52.959 --> 05:04:57.600
And finally, ‘Sally and I will be meet our
friends soon.’

05:04:58.799 --> 05:05:02.799
Remember, we need ‘will be’ and then verb
+ing.

05:05:03.520 --> 05:05:05.280
So the correct answer is,

05:05:06.959 --> 05:05:10.080
‘Sally and I will be meeting our friends
soon.’

05:05:11.119 --> 05:05:12.240
Good job, everyone.

05:05:12.240 --> 05:05:14.000
Let's move on.

05:05:14.000 --> 05:05:19.039
Now, let's move on to the next checkup of
the future continuous tense.

05:05:19.039 --> 05:05:21.199
Take a look at the first sentence.

05:05:21.199 --> 05:05:25.359
It says, ‘He _blank_ at the door when the
movie ends.’

05:05:25.920 --> 05:05:29.119
I want you to use ‘will’ and the verb
‘wait’.

05:05:30.561 --> 05:05:35.920
Remember, for this tense, we need ‘will
be’ and then verb +ing,

05:05:36.639 --> 05:05:38.639
so the correct answer is,

05:05:38.639 --> 05:05:42.959
‘He will be waiting at the door when the
movie ends.’

05:05:44.160 --> 05:05:49.039
The next sentence says,
‘We are not …’ so this is a negative,

05:05:49.039 --> 05:05:51.760
‘_blank_ the play when he performs’.

05:05:52.400 --> 05:05:58.080
Here, instead of ‘will’, I want you to
use ‘be going to be’ and the verb ‘see’.

05:06:00.160 --> 05:06:03.039
We already have part of that phrase for you.

05:06:03.680 --> 05:06:06.799
‘We are …’, here's the ‘be’ verb,
‘not’

05:06:06.799 --> 05:06:08.320
so this is negative.

05:06:08.320 --> 05:06:12.080
And then we say ‘going to be’

05:06:13.279 --> 05:06:15.199
and then verb +ing.

05:06:17.199 --> 05:06:21.439
‘We are not going to be seeing the play
when he performs.’

05:06:22.400 --> 05:06:24.959
Now find the mistake in this sentence.

05:06:25.680 --> 05:06:30.000
‘They won't be stay at home when the delivery
