05:08:01.039 --> 05:08:06.000
The future perfect tense is used to express
an action in the future

05:08:06.000 --> 05:08:08.879
that will happen by a specific time in the
future.

05:08:09.520 --> 05:08:11.120
Let's look at some examples.

05:08:12.240 --> 05:08:13.920
The first sentence says,

05:08:13.920 --> 05:08:16.719
‘The snow will have stopped by April.’

05:08:17.680 --> 05:08:19.600
We start with the subject.

05:08:19.600 --> 05:08:21.280
In this case, ‘The snow’.

05:08:22.320 --> 05:08:27.599
Then, we follow with ‘will have’ and the
past participle of the verb.

05:08:28.160 --> 05:08:32.160
In this case, we used ‘stopped’ for the
verb ‘stop’.

05:08:33.199 --> 05:08:36.400
At the end of the sentence, you'll notice
‘by April’.

05:08:37.279 --> 05:08:43.840
‘by April’ shows the specific time in
the future when this action will have happened.

05:08:45.199 --> 05:08:46.799
The next sentence says,

05:08:46.799 --> 05:08:51.840
‘By the time he graduates, he will have
completed five years of study.’

05:08:52.879 --> 05:08:53.840
In this sentence,

05:08:54.400 --> 05:08:58.718
‘By the time he graduates’
or the specific time in the future.

05:08:58.719 --> 05:09:00.719
comes at the beginning of the sentence

05:09:01.279 --> 05:09:04.879
so ‘by’ plus ‘a time in the future’

05:09:04.879 --> 05:09:08.561
can come at the end
or it can come at the beginning.

05:09:09.279 --> 05:09:13.359
‘By the time he graduates, he will have
completed…’

05:09:14.000 --> 05:09:19.920
Again, you see ‘subject + will + have’
and the past participle of the verb.

05:09:19.920 --> 05:09:21.520
In this case, ‘completed’.

05:09:22.320 --> 05:09:27.679
‘By the time he graduates, he will have
completed five years of study.’

05:09:28.639 --> 05:09:30.241
The next sentence says,

05:09:30.240 --> 05:09:33.599
‘Her arm will have fully healed by the summer.’

05:09:34.400 --> 05:09:40.400
In this example, ‘by the summer’, the
future specific time, comes at the end.

05:09:41.359 --> 05:09:48.638
By this time in the future, her ‘arm’,
that's the subject, will have ‘healed’,

05:09:48.639 --> 05:09:50.000
the past participle.

05:09:50.561 --> 05:09:55.840
Here I put ‘fully’ just to show how much
it will have healed.

05:09:55.840 --> 05:09:58.160
I’m just adding an extra description.

05:09:59.199 --> 05:10:00.719
The last sentence says,

05:10:00.719 --> 05:10:05.600
‘By next month, …’ so here we see ‘by’
and ‘the time’ at the beginning of the

05:10:05.600 --> 05:10:06.080
sentence.

05:10:06.959 --> 05:10:09.039
‘you’, that's the subject.

05:10:09.039 --> 05:10:12.480
‘will have received’, there's the past
participle.

05:10:12.480 --> 05:10:13.359
‘your promotion.’

05:10:14.240 --> 05:10:19.039
Again, ‘By next month you will have received
your promotion.’

05:10:19.920 --> 05:10:20.719
Let's move on.

05:10:21.600 --> 05:10:26.080
Now, let's talk about the negative form of
the future perfect tense.

05:10:26.639 --> 05:10:28.080
Here are some examples.

05:10:28.719 --> 05:10:29.520
Let's take a look.

05:10:30.240 --> 05:10:31.840
The first sentence says,

05:10:31.840 --> 05:10:35.840
‘I will not have graduated from university
by July.’

05:10:36.879 --> 05:10:42.481
First, I want to point out that at the end,
I have the specific time in the future,

05:10:43.119 --> 05:10:44.000
‘byJuly’.

05:10:44.799 --> 05:10:51.119
Now for the negative form, what I do is say,
‘subject’ and ‘will not have’,

05:10:52.080 --> 05:10:55.039
then we put the past participle of the verb.

05:10:55.760 --> 05:11:00.799
‘I will not have graduated from university
by July.’

05:11:02.000 --> 05:11:03.760
The next sentence says,

05:11:03.760 --> 05:11:07.600
‘Ollie and Max will not have spoken ...’

05:11:07.600 --> 05:11:13.440
There it is again, ‘will not have’ and
then the past participle of speak ...

05:11:13.439 --> 05:11:14.759
which is ‘spoken’.

05:11:14.760 --> 05:11:18.000
‘… before the plane leaves.’

05:11:18.000 --> 05:11:24.080
Here, instead of the word ‘by’, we used
‘before’ to show a specific time in the

05:11:24.080 --> 05:11:24.959
future.

05:11:24.959 --> 05:11:26.160
That's okay as well.

05:11:27.279 --> 05:11:28.959
The next sentence says,

05:11:28.959 --> 05:11:32.000
‘You will not have eaten dinner by 6 p.m.’

05:11:32.879 --> 05:11:37.920
Here, again, we've used ‘by 6 p.m.’ to
show a time in the future.

05:11:38.561 --> 05:11:45.040
And again, you see ‘you will not have’
and then the past participle of eat which

05:11:45.039 --> 05:11:45.840
is ‘eaten’.

05:11:46.959 --> 05:11:50.799
The last sentence says,
‘By noon …’, there's the time again,

05:11:51.439 --> 05:11:54.878
‘I will not have taken off to Japan.’

05:11:55.840 --> 05:11:59.920
‘taken’ is the past participle of ‘take’.

05:11:59.920 --> 05:12:00.719
Let's move on.

05:12:01.279 --> 05:12:06.160
Now, let's move on to how to form questions
in the future perfect tense.

05:12:06.959 --> 05:12:08.561
The first sentence here says,

05:12:09.119 --> 05:12:12.000
‘You will have gone to work by 10 a.m.’

05:12:12.959 --> 05:12:15.840
To turn this into a question, all we have
to

05:12:15.840 --> 05:12:18.799
do is switch the order of the first two words.

05:12:19.760 --> 05:12:22.080
‘You will’ becomes ‘Will you’.

05:12:22.879 --> 05:12:28.320
You'll notice that the rest of the question
stays the same as the sentence.

05:12:28.320 --> 05:12:31.039
‘Will you have gone to work by 10 a.m.?’

05:12:31.920 --> 05:12:35.440
You can answer by saying,
‘Yes, I will have.’

05:12:35.439 --> 05:12:37.679
or ‘No, I will have not.’

05:12:38.799 --> 05:12:42.799
The next sentence says,
‘She will have woken up by noon.’

05:12:43.760 --> 05:12:48.481
Again, to turn this into a question just switch
the first two words.

05:12:49.039 --> 05:12:51.439
‘She will’ becomes ‘Will she’.

05:12:52.320 --> 05:12:54.400
‘Will she have woken up by noon?’

05:12:55.199 --> 05:12:58.560
Again, the rest of the sentence stays the
same.

05:12:59.760 --> 05:13:01.840
‘Will she have woken up by noon?’

05:13:02.879 --> 05:13:06.799
To reply, you can say,
‘Yes, she will have.’

05:13:06.799 --> 05:13:10.000
or ‘No, she will have not.’

05:13:10.000 --> 05:13:10.799
Let's move on.

05:13:11.840 --> 05:13:16.959
Now, I'll talk about how to form ‘WH’
questions in the future perfect tense.

05:13:17.680 --> 05:13:23.039
If you notice on the board, each of these
questions begins with the ‘WH’ word.

05:13:23.600 --> 05:13:26.879
‘Where’, ‘what’, ‘who’, and ‘when’.

05:13:28.080 --> 05:13:31.760
Then after each ‘WH’ word comes the word
‘will’.

05:13:32.480 --> 05:13:34.560
‘Where will’
‘What will’

05:13:34.561 --> 05:13:36.321
‘Who will’
and ‘When will’

05:13:36.959 --> 05:13:39.439
So let's take a look at the first question.

05:13:40.160 --> 05:13:43.840
‘Where will’…’ then you add ‘the
subject’.

05:13:43.840 --> 05:13:45.119
In this case, ‘you’.

05:13:46.000 --> 05:13:51.520
And then, ‘have’ and after that the past
participle of the verb.

05:13:51.520 --> 05:13:53.280
In this case, it's ‘traveled’.

05:13:54.000 --> 05:13:57.039
‘Where will you have traveled by December?’

05:13:57.680 --> 05:14:02.719
I can answer by saying,
‘I will have traveled to Germany and Denmark.’

05:14:02.719 --> 05:14:05.840
There are many possible answers here and this
is just an example.

05:14:07.119 --> 05:14:11.359
The next question says,
‘What will they have done …’

05:14:11.359 --> 05:14:13.759
‘done’ is the past participle of ‘do’.

05:14:13.760 --> 05:14:16.240
‘… by the end of the evening?’

05:14:16.959 --> 05:14:20.400
I can answer by saying,
‘They will have done their homework.’

05:14:21.680 --> 05:14:26.401
The next question says,
‘Who will she have interviewed by 5 p.m.?’

05:14:27.359 --> 05:14:34.240
Again, ‘who will’ + the subject ‘have’
and the past participle of the verb.

05:14:34.240 --> 05:14:36.638
I can answer this question by saying,

05:14:36.639 --> 05:14:39.760
‘She will have interviewed the teachers
by 5 p.m.’

05:14:40.799 --> 05:14:43.920
And finally, ‘When will they have started
to learn?’

05:14:44.959 --> 05:14:47.760
One way to answer this question is to say,

05:14:47.760 --> 05:14:50.639
‘They will have started to learn in January.’

05:14:51.439 --> 05:14:52.240
Let's move on.

05:14:53.199 --> 05:14:56.320
Let's start this checkup for the future perfect
tense.

05:14:56.879 --> 05:14:59.199
Take a look at the first sentence.

05:14:59.199 --> 05:15:03.199
It says,
‘We _blank_ that book by tomorrow.’

05:15:03.840 --> 05:15:06.000
The verb to use is ‘read’.

05:15:07.600 --> 05:15:11.760
Remember, in the future perfect tense, we
