05:17:47.279 --> 05:17:51.679
In this video, I will talk about the future
perfect continuous tense.

05:17:52.480 --> 05:17:56.160
This tense can be used to describe an ongoing
action

05:17:56.160 --> 05:18:01.439
or situation that will last for a specified
period of time in the future.

05:18:02.000 --> 05:18:04.240
There's a lot to learn, so keep watching.

05:18:08.240 --> 05:18:14.160
The future perfect continuous tense is used
to talk about an ongoing situation

05:18:14.160 --> 05:18:20.560
that will be in progress for a period of time
at a specific point in time in the future.

05:18:21.279 --> 05:18:23.119
Let's take a look at some examples.

05:18:23.840 --> 05:18:25.520
The first sentence says,

05:18:25.520 --> 05:18:30.081
‘She will have been living in Ireland for
10 years at that point.’

05:18:30.959 --> 05:18:34.639
So no matter what the subject, in this case
we have ‘she’,

05:18:35.279 --> 05:18:39.439
we follow with ‘will have been’ and then
‘verb +ing’.

05:18:40.000 --> 05:18:44.719
So, ‘She will have been living in Ireland
…’

05:18:44.719 --> 05:18:47.440
Then this sentence has the duration.

05:18:48.080 --> 05:18:52.400
What period of time will this last?
‘for 10 years’

05:18:53.039 --> 05:18:53.920
And when?

05:18:54.480 --> 05:18:57.519
Remember, we need a point in time in the future.

05:18:58.160 --> 05:19:03.039
In this case, we just use a general expression,
‘at that point’.

05:19:03.600 --> 05:19:06.080
Here, it's not specific and that's okay.

05:19:06.639 --> 05:19:09.680
We'll see some specific examples in the next
sentence.

05:19:10.719 --> 05:19:15.039
‘By midnight, he will have been sleeping
for four hours.’

05:19:15.840 --> 05:19:20.719
Here, the specific time in the future comes
at the beginning of the sentence.

05:19:21.279 --> 05:19:26.000
‘By midnight’
And, again, we see ‘will have been’ +

05:19:26.000 --> 05:19:26.879
verb 'ing'.

05:19:27.760 --> 05:19:31.440
‘By midnight, he will have been sleeping
for four hours.’.

05:19:31.439 --> 05:19:33.439
Here we have ‘for four hours’.

05:19:34.000 --> 05:19:39.199
This shows the duration or how long this action
will be in progress.

05:19:40.000 --> 05:19:44.799
So, again, ‘By midnight he will have been
sleeping for four hours.’

05:19:45.680 --> 05:19:48.401
The last sentence says, ‘In June …’

05:19:48.400 --> 05:19:54.320
Here, again, we have the specific time in
the future at the beginning of the sentence.

05:19:55.119 --> 05:19:58.320
‘In June, ‘we’ that's the subject.

05:19:58.320 --> 05:20:01.920
‘we'll have been studying …’
There's the ‘verb +ing’.

05:20:01.920 --> 05:20:04.959
‘… at this university for four years.’

05:20:05.520 --> 05:20:08.321
Here is the duration, ‘for four years’.

05:20:09.119 --> 05:20:09.760
Good job.

05:20:09.760 --> 05:20:10.639
And let's move on.

05:20:11.199 --> 05:20:16.320
Now, let's look at the negative form of the
future perfect continuous tense.

05:20:17.039 --> 05:20:24.080
In the affirmative form, we say ‘subject’
+ ‘will have been’ and then ‘verb +ing’.

05:20:24.080 --> 05:20:29.600
In the negative form, however, we say, ‘subject’
+ ‘will not have been’

05:20:29.600 --> 05:20:30.959
and then ‘verb +ing’.

05:20:31.680 --> 05:20:33.520
Let's take a look at some examples.

05:20:34.400 --> 05:20:35.920
The first sentence here says,

05:20:36.480 --> 05:20:41.119
‘At that point, I will not have been living
in Spain for 10 years.’

05:20:41.840 --> 05:20:42.799
And so you see it.

05:20:43.520 --> 05:20:44.879
‘I’ is the subject.

05:20:44.879 --> 05:20:49.279
‘… will not have been’
and then ‘verb +ing’.

05:20:49.840 --> 05:20:51.840
In this case, ‘living’.

05:20:52.400 --> 05:20:53.519
The next sentence says,

05:20:54.080 --> 05:20:57.920
‘He will not have been sleeping for four
hours by midnight.’

05:20:58.559 --> 05:21:04.080
Again, we see the ‘subject’ + ‘will
not have been’ and then ‘verb +ing’,

05:21:04.719 --> 05:21:06.321
‘sleeping’.

05:21:06.320 --> 05:21:08.080
The last sentence says,

05:21:08.080 --> 05:21:13.359
‘By then, we will not have been studying
at this university for three years.’

05:21:14.160 --> 05:21:20.558
Again, we see the ‘subject’ + ‘we will
not have been’ and then ‘verb +ing’

05:21:20.559 --> 05:21:21.760
here, ‘studying’.

05:21:22.480 --> 05:21:23.199
Let's move on.

05:21:24.000 --> 05:21:29.520
Now let's take a look at how to form questions
in the future perfect continuous tense.

05:21:30.320 --> 05:21:32.240
Here, the sentence says,

05:21:32.240 --> 05:21:36.240
‘Sean will have been playing soccer for
a year by December.’

05:21:36.959 --> 05:21:42.160
To turn this into a question, all we have
to do is switch the order of the first two

05:21:42.160 --> 05:21:43.039
words.

05:21:43.039 --> 05:21:46.959
So instead of ‘Sean will’, I can say ‘Will
Sean’.

05:21:47.680 --> 05:21:51.440
‘Will Sean have been playing soccer for
a year by December?’

05:21:52.080 --> 05:21:55.600
You'll notice that the rest of the sentence
stays the same.

05:21:56.480 --> 05:22:00.320
I can answer by saying,
‘Yes, he will have.’

05:22:00.320 --> 05:22:02.799
or ‘No, he will have not.’

05:22:03.680 --> 05:22:05.280
The next sentence says,

05:22:05.279 --> 05:22:09.119
‘They will have been working there for three
months by that time.’

05:22:10.000 --> 05:22:13.359
Again, I changed the order of the first two
words.

05:22:13.359 --> 05:22:17.920
To turn this into a question ‘They will’
becomes ‘Will they’.

05:22:18.799 --> 05:22:22.481
‘Will they have been working there for three
months by that time?’

05:22:23.359 --> 05:22:26.480
Again, the rest of the sentence stays the
same.

05:22:28.240 --> 05:22:31.920
I can answer by saying,
‘Yes, they will have.’

05:22:31.920 --> 05:22:34.400
or ‘No, they will have not.’

05:22:35.119 --> 05:22:36.400
Let's move on.

05:22:36.400 --> 05:22:42.160
Now let's take a look at how to form ‘WH”
questions in the future perfect continuous

